  {
    "title": "The best way to apologize (according to science)",
    "youtubeId": "q-ApAdEOm5s",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "TED-Ed",
    "theme": "learning",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.878,
        "end": 11.466,
        "text": "多年来，人们想出了一些 真正糟糕的道歉方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.924,
        "end": 15.678,
        "text": "从糟糕的虚伪道歉到不坦率的理由，"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.678,
        "end": 17.638,
        "text": "以及信口开河的承诺，"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.638,
        "end": 20.725,
        "text": "要做一个糟糕的道歉太容易了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.309,
        "end": 26.481,
        "text": "但是，研究人员发现， 好的道歉一般都有某些要素，"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.647,
        "end": 30.693,
        "text": "深思熟虑地考虑这些因素可以帮助你"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.693,
        "end": 33.112,
        "text": "在各种情况下做出赔罪道歉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.946,
        "end": 37.825,
        "text": "由于公开道歉有其独特的复杂性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.825,
        "end": 41.329,
        "text": "我们将重点关注一些 人与人之间的例子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.038,
        "end": 45.958,
        "text": "所以，想象一下：你的 新办公室的公共冰箱里"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.958,
        "end": 48.294,
        "text": "有免费的冰激凌三明治--"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.294,
        "end": 50.505,
        "text": "或者至少你是这么想的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.838,
        "end": 53.633,
        "text": "但是在星期五，当你帮助 你的同事特伦斯"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.633,
        "end": 56.177,
        "text": "为另一位同事举办生日派对时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.177,
        "end": 60.223,
        "text": "他发现他为庆祝活动买的 冰淇淋已经不见了一半。"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.015,
        "end": 63.726,
        "text": "虽然这显然是个令人尴尬的事件，"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.726,
        "end": 67.146,
        "text": "但是站出来道歉仍旧 是正确的做法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.522,
        "end": 71.025,
        "text": "理解并为自己的行为承担责任"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.025,
        "end": 75.113,
        "text": "是一些研究人员所说的“道歉的核心”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.78,
        "end": 79.992,
        "text": "但如果这让人感到困难和容易受到 指责也没关系——这本该如此！"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.243,
        "end": 84.247,
        "text": "道歉之所以有意义， 部分原因在于它代价高昂。"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.58,
        "end": 88.668,
        "text": "因此，虽然你可能想为你的 认为是偶然的行为辩护，"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.668,
        "end": 91.337,
        "text": "但重要的是要记住，一个好的道歉"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.337,
        "end": 93.798,
        "text": "并不是为了让你自己感觉更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.132,
        "end": 98.30199999999999,
        "text": "它是关于寻求理解被误解方的观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.30199999999999,
        "end": 101.013,
        "text": "并修复对你们关系的损害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.556,
        "end": 106.477,
        "text": "这意味着，对主动澄清你的 意图是有帮助的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.686,
        "end": 110.02199999999999,
        "text": "同时，你的错误是一个事故， 不应该免除你给予"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.02199999999999,
        "end": 112.56700000000001,
        "text": "一个真诚的道歉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.068,
        "end": 117.155,
        "text": "但如果你的错误不是意外呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.655,
        "end": 118.82300000000001,
        "text": "想想看："
      },
      {
        "start": 118.906,
        "end": 123.327,
        "text": "你答应你的朋友玛丽， 你会去看她的足球冠军赛。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.327,
        "end": 126.289,
        "text": "但是另一位朋友刚给你打电话， 要给你一张"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.289,
        "end": 128.916,
        "text": "你最喜欢的音乐家的 告别巡演的额外门票。"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.083,
        "end": 131.544,
        "text": "你知道，这是一个千载难逢的机会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.544,
        "end": 133.588,
        "text": "你不可能错过它。"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.088,
        "end": 137.508,
        "text": "而且如果你错过了比赛， 你估计玛丽是不会介意的——"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.508,
        "end": 139.927,
        "text": "她总是有很多粉丝支持她。"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.428,
        "end": 143.639,
        "text": "但是第二天，玛丽告诉你， 她真的很伤心，"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.639,
        "end": 145.6,
        "text": "当她没有在人群中看到你时。"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.975,
        "end": 150.897,
        "text": "你因为让她不高兴而感到过意不去， 并真诚地想要道歉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.98,
        "end": 153.357,
        "text": "但是，虽然你后悔伤害了玛丽，"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.357,
        "end": 156.94400000000002,
        "text": "你实际上并不确定自己 是否做出了错误的选择。"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.445,
        "end": 161.199,
        "text": "那你该如何避免 糟糕的虚伪道歉"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.365,
        "end": 163.91,
        "text": "“我很抱歉你有这种感觉”？"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.119,
        "end": 169.999,
        "text": "在这样的场合下，当你应该 努力理解对方的感受时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.999,
        "end": 173.628,
        "text": "你很容易把注意力集中在 对你的行为做出合理的解释上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.17000000000002,
        "end": 177.423,
        "text": "关心地问问玛丽你带给她的感受，"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.423,
        "end": 179.383,
        "text": "以便更好地解释你的过错。"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.88400000000001,
        "end": 183.262,
        "text": "在这种情况下，玛丽 可能会说她很失望，"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.262,
        "end": 184.43,
        "text": "你违背了你的诺言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.43,
        "end": 187.225,
        "text": "她真的指望你的支持。"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.434,
        "end": 192.063,
        "text": "这种清楚的表白可以帮助你 认识到自己的错误，"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.063,
        "end": 195.566,
        "text": "并让她真诚地容忍你的 行为造成的伤害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.067,
        "end": 200.071,
        "text": "然后你可以就她的感受表达道歉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.071,
        "end": 203.61599999999999,
        "text": "或许是承认你违背承诺是错误的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.61599999999999,
        "end": 205.701,
        "text": "你很抱歉你没有在她身边。"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.536,
        "end": 210.539,
        "text": "明智地承认错误的行为表明， 你清楚地知道"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.539,
        "end": 212.458,
        "text": "你是如何把事情搞砸的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.458,
        "end": 216.879,
        "text": "这会让玛丽相信 以后你会有不同的表现。"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.255,
        "end": 221.09199999999998,
        "text": "而这一点总是能帮助你 确切地表明你将如何改变，"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.09199999999998,
        "end": 224.762,
        "text": "以及你会做点什么来修复 因你的过错造成地伤害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.012,
        "end": 227.93200000000002,
        "text": "研究人员称之为“采用补救手段”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.349,
        "end": 232.478,
        "text": "它通常被认为是道歉中 最关键的部分之一。"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.937,
        "end": 236.023,
        "text": "在某些情况下，这些姿态是坦率的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.023,
        "end": 238.81799999999998,
        "text": "比如赔还你吃掉的冰淇淋。"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.11,
        "end": 242.029,
        "text": "然而，对于不太明显的过错，"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.029,
        "end": 244.115,
        "text": "这可能需要更具象征性的表达，"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.407,
        "end": 248.035,
        "text": "比如表达你对受委屈 的人的爱和问候。"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.369,
        "end": 251.998,
        "text": "一种常见的补救手段是口头承诺"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.998,
        "end": 254.208,
        "text": "不再犯同样的错误，"
      },
      {
        "start": 254.208,
        "end": 259.588,
        "text": "但承诺做得再好也只有在你真的做得 更好的情况下才能让人信服。"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.798,
        "end": 264.176,
        "text": "站在受害者的角度， 承担责任，"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.176,
        "end": 266.721,
        "text": "提出具体的补偿建议，"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.721,
        "end": 269.473,
        "text": "都只是一个好的道歉中的几个要素。"
      },
      {
        "start": 269.724,
        "end": 274.395,
        "text": "但请记住，道歉并不是为了获得 宽恕和继续你们的关系；"
      },
      {
        "start": 274.687,
        "end": 278.524,
        "text": "而是为了表达悔意和承担责任。"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.983,
        "end": 282.236,
        "text": "而最好的道歉只是通往"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.236,
        "end": 284.322,
        "text": "和解之路的第一步。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How can you change someone's mind?",
    "youtubeId": "58jHhNzUHm4",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Hugo Mercier",
    "theme": "learning",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.833,
        "end": 9.03,
        "text": "三个人正在参加晚宴。"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.03,
        "end": 12.054,
        "text": "已婚的保罗正盯着琳达看。"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.054,
        "end": 16.88,
        "text": "与此同时，琳达却盯着未婚的约翰。"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.48,
        "end": 20.964,
        "text": "有没有谁已经结婚 却盯着未婚的人看呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.964,
        "end": 22.904,
        "text": "花点时间想一想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.564,
        "end": 28.395,
        "text": "大多数人回答说 没有足够的信息能够判断。"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.395,
        "end": 30.53,
        "text": "但他们都错了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.53,
        "end": 34.77,
        "text": "琳达必然是已婚或是未婚， 没有其他可能。"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.77,
        "end": 40.064,
        "text": "因此不管在哪一种情况下， 都存在已婚的某人在看着未婚的某人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.064,
        "end": 43.322,
        "text": "当给出这个解释时， 大多数人都改变了他们的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.322,
        "end": 44.799,
        "text": "并且接受了这个正确答案，"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.799,
        "end": 48.1,
        "text": "即便他们当时对自己 第一次的回答十分自信。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.1,
        "end": 49.906,
        "text": "现在我们再来看看另一个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.906,
        "end": 53.781,
        "text": "2005年，Brendan Nyhan 和 Jason Reifler 进行了一项研究"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.781,
        "end": 58.831,
        "text": "调查了美国人对于伊拉克战争是否正义的态度。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.831,
        "end": 61.938,
        "text": "研究员们展示给参与者一篇新的文章，"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.938,
        "end": 65.574,
        "text": "内容是说没有找到大规模杀伤性武器。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.574,
        "end": 70.669,
        "text": "但是许多参与人员不仅继续相信 大规模杀伤性武器存在，"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.669,
        "end": 74.528,
        "text": "并且甚至更坚定自己原来的想法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.528,
        "end": 80.136,
        "text": "为何观点有时能改变人们的想法 而有时却起到反作用？"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.136,
        "end": 85.03399999999999,
        "text": "观点若要更具说服力 需要建立在充分了解受众的基础上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.03399999999999,
        "end": 87.615,
        "text": "考虑到他们相信什么，"
      },
      {
        "start": 87.615,
        "end": 88.845,
        "text": "他们信任谁，"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.845,
        "end": 91.185,
        "text": "以及他们在乎什么。"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.185,
        "end": 95.61500000000001,
        "text": "对于晚宴问题这样的趣味智力题 数理逻辑的观点之所以行得通"
      },
      {
        "start": 95.61500000000001,
        "end": 98.215,
        "text": "在于即便人们得到不同的结论，"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.215,
        "end": 101.543,
        "text": "他们是基于相同的价值观 进行思考。"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.543,
        "end": 107.562,
        "text": "1931年，一位年轻而默默无闻的数学家 Kurt Gödel 证明了"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.562,
        "end": 111.407,
        "text": "一个逻辑上完备的数学体系是不可能的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.407,
        "end": 114.684,
        "text": "即便经过杰出数学家 Bertrand Russell"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.684,
        "end": 117.38300000000001,
        "text": "和 David Hilbert 数十年的努力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.38300000000001,
        "end": 118.47200000000001,
        "text": "这项证明仍然被接受了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.47200000000001,
        "end": 123.452,
        "text": "因为它建立在该领域已经承认的公理上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.452,
        "end": 126.774,
        "text": "当然，许多不同意见包含有不同的看法"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.774,
        "end": 129.398,
        "text": "这些不同意见无法 通过逻辑简单调和。"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.398,
        "end": 132.142,
        "text": "当这些想法涉及到外部信息，"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.142,
        "end": 137.091,
        "text": "问题经常变成人们信任 哪些信息来源和权威人士。"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.091,
        "end": 138.473,
        "text": "一项研究让人们"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.473,
        "end": 142.911,
        "text": "对气候变化领域的数据做出预测。"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.911,
        "end": 144.937,
        "text": "参加者需要回答一些问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.937,
        "end": 149.589,
        "text": "例如1995年至2006年这12年间，"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.589,
        "end": 154.001,
        "text": "有多少年是1850年来最炎热的年份。"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.001,
        "end": 155.721,
        "text": "在参与者提供答案之后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.721,
        "end": 160.204,
        "text": "他们会看到来自 气候变化政府小组的数据，"
      },
      {
        "start": 160.204,
        "end": 164.11,
        "text": "数据会先显示出答案是11年。"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.11,
        "end": 168.862,
        "text": "当看到这些来自值得信任的官方数据，"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.862,
        "end": 173.499,
        "text": "人们更倾向于接受全球变暖的事实。"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.499,
        "end": 176.416,
        "text": "最后，对于完全不能靠数据或证据"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.416,
        "end": 178.778,
        "text": "解决的不同意见来说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 178.778,
        "end": 180.776,
        "text": "给出令人信服的观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.776,
        "end": 183.996,
        "text": "可能在于抓住受众所在乎的东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.996,
        "end": 187.717,
        "text": "例如，研究人员进行了一些研究，"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.717,
        "end": 190.774,
        "text": "他们询问了不同政治背景的人们"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.774,
        "end": 192.85,
        "text": "让他们对自己的价值观进行排位。"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.85,
        "end": 194.505,
        "text": "平均来看，在这项研究中"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.505,
        "end": 201.638,
        "text": "自由党人士认为 人人平等比忠诚更重要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.638,
        "end": 205.376,
        "text": "在之后的研究中， 研究者们试图用各种观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.376,
        "end": 208.999,
        "text": "说服自由派人士支持军费开支。"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.999,
        "end": 210.773,
        "text": "基于平等的观点——"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.773,
        "end": 213.428,
        "text": "例如军队为那些来自贫困家庭的人们"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.428,
        "end": 215.723,
        "text": "提供就业以及教育——"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.723,
        "end": 219.20499999999998,
        "text": "比基于忠诚的观点更有说服力"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.20499999999998,
        "end": 222.173,
        "text": "比如军队使国家团结。"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.453,
        "end": 224.889,
        "text": "以下三种要素——"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.889,
        "end": 227.562,
        "text": "信仰，可信的信息来源以及价值观——"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.562,
        "end": 231.61599999999999,
        "text": "可能看上去是取得共识的简单公式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.61599999999999,
        "end": 234.51,
        "text": "但问题在于 我们在一开始仍倾向于"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.51,
        "end": 240.023,
        "text": "以自己的信仰、可信消息来源和价值观 为基础构想观点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.023,
        "end": 241.676,
        "text": "即便我们不这样做，"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.676,
        "end": 244.719,
        "text": "正确识别出意见不同的人们看重什么"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.719,
        "end": 247.273,
        "text": "也是一件很困难的事情。"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.273,
        "end": 250.25900000000001,
        "text": "最好的办法是和他们聊天。"
      },
      {
        "start": 250.25900000000001,
        "end": 252.017,
        "text": "在讨论的过程中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.017,
        "end": 255.014,
        "text": "你会接触到反面观点和驳斥。"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.014,
        "end": 259.323,
        "text": "这些可以帮助你 完善自己的观点和推理，"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.323,
        "end": 263.563,
        "text": "甚至有时候，最终改变你想法的人 可能就是你自己。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to use rhetoric to get what you want",
    "youtubeId": "3klMM9BkW5o",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Camille A. Langston",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.072,
        "end": 11.132,
        "text": "如何用自己的语言得出结果？"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.132,
        "end": 15.653,
        "text": "早在2000多年前，亚里士多德就通过关于修辞的专门论述"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.653,
        "end": 18.152,
        "text": "开始回答这个问题了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.152,
        "end": 19.993,
        "text": "修辞学，根据亚里士多德的观点，"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.993,
        "end": 24.013,
        "text": "是用不同方式说服他人的艺术。"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.013,
        "end": 27.143,
        "text": "如今，修辞学被广泛运用于各种交流场合。"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.143,
        "end": 29.582,
        "text": "然而，亚里士多德当时专注于演说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.582,
        "end": 33.623,
        "text": "而且，他阐述了三大说服性演讲类别。"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.623,
        "end": 35.713,
        "text": "辩论型，或者叫做审议型修辞手法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.713,
        "end": 38.753,
        "text": "根据既成事实与判断得出结论，"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.753,
        "end": 41.314,
        "text": "类似于置身于犯罪现场的警探。"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.314,
        "end": 43.714,
        "text": "修饰型，或者叫做抒发型修辞手法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.714,
        "end": 46.134,
        "text": "通常是重申某种现实状况，"
      },
      {
        "start": 46.134,
        "end": 48.384,
        "text": "比如说，婚礼致辞。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.384,
        "end": 52.064,
        "text": "然而，审议修辞是达到目和促成改变的重要手段，"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.064,
        "end": 54.253,
        "text": "或叫做象征型修辞。"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.253,
        "end": 56.164,
        "text": "审议修辞既不关注过去，也不着眼现状，"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.164,
        "end": 59.164,
        "text": "而是专注于未来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.164,
        "end": 61.254,
        "text": "政治家们运用这样的审议修辞"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.254,
        "end": 65.085,
        "text": "来辩论一个新法案会带来的影响。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.085,
        "end": 68.106,
        "text": "就像罗纳德·里根警告美国老年人医疗保险制度"
      },
      {
        "start": 68.106,
        "end": 71.274,
        "text": "有可能给我们的下一代传达一种社会主义思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.274,
        "end": 76.135,
        "text": "并且会代代相传下去曾经那个人人自由的美国社会。"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.135,
        "end": 79.465,
        "text": "同时该修辞也是活跃分子寻求改变的方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.465,
        "end": 81.995,
        "text": "就像马丁·路德·金关于梦想的演讲，"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.995,
        "end": 84.195,
        "text": "他的子孙后代终有一天会生活在一个国度"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.195,
        "end": 86.905,
        "text": "那里，人们不会因为他们的肤色受到歧视，"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.905,
        "end": 89.255,
        "text": "每个人的品行才是判断的标准。"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.255,
        "end": 93.11699999999999,
        "text": "以上这两个案例中，演讲者都为听众描绘了可能的未来"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.11699999999999,
        "end": 97.064,
        "text": "并且希望得到听众们的帮助，以此避免、或实现那样的结果。"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.064,
        "end": 99.435,
        "text": "但是除了描绘未来场景，还能如何打造有效的"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.435,
        "end": 101.465,
        "text": "审议修辞型的演讲？"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.465,
        "end": 104.923,
        "text": "根据亚里士多德的观点，有三种方式："
      },
      {
        "start": 104.923,
        "end": 106.066,
        "text": "认知、"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.066,
        "end": 107.025,
        "text": "标识、"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.025,
        "end": 108.477,
        "text": "和同情心。"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.477,
        "end": 112.14500000000001,
        "text": "通过和听众的认知达成一致，演讲者可以建立起可信度。"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.14500000000001,
        "end": 116.856,
        "text": "温斯顿·丘吉尔1942年美国国会的演说，开场白："
      },
      {
        "start": 116.856,
        "end": 121.244,
        "text": "“太平洋两岸的潮汐一直和谐地流动在我的生命中，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.244,
        "end": 125.615,
        "text": "“一直对抗着特权和垄断，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.615,
        "end": 129.776,
        "text": "从而突显出他一直致力于民主推广的美德。"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.776,
        "end": 132.686,
        "text": "早在古代，为诗人阿基亚斯辩护的演讲中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.686,
        "end": 136.367,
        "text": "罗马执政官西塞罗通过自有的实践智慧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.367,
        "end": 138.657,
        "text": "以及身为政治家的专业素质："
      },
      {
        "start": 138.657,
        "end": 141.538,
        "text": "“无论是我自身的文学教育，"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.538,
        "end": 143.828,
        "text": "“还是专注的训练体系中我承认”"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.828,
        "end": 147.407,
        "text": "“我生活中没有任何一个部分遭到了厌恶。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.407,
        "end": 150.736,
        "text": "最终，你可以通过证明事不关己，"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.736,
        "end": 153.86599999999999,
        "text": "或者你是无偿奉献的精神来说服听众。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.86599999999999,
        "end": 157.247,
        "text": "理性修辞是通过逻辑和推理来表达观点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.247,
        "end": 161.138,
        "text": "该方式可以通过类比，"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.138,
        "end": 162.177,
        "text": "举例，"
      },
      {
        "start": 162.177,
        "end": 165.177,
        "text": "以及科研引用和数据来进行论述。"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.177,
        "end": 167.728,
        "text": "但是这不仅仅是事实和数字。"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.728,
        "end": 171.148,
        "text": "更重要的是演讲本身的结构和内容。"
      },
      {
        "start": 171.148,
        "end": 174.90699999999998,
        "text": "关键在于用事实去说服听众。"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.90699999999998,
        "end": 178.577,
        "text": "就像索茹尔内·特鲁斯关于女权的观点一样："
      },
      {
        "start": 178.577,
        "end": 182.597,
        "text": "“我拥有比得上任何一位男性的力量，并且可以做同样的工作。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.597,
        "end": 186.788,
        "text": "“我耕地，收割，去壳，伐木，割草”"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.788,
        "end": 189.939,
        "text": "\"有任何一个男人可以做得更多吗？\""
      },
      {
        "start": 189.939,
        "end": 194.472,
        "text": "不幸的是，演讲者也会利用错误的信息来愚弄听众"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.472,
        "end": 196.939,
        "text": "让听众信以为真。"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.939,
        "end": 199.589,
        "text": "比如已经被辟谣，但是依然广泛被相信的谣言："
      },
      {
        "start": 199.589,
        "end": 202.247,
        "text": "“疫苗会导致自闭症”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.247,
        "end": 205.602,
        "text": "最后一种方式，同情，是引起情感上共鸣的技巧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.602,
        "end": 209.639,
        "text": "在现今大众传播媒体社会，这也是最有效的方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.639,
        "end": 212.208,
        "text": "同情本身并没有好坏对错之分，"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.208,
        "end": 215.309,
        "text": "但是有可能变得不理性、难预测"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.309,
        "end": 217.868,
        "text": "就像怜悯可以轻易团结民众一样，"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.868,
        "end": 220.25900000000001,
        "text": "也可以教唆战争。"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.25900000000001,
        "end": 221.703,
        "text": "大部分的广告，"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.703,
        "end": 225.609,
        "text": "从美容产品保证可以减轻人们对自己身体的不安全感"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.609,
        "end": 227.91899999999998,
        "text": "到可以让人们感觉力量倍增的汽车，"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.91899999999998,
        "end": 230.41899999999998,
        "text": "都依赖于情感上的共鸣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.41899999999998,
        "end": 234.728,
        "text": "亚里士多德的修辞学说现今也依然是个强有力的工具，"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.728,
        "end": 236.799,
        "text": "但是选择使用哪一种方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.799,
        "end": 239.372,
        "text": "取决于熟悉讲演的受众以及目的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.372,
        "end": 241.629,
        "text": "并且也和时间地点息息相关。"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.629,
        "end": 244.369,
        "text": "同时，作为听众时"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.369,
        "end": 248.49,
        "text": "能够辨别这些说服技巧的能力也是一样的重要！"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to communicate clearly",
    "youtubeId": "btWlBHE0pe4",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "TED-Ed",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.128,
        "end": 12.05,
        "text": "人类历史长河中，你是独一无二的"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.258,
        "end": 15.303,
        "text": "你的经历是你的，独属于你的"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.47,
        "end": 21.184,
        "text": "它们让你学到了很值得分享的东西"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.267,
        "end": 23.728,
        "text": "通过这个视频我们将要学习如何分享它们"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.811,
        "end": 27.648,
        "text": "当你有了灵感， 找到了一个你愿意分享的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.732,
        "end": 30.401,
        "text": "你就可以开始准备演讲了"
      },
      {
        "start": 31.944,
        "end": 35.114,
        "text": "演讲的目的是传达有意义的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.323,
        "end": 37.617,
        "text": "但很多演讲并没有达到这个目的"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.992,
        "end": 40.078,
        "text": "这种情况的主要原因是"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.119,
        "end": 45.124,
        "text": "演讲者没有把演讲作为一个整体来计划"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.458,
        "end": 49.837,
        "text": "他们可能逐词逐句地做了计划，"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.879,
        "end": 53.174,
        "text": "但没有考虑过内容和内容之间是如何连接起来"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.216,
        "end": 55.593,
        "text": "传达有意义的信息的"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.511,
        "end": 61.766,
        "text": "人们常用一个词分析戏剧、电影和小说这类作品"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.766,
        "end": 63.559,
        "text": "这个词也适用于分析演讲"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.81,
        "end": 66.354,
        "text": "它就是贯穿线，也叫主线"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.687,
        "end": 69.482,
        "text": "演讲的主线就是中心思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.524,
        "end": 72.36,
        "text": "将演讲者所呈现的一切联系在一起的中心思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.568,
        "end": 75.196,
        "text": "每个演讲都应该有一条主线"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.571,
        "end": 78.699,
        "text": "这不代表一次只能讲一个话题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.699,
        "end": 83.57900000000001,
        "text": "或者只能讲一个故事，或者只能朝一个方向发展"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.70400000000001,
        "end": 85.748,
        "text": "这只代表演讲中所有的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.748,
        "end": 89.21000000000001,
        "text": "应该相互关联，围绕中心思想展开。"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.669,
        "end": 92.505,
        "text": "下面举一个无主线的演讲的例子："
      },
      {
        "start": 92.922,
        "end": 97.38499999999999,
        "text": "“我想和大家分享我最近去开普敦的经历，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.426,
        "end": 100.555,
        "text": "以及一些旅途中的所见所闻。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.22200000000001,
        "end": 105.852,
        "text": "接下来是一个开头就挑明主线的演讲："
      },
      {
        "start": 106.519,
        "end": 110.648,
        "text": "“最近的开普敦之行中， 我学会了如何跟陌生人打交道，"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.648,
        "end": 113.60900000000001,
        "text": "何时可以还有何时绝对不该信任他们。"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.60900000000001,
        "end": 117.572,
        "text": "我将分享发生在我身上的两个故事”"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.197,
        "end": 122.201,
        "text": "没有主线的版本可能适合你与家人分享，"
      },
      {
        "start": 122.201,
        "end": 126.956,
        "text": "但是对于大众而言，有主线的版本更有吸引力"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.623,
        "end": 130.626,
        "text": "下面是一些受欢迎的TED演讲的主线："
      },
      {
        "start": 131.294,
        "end": 134.255,
        "text": "“拥有更多的选择不会使我们更幸福。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.714,
        "end": 138.718,
        "text": "“脆弱的一面是是值得珍惜的， 不需要隐藏的。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.635,
        "end": 144.932,
        "text": "“请让我们开展一场安静的革命， 重新为性格内向的人构造世界”"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.266,
        "end": 150.47899999999998,
        "text": "“18 分钟的宇宙史向我们展示了 从混沌到井井有条的全过程”"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.022,
        "end": 154.859,
        "text": "“糟糕的城市旗帜中藏着令人惊喜的设计秘密”"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.44299999999998,
        "end": 158.446,
        "text": "“前往南极的惊险滑雪旅行"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.446,
        "end": 160.74,
        "text": "改变了我的人生意义。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.949,
        "end": 165.62,
        "text": "还记得刚开始我们将演讲分享比作"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.661,
        "end": 168.07999999999998,
        "text": "演讲者和听众共同的旅程吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.372,
        "end": 169.874,
        "text": "如果说一次演讲是一段旅程，"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.874,
        "end": 173.586,
        "text": "那么主线就是这趟旅程走的道路"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.836,
        "end": 179.258,
        "text": "顺着主线这条路可以确保 旅程中没有不可飞跃的鸿沟"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.71699999999998,
        "end": 180.927,
        "text": "演讲临近尾声时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.927,
        "end": 185.598,
        "text": "演讲者和听众才能一起到达称心如意的目的地"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.557,
        "end": 188.935,
        "text": "那么你应该怎么找出你的主线呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.268,
        "end": 194.482,
        "text": "挑选一个你在规定时间内能讲清楚的点"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.815,
        "end": 199.904,
        "text": "其次要确保你在演讲提到的所有内容 都能落到你的中心思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 199.904,
        "end": 205.493,
        "text": "在有限的时间内 完成精彩的演讲是一项艰巨的任务"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.743,
        "end": 208.746,
        "text": "但是借助正确的方法，我们可以解决这个难题"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.121,
        "end": 213.417,
        "text": "大家容易犯的错是 将你认为所有要点都包括在内"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.501,
        "end": 215.54399999999998,
        "text": "但为了尽可能简短地阐述那些要点"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.586,
        "end": 218.673,
        "text": "却忽略了细节或事例"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.048,
        "end": 224.929,
        "text": "你可先创建一个表单， 里面简短地概括每个话题的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.929,
        "end": 228.55700000000002,
        "text": "如果可以，你要构思一条主线将它们串联起来"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.724,
        "end": 233.02,
        "text": "但一条主线通常无法连接起太多的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.145,
        "end": 237.566,
        "text": "如果你在没有深入探讨你所提及的话题"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.692,
        "end": 240.236,
        "text": "那么你的讲话不会给听众留下任何深刻的印象"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.403,
        "end": 242.071,
        "text": "总结成一个简单的式子："
      },
      {
        "start": 242.154,
        "end": 245.408,
        "text": "观点繁多等于讲得不清楚"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.492,
        "end": 248.869,
        "text": "要让演讲变得有意义的话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.869,
        "end": 252.415,
        "text": "你最少需要做到两件事"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.623,
        "end": 256.502,
        "text": "首先，你要说明为什么你谈及的内容很重要"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.919,
        "end": 259.255,
        "text": "你想回答的问题是什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.338,
        "end": 261.549,
        "text": "你想解决的问题是什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.674,
        "end": 264.635,
        "text": "你想分享什么样的经历？"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.177,
        "end": 271.934,
        "text": "其次，你要用故事、例子 和真实的数据支撑你的观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 272.39300000000003,
        "end": 277.315,
        "text": "只有这样对你来说很重要的想法 才能在别人的脑海中建立起来"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.399,
        "end": 280.818,
        "text": "一场真正精彩的演讲，"
      },
      {
        "start": 280.86,
        "end": 284.155,
        "text": "你可能需要减少你想讲的话题数量，"
      },
      {
        "start": 284.196,
        "end": 288.784,
        "text": "把注意力放在连贯的主线上"
      },
      {
        "start": 288.868,
        "end": 291.996,
        "text": "全面且完整地展开你的演讲"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.538,
        "end": 297.668,
        "text": "以上就是在有限时间内进行精彩演讲的有效方法"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.002,
        "end": 301.63,
        "text": "你能提到的点可能比没有主线时少，"
      },
      {
        "start": 301.714,
        "end": 305.426,
        "text": "但是你演讲中提及的观点会产生更大的影响。"
      },
      {
        "start": 305.676,
        "end": 307.72,
        "text": "有舍才有得"
      },
      {
        "start": 309.055,
        "end": 311.223,
        "text": "选择一条主线将帮助你在演讲中做取舍"
      },
      {
        "start": 311.265,
        "end": 315.102,
        "text": "哪些话题可以展开讲讲，哪些可以省略"
      },
      {
        "start": 315.269,
        "end": 319.648,
        "text": "它将帮助你筛掉 与你的中心思想无关的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 319.94,
        "end": 322.36,
        "text": "如果你在确定主线时遇到困难，"
      },
      {
        "start": 322.36,
        "end": 327.907,
        "text": "一个实用的技巧是 尽量在 15 个字以内把主线讲清楚"
      },
      {
        "start": 328.157,
        "end": 332.536,
        "text": "你想给听众心里种下什么种子？"
      },
      {
        "start": 332.828,
        "end": 335.456,
        "text": "你想让听众中从你的演讲中收获些什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 336.248,
        "end": 340.378,
        "text": "在构思主线时，你可以从以下几个问题入手："
      },
      {
        "start": 340.836,
        "end": 343.297,
        "text": "这个话题对我来说有特殊意义吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 343.422,
        "end": 345.508,
        "text": "它能吸引听众吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 345.966,
        "end": 349.178,
        "text": "它能为观众提供了看待事物的新角度吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 349.261,
        "end": 352.348,
        "text": "我的演讲是一份礼物吗？ 它会引发观众的思考吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 352.556,
        "end": 356.06,
        "text": "这些信息是否新颖？ 或者某些方面很意想不到？"
      },
      {
        "start": 356.394,
        "end": 362.316,
        "text": "我能在规定时间内解释清楚这个话题 并附上必要的案例吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 362.691,
        "end": 366.57,
        "text": "我足够了解这个主题吗， 还是说我需要再研究研究？"
      },
      {
        "start": 366.695,
        "end": 369.156,
        "text": "这个话题与我的经历相关吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 369.448,
        "end": 373.369,
        "text": "能概括我演讲的 15 个字是什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 373.494,
        "end": 377.415,
        "text": "这 15 个字能勾起听众对我的兴趣吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 378.457,
        "end": 381.043,
        "text": "阿比盖尔·特内鲍姆，一位演讲培训师"
      },
      {
        "start": 381.043,
        "end": 383.796,
        "text": "建议我们先找人听一下你的主线"
      },
      {
        "start": 384.13,
        "end": 387.216,
        "text": "大声地讲出你想在演讲中包含的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 387.425,
        "end": 389.677,
        "text": "有助于你分析哪些部分是你能讲清楚的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 389.885,
        "end": 392.221,
        "text": "哪些部分你需要再下功夫，"
      },
      {
        "start": 392.221,
        "end": 397.89300000000003,
        "text": "以及为了让你的中心思想更有冲击力 哪些部分应该被删掉"
      },
      {
        "start": 398.602,
        "end": 400.146,
        "text": "当你有了主线之后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 400.146,
        "end": 402.481,
        "text": "你就可以计划更详细的内容了"
      },
      {
        "start": 402.69,
        "end": 406.652,
        "text": "无论时间限制是两分钟，十八分钟，还是一小时"
      },
      {
        "start": 406.777,
        "end": 412.116,
        "text": "请记住：只讲你在有限时间内能深度讨论的内容"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Three anti-social skills to improve your writing",
    "youtubeId": "flthk8SNiiE",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Nadia Kalman",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 17.263,
        "end": 19.08,
        "text": "对话使故事变得生动有趣"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.08,
        "end": 21.513,
        "text": "推动着情节发展"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.513,
        "end": 26.38,
        "text": "罗密欧：啊，难道你不打算满足我吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.38,
        "end": 30.603,
        "text": "朱丽叶：今晚如何才能满足你？"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.603,
        "end": 36.93,
        "text": "罗密欧：用你忠诚的爱情誓言来交换我的誓言。"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.93,
        "end": 40.997,
        "text": "如果没有对话：（蛐蛐声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.997,
        "end": 44.58,
        "text": "那么怎样写出对故事有利的对话呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.58,
        "end": 47.13,
        "text": "常规的三大社交技巧："
      },
      {
        "start": 47.13,
        "end": 51.913,
        "text": "交朋友，化解冲突，表现得彬彬有礼"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.913,
        "end": 54.414,
        "text": "但是我们今天不讨论这些"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.414,
        "end": 59.132,
        "text": "我们今天要讨论的是——“反社交技巧”"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.132,
        "end": 63.031,
        "text": "如果你是个作家，应该已经具备某些类似技巧"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.031,
        "end": 65.38,
        "text": "第一个技巧是偷听"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.38,
        "end": 70.282,
        "text": "如果你在乘车时听到了有趣的对话，应该把它们都记下来"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.282,
        "end": 74.48,
        "text": "虽然在小说里你写的不是真实人物"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.48,
        "end": 76.263,
        "text": "而是虚构的角色"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.263,
        "end": 79.98,
        "text": "但有时偷听到的对话能为你带来灵感"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.98,
        "end": 82.764,
        "text": "“我没做”，一个人辩解着"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.764,
        "end": 85.481,
        "text": "“我看见你做了”，另一个人反驳"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.481,
        "end": 88.314,
        "text": "这样的对话会是谁在说呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.314,
        "end": 93.76400000000001,
        "text": "也许是班里的两个孩子，小男孩以为小女孩推了他"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.76400000000001,
        "end": 96.963,
        "text": "也许是一对夫妻，妻子是吸血鬼"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.963,
        "end": 101.213,
        "text": "她看到丈夫与一个僵尸调情"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.213,
        "end": 103.249,
        "text": "还有更多可能性"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.249,
        "end": 105.74600000000001,
        "text": "比如是儿子和母亲间的对话"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.74600000000001,
        "end": 110.99600000000001,
        "text": "他们是素食主义者，但妈妈看到儿子偷吃了汉堡"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.99600000000001,
        "end": 113.664,
        "text": "如果你确定好了角色"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.664,
        "end": 115.98400000000001,
        "text": "就可以采用第二个反社会技巧"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.98400000000001,
        "end": 118.348,
        "text": "把他们当成真人"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.348,
        "end": 121.847,
        "text": "他们长什么样？来自哪里？喜欢什么样的音乐？"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.847,
        "end": 123.514,
        "text": "在角色身上多花点心思"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.514,
        "end": 126.613,
        "text": "你乘车时可以想象，他们坐在车上时会做什么"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.613,
        "end": 128.697,
        "text": "他们是在打电话？听音乐？"
      },
      {
        "start": 128.697,
        "end": 130.83,
        "text": "画画？还是打瞌睡？"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.83,
        "end": 133.982,
        "text": "人的性格背景决定了他的语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.982,
        "end": 136.803,
        "text": "年长者和年轻者说的话是不同的"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.803,
        "end": 140.663,
        "text": "南方人和北方人说的话也不一样"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.663,
        "end": 145.046,
        "text": "只要了解人物性格背景，就知道他们会说什么"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.046,
        "end": 148.865,
        "text": "接着，到了使用第三个技巧的时候"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.865,
        "end": 149.98,
        "text": "自言自语"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.98,
        "end": 153.312,
        "text": "念出角色的台词之后，你就会发现不妥之处"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.312,
        "end": 155.48,
        "text": "然后对台词进行修改"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.48,
        "end": 159.131,
        "text": "大多数人讲话都很随意"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.131,
        "end": 161.832,
        "text": "用词和缩略语都很简单"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.832,
        "end": 168.03199999999998,
        "text": "因此，“别想骗我”比“不要想对我撒谎”听上去自然"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.03199999999998,
        "end": 170.23,
        "text": "人物对话还应该保持简短"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.23,
        "end": 172.231,
        "text": "人们讲话时句子都短小精炼"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.231,
        "end": 174.364,
        "text": "而非长篇大论"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.364,
        "end": 176.213,
        "text": "记得多用对话的形式"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.213,
        "end": 180.13,
        "text": "此外，再反问自己：这句话真的需要副词吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.13,
        "end": 184.913,
        "text": "举个例子，“要钱还要命”，她威胁地说"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.913,
        "end": 188.831,
        "text": "此处，“威胁地”就显多余，可以省略"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.831,
        "end": 193.347,
        "text": "但如果语言和动作不搭调，副词有助于读者的理解"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.347,
        "end": 197.38,
        "text": "比如，“要钱还要命”，她深情地说"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.38,
        "end": 199.68,
        "text": "我来总结一下"
      },
      {
        "start": 199.68,
        "end": 203.498,
        "text": "第一，偷听；第二，把角色当成真人"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.498,
        "end": 207.98,
        "text": "第三，自言自语，并把台词写下来"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.98,
        "end": 210.698,
        "text": "现在，你已经掌握了必备的技巧"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.698,
        "end": 214.813,
        "text": "这是虚构的对话，也叫做“如何听到脑内的声音”"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "4 things all great listeners know",
    "youtubeId": "i3ku5nx4tMU",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "TED-Ed",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.086,
        "end": 9.922,
        "text": "察觉到别人在走神是容易的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 10.381,
        "end": 14.886,
        "text": "但真正优秀的倾听是难以具象化的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.72,
        "end": 22.268,
        "text": "行为科学家发现，认真聆听是"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.351,
        "end": 23.77,
        "text": "最有助于改善关系， 形成我们的世界观，"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.77,
        "end": 28.608,
        "text": "甚至是改变他人想法的做法之一。"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.983,
        "end": 32.737,
        "text": "那么，我们怎样才能 成为更好的倾听者呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.28,
        "end": 38.701,
        "text": "在面对面的交谈中，倾听的本质是"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.743,
        "end": 42.58,
        "text": "专注于对方的言谈， 让他们感到被人理解。"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.247,
        "end": 47.376,
        "text": "虽然没有关于 高质量聆听的公认定义，"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.46,
        "end": 52.09,
        "text": "但这通常意味着 全神投入、表露同情"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.09,
        "end": 55.343,
        "text": "和对谈话者的积极看法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.593,
        "end": 58.221,
        "text": "单单面部表情是不够的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.221,
        "end": 63.267,
        "text": "研究表明，隔一段时间 微笑、点点头作用不大。"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.434,
        "end": 67.23,
        "text": "但倾听本身具有些许表演成分，"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.23,
        "end": 69.982,
        "text": "因为表现出你在听十分必要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.441,
        "end": 73.986,
        "text": "除了实时关注 发言人的言谈之外，"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.07,
        "end": 77.615,
        "text": "优秀的倾听者还会 通过提问与肢体语言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 77.615,
        "end": 82.036,
        "text": "体现自己的同理心 以及想要理解发言的欲望。"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.995,
        "end": 85.289,
        "text": "起初，这也许会让人觉得别扭，"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.289,
        "end": 89.08500000000001,
        "text": "而最为有效的方法取决于 你与谈话者的关系。"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.33500000000001,
        "end": 94.173,
        "text": "但伴随着时间和练习， 你会习惯这类基础行为。"
      },
      {
        "start": 95.59100000000001,
        "end": 98.761,
        "text": "假设一位好朋友想告诉你"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.761,
        "end": 100.555,
        "text": "其与伴侣之间的矛盾。"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.763,
        "end": 103.47399999999999,
        "text": "在谈话开始前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.47399999999999,
        "end": 106.185,
        "text": "去掉环境里的任何干扰因素。"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.269,
        "end": 111.899,
        "text": "关掉电视、摘掉耳机， 把手机拿走——拿远点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.9,
        "end": 116.195,
        "text": "一项研究显示，手机处于可见的位置"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.195,
        "end": 120.575,
        "text": "会让参与者感觉谈话 缺少了些亲密感与满足感。"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.993,
        "end": 123.911,
        "text": "谈话一旦开始，"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.911,
        "end": 128.583,
        "text": "最重要以及自然的行为"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.041,
        "end": 130.668,
        "text": "是尽量不要打断对方。"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.294,
        "end": 133.963,
        "text": "这并不意味你得一声不吭。"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.963,
        "end": 137.091,
        "text": "但插话应该在自然停顿时进行，"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.091,
        "end": 138.926,
        "text": "问些开放性的， 有助于对方的问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.051,
        "end": 141.804,
        "text": "而不只是出于自身兴趣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.096,
        "end": 146.767,
        "text": "例如“之后发生了什么？” “这使你感受如何？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.767,
        "end": 149.562,
        "text": "体现你跟着故事线走， 并同时帮助对方"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.562,
        "end": 153.399,
        "text": "更深刻地去思索。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.399,
        "end": 156.736,
        "text": "另一个表现你理解的方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.736,
        "end": 159.78,
        "text": "是简述你听到的信息 并询问是否有遗漏。"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.40699999999998,
        "end": 165.494,
        "text": "这样的小结告诉对方 你真的是在努力理解他们，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.703,
        "end": 168.247,
        "text": "而不是干等着轮到你讲话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.70600000000002,
        "end": 172.877,
        "text": "说到这点，虽然 好的交谈需要双方互动，"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.04399999999998,
        "end": 176.297,
        "text": "在对方讲话时考虑自己接下来的回答"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.297,
        "end": 179.258,
        "text": "是漏掉讲话内容的常见原因。"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.675,
        "end": 182.637,
        "text": "请尽可能保持注意力集中， 如果走神了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.637,
        "end": 185.848,
        "text": "不要不好意思让对方 重复你错过的那点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.015,
        "end": 187.558,
        "text": "这也许会挺难堪，"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.558,
        "end": 191.187,
        "text": "但请对方澄清其实体现出了"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.187,
        "end": 192.855,
        "text": "你在努力理解。"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.439,
        "end": 196.692,
        "text": "还有，不要害怕沉默。"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.984,
        "end": 200.112,
        "text": "寻求些时间来完善 你的回应是正常的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.112,
        "end": 204.992,
        "text": "而暂停一下来思考也能 让对方回顾自身的讲话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.41,
        "end": 211.499,
        "text": "这些改变也许看起来微不足道， 但共同作用下会产生巨变。"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.499,
        "end": 215.253,
        "text": "而当人们的声音被听到， 他们会从人际关系中"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.253,
        "end": 218.381,
        "text": "获得更多满足感、信任和亲近感。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.673,
        "end": 223.761,
        "text": "在职场，受人倾听的 员工更少会过载，"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.761,
        "end": 226.973,
        "text": "并会对细听他们说话的经理 印象更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.64,
        "end": 231.31,
        "text": "不幸的是，虽然倾听些许人挺容易，"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.31,
        "end": 234.855,
        "text": "但如果你与讲话者 存在分歧或讨厌他，"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.855,
        "end": 237.984,
        "text": "就很难保持注意力集中。"
      },
      {
        "start": 238.609,
        "end": 242.321,
        "text": "在此类情况下，保持开放心态"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.321,
        "end": 243.739,
        "text": "最有成效。"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.49,
        "end": 248.953,
        "text": "心理抗拒理论表明， 强迫别人改变意见，"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.953,
        "end": 253.541,
        "text": "只会让他们更加坚定自己的观点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.833,
        "end": 258.796,
        "text": "最近研究表明，高质量的倾听行为"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.796,
        "end": 262.508,
        "text": "能通过塑造一个非主观、 使人放松的环境，"
      },
      {
        "start": 262.508,
        "end": 265.136,
        "text": "形成开放的氛围。"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.053,
        "end": 271.142,
        "text": "当然了，真正的开放式聆听 不是为了改变他人的想法；"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.225,
        "end": 274.02,
        "text": "善于倾听并不等于接受、妥协。"
      },
      {
        "start": 274.02,
        "end": 277.315,
        "text": "谈话也不是必须愉快地收尾。"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.024,
        "end": 279.942,
        "text": "但即使存在看法差异，"
      },
      {
        "start": 280.234,
        "end": 285.448,
        "text": "被人听见也足以推动更深的交流。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How miscommunication happens (and how to avoid it)",
    "youtubeId": "gCfzeONu3Mo",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Katherine Hampsten",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.631,
        "end": 9.863,
        "text": "你有没有遇到过这样的情况， 当你跟一个朋友聊起自己的困难，"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.863,
        "end": 14.54,
        "text": "你发现他好像无法明白 这事为什么对你这么重要？"
      },
      {
        "start": 14.54,
        "end": 18.783,
        "text": "当你表达自己的想法给一群人， 结果却发现没人能明白？"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.783,
        "end": 20.482,
        "text": "或者跟别人辩论，"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.482,
        "end": 22.64,
        "text": "对方突然指责起你来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.64,
        "end": 26.347,
        "text": "说你根本没有在听他们在说什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.347,
        "end": 27.95,
        "text": "这是怎么回事呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.95,
        "end": 30.017,
        "text": "答案是交流不畅，"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.017,
        "end": 31.49,
        "text": "而且不管是哪种形式（的交流不畅），"
      },
      {
        "start": 31.49,
        "end": 33.23,
        "text": "我们都遇到过。"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.23,
        "end": 34.578,
        "text": "它会让人糊涂，"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.578,
        "end": 35.682,
        "text": "产生仇恨，"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.682,
        "end": 36.874,
        "text": "引起误会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.874,
        "end": 41.573,
        "text": "甚至使一个价值数百万的 探测器在火星坠毁。"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.573,
        "end": 44.823,
        "text": "其实，即便人们当面聊天，"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.823,
        "end": 46.308,
        "text": "在同一个房间，"
      },
      {
        "start": 46.308,
        "end": 48.074,
        "text": "说同一种语言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.074,
        "end": 51.489,
        "text": "人类的交流 依然是极为复杂的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.489,
        "end": 54.637,
        "text": "好在，当我们交流时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.637,
        "end": 56.406,
        "text": "对当下情况的基本理解"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.406,
        "end": 59.275,
        "text": "可以帮我们避免交流不畅。"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.275,
        "end": 64.228,
        "text": "数十年来，科学家们不断探索 “当我们交流时，到底发生了什么？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.228,
        "end": 66.935,
        "text": "有一种解释是“传递模式”出问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.935,
        "end": 71.766,
        "text": "它视这种交流模式是一种 将讯息只做单向的传递而已。"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.766,
        "end": 75.622,
        "text": "这就好比，A 向 B 扔了一个球， 然后走掉了"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.622,
        "end": 76.753,
        "text": "但是，"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.753,
        "end": 80.68,
        "text": "这个简易的模式 并不能用来解释复杂的交流。"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.68,
        "end": 82.67099999999999,
        "text": "另一种解释是“交换模式”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.67099999999999,
        "end": 86.675,
        "text": "它承认交流中的附加障碍。"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.675,
        "end": 88.425,
        "text": "这个模式更准确地形容，"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.425,
        "end": 92.27199999999999,
        "text": "就好比把人与人的交流 比喻成一场接球游戏。"
      },
      {
        "start": 92.27199999999999,
        "end": 96.0,
        "text": "当我们在交流信息时， 我们会收到对方的反馈。"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.0,
        "end": 99.674,
        "text": "通过这样的信息交换， 双方共同建立语义。"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.674,
        "end": 103.307,
        "text": "但是这样的交换 也会有复杂性产生。"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.307,
        "end": 105.273,
        "text": "它不像星际迷航"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.273,
        "end": 107.393,
        "text": "裡面的演员可以心灵感应，"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.393,
        "end": 109.523,
        "text": "可以完全准确地传递想法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 109.523,
        "end": 110.167,
        "text": "相反，"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.167,
        "end": 115.695,
        "text": "人类只能通过主观视角 来发送和接收信息。"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.695,
        "end": 119.688,
        "text": "在交流中，A按照 她自己的理解去表达信息，"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.688,
        "end": 121.719,
        "text": "而B"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.719,
        "end": 124.521,
        "text": "则会用自己的方式 去理解该信息。"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.521,
        "end": 129.928,
        "text": "所以，我们的“感知过滤器” 一直在改变语言的含义。"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.928,
        "end": 131.57,
        "text": "还记得刚刚的接球游戏吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.57,
        "end": 133.722,
        "text": "让我们把球想像成 一块软软的黏土。"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.722,
        "end": 135.529,
        "text": "当每个人接到它时"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.529,
        "end": 138.356,
        "text": "会受很多因素的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.356,
        "end": 140.71,
        "text": "每个人会把它捏成 符合自己独特知觉的形状。"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.71,
        "end": 145.056,
        "text": "这些影响因素包括 阅历，年龄，种族，性别，"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.056,
        "end": 148.695,
        "text": "民族，宗教，或家庭背景。"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.695,
        "end": 149.858,
        "text": "与此同时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.858,
        "end": 153.236,
        "text": "人们会根据自己与对方的关系"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.236,
        "end": 156.108,
        "text": "以及自己对语言的独特解释"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.108,
        "end": 161.75900000000001,
        "text": "来理解对方说的话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.75900000000001,
        "end": 164.562,
        "text": "人们有时也会 被其他事物分心，"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.562,
        "end": 165.719,
        "text": "比如堵车，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.719,
        "end": 167.47,
        "text": "肚子在叫了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.47,
        "end": 169.649,
        "text": "甚至情绪也会 干扰人们对事物的理解。"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.649,
        "end": 172.508,
        "text": "而且， 当谈话的参与人数增加，"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.508,
        "end": 174.508,
        "text": "每个人都带着主观性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.508,
        "end": 178.601,
        "text": "交流的复杂程度 就会飙升。"
      },
      {
        "start": 178.601,
        "end": 182.937,
        "text": "当黏土块在人们之间"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.937,
        "end": 186.033,
        "text": "不断传递，重塑，变形，"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.033,
        "end": 191.284,
        "text": "难怪我们的讯息有时会变成 一堆交流不畅的烂泥巴。"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.284,
        "end": 193.535,
        "text": "但幸运的是， 一些练习能帮助我们"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.535,
        "end": 198.456,
        "text": "掌控日常互动 从而达到顺畅交流。"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.456,
        "end": 199.586,
        "text": "练习一："
      },
      {
        "start": 199.586,
        "end": 204.041,
        "text": "首先你要意识到，被动聆听 和主动聆听是有区别的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 204.041,
        "end": 208.374,
        "text": "要积极去感受 他人言语和非言语信息，"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.374,
        "end": 212.389,
        "text": "并通过调整你的表达 来促使对方更好地理解你。"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.389,
        "end": 213.286,
        "text": "练习二："
      },
      {
        "start": 213.286,
        "end": 217.317,
        "text": "聆听时要用到你的 眼，耳，甚至内脏。"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.317,
        "end": 220.276,
        "text": "记住，交流并不仅限于 文字交流。"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.276,
        "end": 221.434,
        "text": "练习三："
      },
      {
        "start": 221.434,
        "end": 225.036,
        "text": "理解他人和试图被他人理解 都要慢慢来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.036,
        "end": 227.131,
        "text": "如果急于表达自己的看法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.131,
        "end": 230.227,
        "text": "就容易忘记 交流其实是双向的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.227,
        "end": 232.96,
        "text": "要善于接受对方可能说的话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.96,
        "end": 234.613,
        "text": "最后，练习四："
      },
      {
        "start": 234.613,
        "end": 237.849,
        "text": "要意识到自己的“感知过滤器”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.849,
        "end": 239.402,
        "text": "你的阅历，"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.402,
        "end": 241.967,
        "text": "包括文化，社群和家庭环境，"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.967,
        "end": 244.451,
        "text": "都会影响你如何看待这个世界。"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.451,
        "end": 247.968,
        "text": "你要说：“我是这样 看这个问题的，你呢？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.968,
        "end": 251.385,
        "text": "不要以为你的主观看法 都是客观真理。"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.385,
        "end": 254.177,
        "text": "这个练习可以 帮你改进与他人的谈话"
      },
      {
        "start": 254.177,
        "end": 256.966,
        "text": "从而达成互相理解。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "The art of the metaphor",
    "youtubeId": "A0edKgL9EgM",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Jane Hirshfield",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 14.955,
        "end": 18.088,
        "text": "我们说话时，有时候会直接说"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.088,
        "end": 20.822,
        "text": "“我要去商店，五分钟就回来。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.822,
        "end": 22.403,
        "text": "有时，我们会换一种方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.403,
        "end": 24.521,
        "text": "让人想象一个场景"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.521,
        "end": 27.205,
        "text": "我们会说“真是倾盆大雨啊”(直译：下猫下狗)"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.205,
        "end": 30.136,
        "text": "或“我在等另一只鞋扔下来。” (提心吊胆地等待最后结果)"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.136,
        "end": 32.386,
        "text": "隐喻就是通过描述别的东西"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.386,
        "end": 34.554,
        "text": "来谈论一个事物"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.554,
        "end": 37.387,
        "text": "听起来像是绕圈子，但实际上不是"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.387,
        "end": 41.104,
        "text": "最初，我们通过看、听、尝来了解事物"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.104,
        "end": 45.154,
        "text": "哲学家威廉·詹姆斯 把新生儿的世界描述为："
      },
      {
        "start": 45.154,
        "end": 48.288,
        "text": "“嗡嗡作响的盛开的困惑”"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.288,
        "end": 53.82,
        "text": "抽象概念同最初的蜜蜂和花相比十分苍白"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.82,
        "end": 56.872,
        "text": "隐喻同想象和感觉相联系"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.872,
        "end": 61.039,
        "text": "隐喻像辣椒点燃了嘴巴和思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.039,
        "end": 62.538,
        "text": "它们还十分精确"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.538,
        "end": 65.721,
        "text": "我们不会停下来思考猫狗大小的雨滴"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.721,
        "end": 68.904,
        "text": "提心吊胆地等待最后结果"
      },
      {
        "start": 68.904,
        "end": 71.22,
        "text": "自己明确知道狗一定很小——"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.22,
        "end": 73.536,
        "text": "可卡犬、腊肠"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.536,
        "end": 75.853,
        "text": "一定不会是拉布拉多"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.853,
        "end": 79.456,
        "text": "或者纽芬兰犬，大概是小猎犬那么大"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.456,
        "end": 82.827,
        "text": "比喻并不分真假"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.827,
        "end": 86.19800000000001,
        "text": "比喻是艺术不是科学"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.19800000000001,
        "end": 89.571,
        "text": "但仍能分出对错"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.571,
        "end": 92.588,
        "text": "不好的隐喻让你困惑"
      },
      {
        "start": 92.588,
        "end": 95.67099999999999,
        "text": "你知道“觉得自己像一个方形轮“是什么意思"
      },
      {
        "start": 95.67099999999999,
        "end": 98.888,
        "text": "但不会明白“像蓝鲸一样累”"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.888,
        "end": 100.904,
        "text": "隐喻有一个悖论"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.904,
        "end": 103.92099999999999,
        "text": "他们总是用一些不真实的例子"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.92099999999999,
        "end": 106.438,
        "text": "如果你说：“屋里有头大象。” (显而易见而又被忽略的事实)"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.438,
        "end": 110.654,
        "text": "实际当然没有，看看桌上的花生就知道了"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.654,
        "end": 115.72,
        "text": "隐喻从你的皮肤下直接连接逻辑思维"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.72,
        "end": 117.956,
        "text": "另外，我们习惯了形象思维"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.956,
        "end": 120.687,
        "text": "每天晚上都梦到不可能发生的事"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.687,
        "end": 123.97,
        "text": "当我们醒来时，这种思维模式仍然存在"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.97,
        "end": 125.588,
        "text": "我们离开梦境"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.588,
        "end": 129.304,
        "text": "一键进入现实生活"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.304,
        "end": 132.672,
        "text": "有些比喻里有“像”“同”这样的字"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.672,
        "end": 135.372,
        "text": "“像蜂蜜一样甜”“同树一样健壮”"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.372,
        "end": 137.087,
        "text": "这些是明喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.087,
        "end": 140.804,
        "text": "明喻运用了比较"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.804,
        "end": 143.588,
        "text": "明喻让你思考"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.588,
        "end": 146.622,
        "text": "隐喻让你直接感受事物"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.622,
        "end": 148.739,
        "text": "拿莎士比亚最著名的比喻来举例："
      },
      {
        "start": 148.739,
        "end": 150.856,
        "text": "“世界是一个舞台。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.856,
        "end": 152.973,
        "text": "“世界像一个舞台。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.973,
        "end": 155.893,
        "text": "就没那么有力量了 还很无趣"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.893,
        "end": 158.254,
        "text": "动词中也存在隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.254,
        "end": 161.704,
        "text": "艾米莉·狄金森的诗以 “我看不到路，天空已被缝合”开头"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.704,
        "end": 165.154,
        "text": "我们马上就能明白"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.154,
        "end": 168.606,
        "text": "天空变成一块织物是什么感觉"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.606,
        "end": 170.638,
        "text": "隐喻也可以用在形容词上"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.654,
        "end": 174.574,
        "text": "“静水流深”用来指表面不声不响的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.574,
        "end": 176.699,
        "text": "却蕴藏着大的智慧"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.699,
        "end": 180.541,
        "text": "像水流一样，深度和平静都十分重要"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.541,
        "end": 184.657,
        "text": "诗歌是最容易出现好隐喻的地方"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.657,
        "end": 189.606,
        "text": "以18世纪日本诗人小林一茶的俳句为例"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.606,
        "end": 192.756,
        "text": "“树枝顺流而下，蟋蟀在上面歌唱”"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.756,
        "end": 195.906,
        "text": "发现隐喻的的第一种方法就是"
      },
      {
        "start": 195.906,
        "end": 199.058,
        "text": "通过世界本身的眼睛看世界"
      },
      {
        "start": 199.058,
        "end": 203.323,
        "text": "树枝在河中央顺流而下，一只昆虫在上面歌唱"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.323,
        "end": 206.923,
        "text": "即使你看到，部分的你认出画面描绘了"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.923,
        "end": 212.523,
        "text": "生活在由变化和时间构成的世界上是什么感觉"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.523,
        "end": 216.49099999999999,
        "text": "人终有一死，蟋蟀也一样"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.49099999999999,
        "end": 221.524,
        "text": "即便如此，我们依旧活着，歌唱"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.524,
        "end": 225.74,
        "text": "有时，诗歌里有一个隐喻并把它扩展"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.74,
        "end": 229.174,
        "text": "用不同的方法描绘一个构思"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.174,
        "end": 232.785,
        "text": "这是兰斯顿·休斯最著名的诗 《母亲致儿子》的开头"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.785,
        "end": 236.39600000000002,
        "text": "“噢，儿子，我来告诉你："
      },
      {
        "start": 236.39600000000002,
        "end": 240.007,
        "text": "我的人生没有水晶般的阶梯。"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.007,
        "end": 242.875,
        "text": "那上面钉着钉子，有碎片，"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.875,
        "end": 246.724,
        "text": "木板也是裂开的，地面没铺地毯——— 光秃秃的。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.724,
        "end": 249.724,
        "text": "兰斯顿·休斯将艰难的生活同"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.724,
        "end": 253.506,
        "text": "不得已居住的年久失修的房子相比"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.506,
        "end": 256.24,
        "text": "这些碎片和钉子十分真实"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.24,
        "end": 259.041,
        "text": "它们会划伤你的脚掌和内心"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.041,
        "end": 261.606,
        "text": "但母亲是在描述自己的生活"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.606,
        "end": 264.567,
        "text": "而不是房子"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.567,
        "end": 267.528,
        "text": "饥饿，寒冷令人疲惫的工作"
      },
      {
        "start": 267.528,
        "end": 270.49,
        "text": "以及贫穷也在碎片之中"
      },
      {
        "start": 270.49,
        "end": 273.606,
        "text": "隐喻并不总是同人类生活和情感相关"
      },
      {
        "start": 273.606,
        "end": 276.871,
        "text": "芝加哥诗人卡尔·桑德堡曾写道："
      },
      {
        "start": 276.871,
        "end": 280.181,
        "text": "“雾来了，轻轻地，踏着小猫的脚步。"
      },
      {
        "start": 280.181,
        "end": 282.811,
        "text": "静静地，它坐下观看，观看城市和港口"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.811,
        "end": 285.44100000000003,
        "text": "然后再重新上路。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 285.44100000000003,
        "end": 287.774,
        "text": "这里的比喻十分简单"
      },
      {
        "start": 287.774,
        "end": 290.61,
        "text": "雾被形容成小猫"
      },
      {
        "start": 290.61,
        "end": 292.507,
        "text": "好的隐喻不是猜谜"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.507,
        "end": 294.807,
        "text": "不用来传达隐藏的含义"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.807,
        "end": 299.008,
        "text": "而是让你从不同角度感受了解事物"
      },
      {
        "start": 299.008,
        "end": 301.157,
        "text": "听过这首诗的人都不会忘"
      },
      {
        "start": 301.157,
        "end": 305.257,
        "text": "你看见大雾，附近伴随着一只小灰猫"
      },
      {
        "start": 305.257,
        "end": 308.975,
        "text": "隐喻让词语超越它们本来的意思"
      },
      {
        "start": 308.975,
        "end": 311.423,
        "text": "它们是门上的把手"
      },
      {
        "start": 311.423,
        "end": 314.286,
        "text": "门则是我们可以了解、想象的"
      },
      {
        "start": 314.286,
        "end": 316.141,
        "text": "每扇门通向新的房子"
      },
      {
        "start": 316.141,
        "end": 320.623,
        "text": "新的世界只有一个把手可以打开"
      },
      {
        "start": 320.623,
        "end": 322.656,
        "text": "最令人称奇的是这个："
      },
      {
        "start": 322.656,
        "end": 326.656,
        "text": "你可以通过造一个把手来制造一个世界"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to write descriptively",
    "youtubeId": "RSoRzTtwgP4",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Nalo Hopkinson",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 8.413,
        "end": 11.747,
        "text": "我们出于很多原因去阅读小说。"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.747,
        "end": 12.747,
        "text": "找乐，"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.747,
        "end": 15.0,
        "text": "找出真相，"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.0,
        "end": 18.049,
        "text": "穿越到陌生的新星球，"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.049,
        "end": 19.169,
        "text": "被惊吓，"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.169,
        "end": 19.911,
        "text": "大笑，"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.911,
        "end": 21.29,
        "text": "哭泣，"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.29,
        "end": 22.028,
        "text": "思考，"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.028,
        "end": 23.153,
        "text": "感受，"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.153,
        "end": 28.294,
        "text": "为了沉浸其中而忘记自己身在何处。"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.294,
        "end": 30.954,
        "text": "那么，写小说呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.954,
        "end": 33.559,
        "text": "你怎样把读者吸引到自己的故事中呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.559,
        "end": 34.559,
        "text": "用精彩的故事情节？可能。"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.983,
        "end": 38.715,
        "text": "用引人入胜的角色？ 大概。"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.715,
        "end": 43.401,
        "text": "用优美的语句？ 也许。"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.401,
        "end": 48.344,
        "text": "“比利的腿像面条一样。她的发梢像毒针。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.344,
        "end": 53.414,
        "text": "她的舌头像有毛的海绵，眼睛像是漂白的袋子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.414,
        "end": 57.59,
        "text": "这种描述是否几乎使你像比利一样感到眩晕作呕？"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.59,
        "end": 60.803,
        "text": "我们知道比利的腿并不是真正的面条。"
      },
      {
        "start": 60.803,
        "end": 64.268,
        "text": "对于比利来说，它们像煮熟的面条一样无力松软。"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.268,
        "end": 67.223,
        "text": "这是一个隐晦的对比，叫做“暗喻”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.223,
        "end": 70.239,
        "text": "那么，为什么不直接这样写："
      },
      {
        "start": 70.239,
        "end": 72.961,
        "text": "“比利感到反胃和虚弱。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.961,
        "end": 78.0,
        "text": "很可能是因为第二种描述不像第一种那样生动有趣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.0,
        "end": 81.118,
        "text": "小说的关键是施加一个咒语——"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.118,
        "end": 85.769,
        "text": "一种让读者置身于故事中的短暂幻觉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.769,
        "end": 88.077,
        "text": "小说调动感官，"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.077,
        "end": 90.723,
        "text": "帮我们营造一种"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.723,
        "end": 93.571,
        "text": "关于主人公经历的生动的精神幻象。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.571,
        "end": 97.32900000000001,
        "text": "舞台和荧屏直接调用我们的一部分感官，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.32900000000001,
        "end": 101.727,
        "text": "我们看到、听到那些剧中人物和场景的互动，"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.727,
        "end": 103.297,
        "text": "但是对于单调的小说来说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.297,
        "end": 107.531,
        "text": "你所拥有的只是一些在对比鲜明的背景之上的静止符号。"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.531,
        "end": 111.803,
        "text": "如果你用事实性的、没有质感的语言来描述故事，"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.803,
        "end": 114.211,
        "text": "那个咒语的功能可能就比较弱。"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.211,
        "end": 117.959,
        "text": "你的读者除了理解那些文字之外，可能不会收获更多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.959,
        "end": 120.171,
        "text": "她知道比利的感觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.171,
        "end": 123.762,
        "text": "但是她不会感同身受。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.762,
        "end": 127.454,
        "text": "虽然她在阅读，但并没有沉浸到故事中去，"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.454,
        "end": 132.753,
        "text": "她只是同比利自己一样，发现了关于比利生活的真相。"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.753,
        "end": 135.667,
        "text": "小说依赖于我们的感官："
      },
      {
        "start": 135.667,
        "end": 136.528,
        "text": "味觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.528,
        "end": 137.65800000000002,
        "text": "嗅觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.65800000000002,
        "end": 138.709,
        "text": "触觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.709,
        "end": 139.9,
        "text": "听觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.9,
        "end": 141.24,
        "text": "视觉，"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.24,
        "end": 143.135,
        "text": "以及动感。"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.135,
        "end": 148.786,
        "text": "它还依赖于我们的抽象、联想能力。"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.786,
        "end": 150.816,
        "text": "来看下面这个句子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.816,
        "end": 152.965,
        "text": "“世界像幽灵般寂静，"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.965,
        "end": 158.106,
        "text": "除了船帆的断裂声，以及水拍打船身的汩汩声。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.106,
        "end": 160.769,
        "text": "“寂静”，“断裂”，”汩汩“这些词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 160.769,
        "end": 163.465,
        "text": "和听觉相关。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.465,
        "end": 167.288,
        "text": "注意，巴克尔没有用那个通常会用的词——声音。"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.288,
        "end": 172.752,
        "text": "他选择的每个词都能激发一种特殊的声音质感。"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.752,
        "end": 176.28,
        "text": "然后，像画家涂抹颜料"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.28,
        "end": 179.142,
        "text": "以赋予一幅画质感一样，"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.142,
        "end": 183.723,
        "text": "他添加了另一层，动感，“帆的断裂，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.723,
        "end": 186.723,
        "text": "和触觉，“水拍打船身的汩汩声。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.186,
        "end": 191.174,
        "text": "最终，他给我们一种抽象的连接，"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.174,
        "end": 194.574,
        "text": "通过把”寂静“和”鬼魂“这两个词放在一起。"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.574,
        "end": 196.843,
        "text": "不是“像鬼魂一样寂静，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.843,
        "end": 198.944,
        "text": "这样会把一种间离性的明喻置于"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.944,
        "end": 201.324,
        "text": "读者和经验之间。"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.324,
        "end": 205.626,
        "text": "相反，巴克尔用“鬼魂般的寂静”的比喻，"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.626,
        "end": 209.132,
        "text": "来形成一个暗含的而非明显的比较。"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.132,
        "end": 211.79,
        "text": "作家们通常被告诫：要避免陈词滥调"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.79,
        "end": 216.232,
        "text": "因为在一个用烂了的形象中，读者很难投入进去"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.232,
        "end": 218.482,
        "text": "如“像玫瑰一样红。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.482,
        "end": 219.251,
        "text": "但是如果给他们，"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.251,
        "end": 222.083,
        "text": "“爱情...开始于沙滩上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.083,
        "end": 227.083,
        "text": "它始于当雅各布看到穿着一身'烩樱桃'裙子的安奈特时，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.083,
        "end": 229.78300000000002,
        "text": "这时读者们就开始在头脑中"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.78300000000002,
        "end": 233.186,
        "text": "猜想“烩樱桃”的裙子是什么样的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.186,
        "end": 236.809,
        "text": "突然，他们在沙滩上即将陷入爱河。"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.809,
        "end": 241.498,
        "text": "他们在本能的和观念的层面上同时经历着故事，"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.498,
        "end": 244.188,
        "text": "见到作者正在一个想象性的戏剧中"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.188,
        "end": 247.986,
        "text": "创造一个感官的动态世界。"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.986,
        "end": 251.135,
        "text": "所以当你写作时，用那些精心选择的词汇，"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.135,
        "end": 256.341,
        "text": "以调动听觉、视觉、味觉、触觉、嗅觉，和运动。"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.341,
        "end": 260.341,
        "text": "然后在你的故事元素之中创造一些出其不意的暗示，"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.348,
        "end": 264.348,
        "text": "以点燃读者的想象力。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "The pleasure of poetic pattern",
    "youtubeId": "URuMb15CWJs",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "David Silverstein",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.839,
        "end": 8.32,
        "text": "只要一小会儿"
      },
      {
        "start": 8.32,
        "end": 10.315,
        "text": "请凝神于你的呼吸"
      },
      {
        "start": 10.315,
        "end": 12.14,
        "text": "慢慢吸气"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.14,
        "end": 13.756,
        "text": "慢慢呼气"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.756,
        "end": 15.274,
        "text": "慢慢吸气"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.274,
        "end": 16.625,
        "text": "慢慢呼气"
      },
      {
        "start": 16.625,
        "end": 19.944,
        "text": "每个人都在重复同样的模式"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.944,
        "end": 21.574,
        "text": "想想你的脉搏"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.574,
        "end": 25.474,
        "text": "这个跳动深植于我们的生命结构之中"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.474,
        "end": 29.405,
        "text": "简单来说，我们是节奏和重复的产物"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.405,
        "end": 31.466,
        "text": "这是我们活动的中心"
      },
      {
        "start": 31.466,
        "end": 33.231,
        "text": "节奏和重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.26,
        "end": 36.449,
        "text": "吸气"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.449,
        "end": 38.516,
        "text": "呼气"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.516,
        "end": 41.409,
        "text": "我们每天都从这些节奏和重复中获得快乐"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.409,
        "end": 42.876,
        "text": "比如一首歌的节奏"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.876,
        "end": 44.148,
        "text": "鼓点"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.148,
        "end": 45.564,
        "text": "点头"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.564,
        "end": 47.874,
        "text": "或者是重复 的汤罐头"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.874,
        "end": 49.492,
        "text": "果园里一排排果树"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.492,
        "end": 51.382,
        "text": "花瓣的艺术性"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.382,
        "end": 53.511,
        "text": "模式是让人愉悦的"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.511,
        "end": 56.475,
        "text": "在语言中，节奏和重复常常被用来"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.475,
        "end": 59.406,
        "text": "作为诗歌的构建模块"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.406,
        "end": 61.305,
        "text": "这是语言的节奏"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.305,
        "end": 64.101,
        "text": "由音节和重音构成"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.101,
        "end": 69.806,
        "text": "比如，“So long as men can breathe or eyes can see”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.806,
        "end": 73.026,
        "text": "语言的重复有多个层次："
      },
      {
        "start": 73.026,
        "end": 74.667,
        "text": "字母的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.667,
        "end": 78.071,
        "text": "“So long lives this and this gives life to thee”"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.071,
        "end": 79.291,
        "text": "音节的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.291,
        "end": 81.874,
        "text": "“breathe”、“see”、“thee”"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.874,
        "end": 83.477,
        "text": "以及单词的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.477,
        "end": 85.61,
        "text": "重复的用途极为广泛"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.61,
        "end": 89.342,
        "text": "是诗人们最具可塑性和最可靠的工具之一"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.342,
        "end": 91.818,
        "text": "它可以让听者的情绪跌宕起伏"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.818,
        "end": 94.197,
        "text": "可以强化或削弱句子"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.197,
        "end": 97.223,
        "text": "可以统一或分散观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.223,
        "end": 99.318,
        "text": "事实上，节奏本身"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.318,
        "end": 102.088,
        "text": "就是重音节的重复模式"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.088,
        "end": 104.5,
        "text": "节奏是重复的一种形式"
      },
      {
        "start": 104.5,
        "end": 106.362,
        "text": "虽然用途多样"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.362,
        "end": 108.94200000000001,
        "text": "但太多重复会带来负面效果"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.94200000000001,
        "end": 113.095,
        "text": "想想看，在黑板上写20遍同一个句子"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.095,
        "end": 115.739,
        "text": "一遍，一遍，一遍，一遍"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.739,
        "end": 119.695,
        "text": "或者孩子大声吵闹要引起母亲的注意"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.695,
        "end": 123.241,
        "text": "“妈妈，妈妈，妈咪，妈妈，妈妈”"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.241,
        "end": 126.164,
        "text": "这可不是我们心目中的诗歌"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.164,
        "end": 129.831,
        "text": "那么，诗歌中的重复到底是什么？为什么它们具有艺术性？"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.831,
        "end": 132.249,
        "text": "最常见的重复也许是韵脚"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.249,
        "end": 135.343,
        "text": "单词结尾的音节重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.343,
        "end": 137.529,
        "text": "以莎士比亚为例"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.529,
        "end": 140.547,
        "text": "我们经常在句子结尾读到韵脚"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.547,
        "end": 143.862,
        "text": "这种重复制造了一种期待"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.862,
        "end": 147.601,
        "text": "我们开始仔细聆听这些相似音节的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.601,
        "end": 151.25,
        "text": "当我们听见音节、发现模式时，会感到愉悦"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.25,
        "end": 153.588,
        "text": "就像在视觉混乱的画幅中找到沃尔多"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.588,
        "end": 156.815,
        "text": "我们在纷繁对话中听见了重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.815,
        "end": 161.347,
        "text": "不过韵脚不必只出现在句末"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.347,
        "end": 163.374,
        "text": "请注意有力的“i”音"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.374,
        "end": 167.631,
        "text": "\"So long lives this and this gives life to thee.\""
      },
      {
        "start": 167.631,
        "end": 170.757,
        "text": "元音的重复发音被称为元韵"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.757,
        "end": 173.77100000000002,
        "text": "埃米纳姆的《迷失你自己》中也能听到元韵"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.77100000000002,
        "end": 177.14600000000002,
        "text": "注意在每句中间和结尾"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.14600000000002,
        "end": 179.15,
        "text": "“e”和‘o’音是如何重复的"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.15,
        "end": 181.011,
        "text": "“Oh, there goes gravity,"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.011,
        "end": 183.046,
        "text": "Oh, there goes rabbit, he choked,"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.046,
        "end": 185.578,
        "text": "he so mad but he won't give up that easy,"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.578,
        "end": 187.22,
        "text": "no, he won't have it,"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.22,
        "end": 189.891,
        "text": "he knows his whole back's to these ropes.\""
      },
      {
        "start": 189.903,
        "end": 192.441,
        "text": "交替的元韵创造了自身的节奏"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.441,
        "end": 195.982,
        "text": "让我们试图用自己的声音去重复它"
      },
      {
        "start": 195.982,
        "end": 200.261,
        "text": "类似的，和音是类辅音的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.261,
        "end": 202.385,
        "text": "比如“I”和“th”音"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.385,
        "end": 206.417,
        "text": "\"So long lives this and this gives life to thee.\""
      },
      {
        "start": 206.417,
        "end": 208.99099999999999,
        "text": "实际上，这类特殊的和音"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.99099999999999,
        "end": 211.201,
        "text": "出现在单词的开头"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.201,
        "end": 213.207,
        "text": "你们可能都听过"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.207,
        "end": 216.482,
        "text": "它叫做头韵或前押韵"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.482,
        "end": 218.639,
        "text": "最好的例子就是绕口令"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.639,
        "end": 221.187,
        "text": "Betty bought some butter but the butter was bitter"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.187,
        "end": 224.63400000000001,
        "text": "so Betty bought some better butter to make the bitter butter better."
      },
      {
        "start": 224.63400000000001,
        "end": 229.357,
        "text": "当我们读到和音时，不管是出现在单词中间或开头"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.357,
        "end": 232.54399999999998,
        "text": "模式带来的愉悦感很明显。"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.54399999999998,
        "end": 237.281,
        "text": "虽然绕口令也反映出对诗歌重复的多样性的需求"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.281,
        "end": 239.253,
        "text": "但不得不说，在有些人看来"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.253,
        "end": 242.5,
        "text": "绕口令是对诗歌的低级模仿，或只是噱头"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.5,
        "end": 246.784,
        "text": "因为它们在相同音节上的重复如此强烈"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.784,
        "end": 249.192,
        "text": "近似于在黑板上抄写相同句子的重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.192,
        "end": 252.538,
        "text": "从根本上说，只有诗人才能找到平衡"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.538,
        "end": 253.858,
        "text": "学习何时重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.858,
        "end": 255.181,
        "text": "何时即兴重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.181,
        "end": 257.009,
        "text": "何时满足人们的期待"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.009,
        "end": 259.367,
        "text": "以及何时打破期待"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.367,
        "end": 261.97,
        "text": "在这种平衡中，也许只需要记住"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.97,
        "end": 265.061,
        "text": "我们都生活在一个极度多样化的世界中"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.061,
        "end": 267.987,
        "text": "我们都有自己的呼吸和心跳"
      },
      {
        "start": 267.987,
        "end": 270.755,
        "text": "不管身在何方，我们都有自己的重复节奏"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "What makes a poem … a poem?",
    "youtubeId": "JwhouCNq-Fc",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Melissa Kovacs",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.039,
        "end": 9.319,
        "text": "穆罕默德·阿里花费数年时间训练"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.319,
        "end": 13.24,
        "text": "最终成为了世界上最伟大的拳击手，"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.52,
        "end": 17.149,
        "text": "但他只用了很少的时间， 创造出了最短的诗。"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.149,
        "end": 20.95,
        "text": "1975年，阿里在哈佛毕业典礼上演讲，"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.95,
        "end": 24.68,
        "text": "演讲以团结和友谊为主题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.68,
        "end": 27.371,
        "text": "演讲之后，观众仍不肯让阿里结束。"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.371,
        "end": 29.06,
        "text": "希望他可以做一首诗。"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.06,
        "end": 32.962,
        "text": "于是，阿里作出了目前最短的诗。"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.962,
        "end": 35.661,
        "text": "“我，我们。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.661,
        "end": 37.971,
        "text": "或者是“我，哦耶？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.971,
        "end": 39.121,
        "text": "没人能完全肯定。"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.121,
        "end": 45.471,
        "text": "不管怎样，如果两个词即可成诗， 那到底什么才叫做诗呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.471,
        "end": 48.101,
        "text": "诗人自己也对这个问题很头疼，"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.101,
        "end": 51.605,
        "text": "人们通常使用比喻去给出答案。"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.605,
        "end": 53.68,
        "text": "诗歌是一台小型的机器吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.68,
        "end": 54.765,
        "text": "是烟火吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.765,
        "end": 55.821,
        "text": "是回声吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.821,
        "end": 57.01,
        "text": "抑或是一个梦吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.01,
        "end": 60.442,
        "text": "诗歌通常具有可辨识的特点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.352,
        "end": 65.081,
        "text": "第一，诗歌通常侧重于语言的音乐属性。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.551,
        "end": 68.481,
        "text": "这可以通过使用押韵、节奏、格律实现，"
      },
      {
        "start": 68.481,
        "end": 69.979,
        "text": "从莎士比亚的十四行诗，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.979,
        "end": 71.542,
        "text": "到孔子的颂诗，"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.542,
        "end": 73.772,
        "text": "再到梵语都有此特点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.852,
        "end": 76.556,
        "text": "第二，诗歌使用凝练的语言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.556,
        "end": 80.492,
        "text": "这仿佛是去掉文学作品中的水分。"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.492,
        "end": 83.69200000000001,
        "text": "第三，诗歌通常表达激烈的情感，"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.872,
        "end": 85.875,
        "text": "例如Rumi的宗教诗歌，"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.875,
        "end": 89.05199999999999,
        "text": "Pablo Neruda的“赞洋葱”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.312,
        "end": 93.88300000000001,
        "text": "诗歌，与艺术一样， 挑战着简单的概念和定义。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.88300000000001,
        "end": 96.303,
        "text": "在发明书写之前，早期诗歌的节奏模式"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.303,
        "end": 100.163,
        "text": "是为了让人们更好的记住故事，"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.163,
        "end": 102.703,
        "text": "但诗歌不总是抒发情感的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.703,
        "end": 104.251,
        "text": "Reinhard Döhl的“苹果”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 104.251,
        "end": 106.649,
        "text": "Eugen Gomringer的具象诗，"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.649,
        "end": 109.68,
        "text": "同时体现出了诗歌与视觉艺术。"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.16,
        "end": 112.456,
        "text": "在E.E. Cummings的诗中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.456,
        "end": 115.17,
        "text": "形式与文字同样重要，"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.31,
        "end": 116.17,
        "text": "在这种情况下，"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.17,
        "end": 121.909,
        "text": "悲伤孤独可以通过一片落叶来展现，"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.909,
        "end": 125.569,
        "text": "如果诗歌的视觉特征消失，"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.569,
        "end": 127.989,
        "text": "也许我们还需要考虑音乐这种形式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.989,
        "end": 130.6,
        "text": "这也是人们所热衷讨论的话题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.6,
        "end": 132.469,
        "text": "一首歌能算是一首诗吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.669,
        "end": 136.189,
        "text": "在文学的层面，很多人并不认为 词作者是诗人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.189,
        "end": 137.189,
        "text": "但是一些艺术家所写的歌词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.189,
        "end": 138.689,
        "text": "例如Paul Simon，"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.689,
        "end": 139.788,
        "text": "Bob Dylan，"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.788,
        "end": 141.159,
        "text": "以及Tupac Shakur，"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.159,
        "end": 143.829,
        "text": "他们的歌词即便没有配乐也是非常出色的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.829,
        "end": 147.049,
        "text": "在说唱中，诗歌所包含的元素例如 韵脚、节奏和意象，"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.049,
        "end": 149.529,
        "text": "也同样是必不可少的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.529,
        "end": 152.359,
        "text": "以Notorious B.I.G的歌词举例来说。"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.359,
        "end": 154.727,
        "text": "“我能听到汗水缓缓流下你的面颊，"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.727,
        "end": 157.019,
        "text": "你的心跳如野兽的脚步，"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.019,
        "end": 159.511,
        "text": "闪电，颤动着实体。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.801,
        "end": 162.49099999999999,
        "text": "目前，我们所看到的诗歌都是分行的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.451,
        "end": 164.458,
        "text": "我们甚至可以想象"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.458,
        "end": 166.385,
        "text": "拳王阿里的那只有两个词的诗，"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.385,
        "end": 170.028,
        "text": "也能断成两部分——我，我们。"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.258,
        "end": 173.304,
        "text": "诗歌拥有可以一眼辨识的特点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.304,
        "end": 176.679,
        "text": "它的分行使得读者可以确定诗歌的节奏。"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.209,
        "end": 179.208,
        "text": "但如果分行消失了呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.628,
        "end": 181.938,
        "text": "诗歌会因此而失去其精华所在么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.118,
        "end": 183.433,
        "text": "也许并不会。"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.433,
        "end": 185.017,
        "text": "想象一下散文。"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.237,
        "end": 187.989,
        "text": "它运用了生动的形象以及对文字的把玩，"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.989,
        "end": 190.631,
        "text": "但是散文是以段落来划分的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.27100000000002,
        "end": 195.343,
        "text": "当我们将诗歌看成是一种概念而非形式时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 195.343,
        "end": 197.969,
        "text": "我们可以发现诗歌随处可见："
      },
      {
        "start": 198.149,
        "end": 199.378,
        "text": "在圣歌中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 199.378,
        "end": 201.899,
        "text": "在马丁·路德金、"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.899,
        "end": 203.179,
        "text": "约翰·肯尼迪、"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.179,
        "end": 204.59,
        "text": "温斯顿·丘吉尔的演讲中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 204.59,
        "end": 207.429,
        "text": "甚至是在社交媒体中， 都可以看到诗歌的影子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.429,
        "end": 212.8,
        "text": "2010年，一名记者Joanna Smith发推特， 介绍海地地震的情况，"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.14,
        "end": 216.091,
        "text": "“在听到我的名字时，我正在B超室穿衣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.091,
        "end": 218.811,
        "text": "一阵震颤。我跑向推拉门冲到外面。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.811,
        "end": 222.251,
        "text": "现在，已然安全。而公鸡正在啼叫。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.531,
        "end": 226.061,
        "text": "这名记者使用简洁、有力的表达，"
      },
      {
        "start": 226.061,
        "end": 228.261,
        "text": "语言生动，历历在目。"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.273,
        "end": 230.673,
        "text": "如同日本俳句，"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.673,
        "end": 235.403,
        "text": "这种日本传统诗歌简短有爆发力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.403,
        "end": 239.514,
        "text": "它仅有三行，遵循“五、七、五”的音节排列。"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.89,
        "end": 243.63,
        "text": "诗歌的发展漫长且形式多变，"
      },
      {
        "start": 243.632,
        "end": 245.504,
        "text": "它也在不断地改变。"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.504,
        "end": 252.403,
        "text": "今天，诗歌、散文、歌曲以及视觉艺术的 界限愈发模糊。"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.633,
        "end": 255.044,
        "text": "然而，始终没有改变的是。"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.044,
        "end": 256.774,
        "text": "诗歌一词本为动词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.774,
        "end": 262.714,
        "text": "来源于古希腊语，意为创造。"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.204,
        "end": 268.294,
        "text": "诗人如同工匠，面对着丰富的素材，"
      },
      {
        "start": 268.294,
        "end": 270.234,
        "text": "用这些生活中的素材去创造新的见解，"
      },
      {
        "start": 270.234,
        "end": 274.712,
        "text": "以仅有人类拥有的方式去定义人类。"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.552,
        "end": 281.705,
        "text": "达特茅斯学院的研究者曾试验 机器人能否写诗。"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.705,
        "end": 284.585,
        "text": "评审员们需要判断十四行诗中"
      },
      {
        "start": 284.585,
        "end": 288.734,
        "text": "哪些由机器写出，哪些由人类写出。"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.374,
        "end": 294.924,
        "text": "尽管科学家已经能够将人工智能使用在众多领域，"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.924,
        "end": 296.212,
        "text": "例如制造业、"
      },
      {
        "start": 296.212,
        "end": 296.96500000000003,
        "text": "制药业、"
      },
      {
        "start": 296.96500000000003,
        "end": 298.495,
        "text": "甚至是在新闻业，"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.495,
        "end": 300.505,
        "text": "诗歌却不是它们所擅长的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 300.935,
        "end": 304.625,
        "text": "机器人在这一领域仍未有任何胜算。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Aphasia: The disorder that makes you lose your words",
    "youtubeId": "-GsVhbmecJA",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Susan Wortman-Jutt",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.263,
        "end": 12.01,
        "text": "语言是生活中非常基本的部分，我们经常会觉得它的存在是理所应当的"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.01,
        "end": 15.389,
        "text": "有了它，我们可以交流我们的思想和感情"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.389,
        "end": 17.37,
        "text": "沉浸在书本里"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.37,
        "end": 18.938,
        "text": "发送短信"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.938,
        "end": 21.124,
        "text": "向朋友打招呼"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.124,
        "end": 25.468,
        "text": "很难想象当我们不能把想法变成语言时会是怎么"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.468,
        "end": 29.304,
        "text": "但是如果大脑中脆弱的语言网络"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.304,
        "end": 33.556,
        "text": "被中风，疾病，或者外伤所损坏了"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.556,
        "end": 37.484,
        "text": "你会发现自己真的哑口无言"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.484,
        "end": 43.505,
        "text": "这种叫做失语症的病症，可以阻碍所有的交流方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.505,
        "end": 47.035,
        "text": "失语症患者患病后智商不变"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.035,
        "end": 48.985,
        "text": "他们知道自己想说什么"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.985,
        "end": 52.246,
        "text": "但是不能每次都准确无误的说出"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.246,
        "end": 56.539,
        "text": "他们可能会不经意的用错词语"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.559,
        "end": 59.684,
        "text": "像用“狗”代替“猫” 一样用相关联的词替换"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.684,
        "end": 66.055,
        "text": "或者是听上去相似的词 例如“house“说成\"horse”"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.055,
        "end": 69.254,
        "text": "有些时候他们说的词语甚至不被认知"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.254,
        "end": 73.995,
        "text": "失语症被分为几种，归属于两大类"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.995,
        "end": 76.325,
        "text": "流畅的，或者善于倾听的失语症"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.325,
        "end": 79.96600000000001,
        "text": "和不流畅的，表达类的失语症"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.96600000000001,
        "end": 83.776,
        "text": "患有流畅失语症的人有正常的语调变化"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.776,
        "end": 86.457,
        "text": "但是用的词没有任何意义"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.457,
        "end": 89.526,
        "text": "他们无法理解别人在说什么"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.526,
        "end": 93.535,
        "text": "也经常时常无法找出自己语句里的错误"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.535,
        "end": 96.305,
        "text": "另一方面，非流畅型失语症患者"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.305,
        "end": 98.206,
        "text": "或许有好的理解能力"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.206,
        "end": 103.36699999999999,
        "text": "但是会说话时出现长时间的停顿以及语法错误"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.36699999999999,
        "end": 105.477,
        "text": "我们都有过那种话到嘴边"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.477,
        "end": 108.488,
        "text": "却找不到适合的词的感觉"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.488,
        "end": 112.818,
        "text": "但是患有失语症意味着连简单的日常生活用品都无法表达"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.818,
        "end": 116.518,
        "text": "连阅读和写作都会变得困难和沮丧"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.518,
        "end": 119.30799999999999,
        "text": "那么这个失语症是怎么发生的呢"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.30799999999999,
        "end": 121.807,
        "text": "人的大脑里有两个半球"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.807,
        "end": 125.56700000000001,
        "text": "我们知道大部分人的左脑负责语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.56700000000001,
        "end": 127.978,
        "text": "这要归功于1861年"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.978,
        "end": 130.677,
        "text": "一位叫做保罗布洛卡的内科医生的研究"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.677,
        "end": 135.506,
        "text": "他的研究的病患只能说一个词 tan"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.506,
        "end": 137.998,
        "text": "通过对他的大脑的尸检"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.998,
        "end": 141.338,
        "text": "布洛卡发现了患者左脑有一大块区域受到了损伤"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.338,
        "end": 143.727,
        "text": "现在这一区域被称为布洛卡区"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.727,
        "end": 148.15800000000002,
        "text": "现在，科学家发现布洛卡区负责给物体取名字"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.15800000000002,
        "end": 151.078,
        "text": "并且协调说话用的肌肉"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.078,
        "end": 155.878,
        "text": "在布洛卡区的后面是威尔尼克区 靠近听觉皮质"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.878,
        "end": 159.008,
        "text": "这里是大脑把意思和声音所联系起来的地方"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.008,
        "end": 163.338,
        "text": "威尔尼克区受伤会干涉到大脑理解语言的能力"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.338,
        "end": 168.489,
        "text": "失语症就是由于二者之一或全部受损产生的"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.489,
        "end": 170.829,
        "text": "幸运的是 大脑里还有别的地方"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.829,
        "end": 172.779,
        "text": "支持着这两个中心区域"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.779,
        "end": 175.21800000000002,
        "text": "同时可以帮助交流"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.21800000000002,
        "end": 179.078,
        "text": "甚至有些控制运动的大脑区域都和语言有联系"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.078,
        "end": 184.478,
        "text": "功能性磁共振成像发现了当我们听到动作词 例如“跑”或“跳”"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.478,
        "end": 187.6,
        "text": "大脑中负责控制运动的部分会亮起来"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.6,
        "end": 190.969,
        "text": "好像身体真的在跑步或者跳舞一样"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.969,
        "end": 193.929,
        "text": "我们右脑半球也对语言有贡献"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.929,
        "end": 197.369,
        "text": "它加强我们讲话时的节奏和声调"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.369,
        "end": 201.099,
        "text": "当交流十分困难的时候"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.099,
        "end": 203.469,
        "text": "这些非语言区域有时也会帮助失语症患者"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.469,
        "end": 205.668,
        "text": "那失语症有多常见呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.668,
        "end": 208.913,
        "text": "在美国，大约有一百万人患有这种疾病"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.913,
        "end": 212.53,
        "text": "估计每年还会新增八万名病患"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.53,
        "end": 215.66899999999998,
        "text": "中风活下来的人里面大约有三分之一被失语症所折磨"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.66899999999998,
        "end": 220.15,
        "text": "这让它比帕金森综合症和多发性硬化症更加普遍"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.18,
        "end": 222.469,
        "text": "但是知道的人却更少"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.469,
        "end": 227.88,
        "text": "有一种罕见的失语症叫做原发性进行性失语症 简称PPA"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.88,
        "end": 230.77100000000002,
        "text": "它不是由中风或者大脑受损引起的"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.77100000000002,
        "end": 233.209,
        "text": "而实际上是失智症的一种表现"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.209,
        "end": 236.061,
        "text": "语言能力退化是失智症的第一症状"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.061,
        "end": 241.232,
        "text": "治疗PPA的目的是让患者在其他症状最终出现之前"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.232,
        "end": 244.56,
        "text": "尽量长时间的保持语言能力"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.56,
        "end": 248.33,
        "text": "如果失语症是由大脑受损或中风引起的"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.33,
        "end": 252.041,
        "text": "语言治疗或许可以提高语言能力"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.041,
        "end": 255.911,
        "text": "我们的大脑有自我修复的能力 被称之为大脑的可塑性"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.911,
        "end": 258.48,
        "text": "在大脑受伤区域自我修复的过程中"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.48,
        "end": 261.994,
        "text": "这使得它周围的部分行使部分功能"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.994,
        "end": 266.405,
        "text": "科学家们在用新的技术开展实验"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.405,
        "end": 271.34,
        "text": "希望达到增强失语症患者大脑可塑性的目标"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.34,
        "end": 275.254,
        "text": "现在 许多失语症患者依然与世隔绝"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.254,
        "end": 279.94100000000003,
        "text": "他们怕别人不理解他们在说什么 或者不给他们多一点时间去表达"
      },
      {
        "start": 279.94100000000003,
        "end": 284.311,
        "text": "通过付出一些时间，用他们可以做到的方式灵活的交流"
      },
      {
        "start": 284.311,
        "end": 287.092,
        "text": "你可以帮助他们重新打开语言的大门"
      },
      {
        "start": 287.092,
        "end": 291.712,
        "text": "超越失语症的限制"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How language shapes the way we think",
    "youtubeId": "RKK7wGAYP6k",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Lera Boroditsky",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 12.94,
        "end": 15.515,
        "text": "我们通过语言交流，"
      },
      {
        "start": 16.09,
        "end": 17.63,
        "text": "因为我可以说话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.634,
        "end": 20.924,
        "text": "这是我们人类拥有的一种神奇能力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.924,
        "end": 25.066,
        "text": "我们可以互相传递非常复杂的思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.479,
        "end": 29.068,
        "text": "我现在正在做的是，一边呼气，"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.068,
        "end": 30.307,
        "text": "一边用我的嘴巴发出声音。"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.307,
        "end": 32.649,
        "text": "我在发出各种语调、嘶嘶声、呼气，"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.649,
        "end": 35.713,
        "text": "而这些引起周边的空气振动。"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.713,
        "end": 38.183,
        "text": "这些空气振动传到你那里，"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.183,
        "end": 39.992,
        "text": "它们到达你的耳鼓，"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.992,
        "end": 44.602,
        "text": "然后你的大脑会 将你耳鼓接收到的振动"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.616,
        "end": 47.379,
        "text": "转化成思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.031,
        "end": 49.322,
        "text": "至少我希望是这样的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.322,
        "end": 50.033,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.033,
        "end": 51.374,
        "text": "我希望如此。"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.374,
        "end": 55.964,
        "text": "正是因为这种能力， 人类能够将我们的思想"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.964,
        "end": 58.69,
        "text": "跨越时间和空间，传递下去"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.69,
        "end": 63.26,
        "text": "我们能够将知识互相传递。"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.26,
        "end": 66.435,
        "text": "比如，我现在就可以给你传递一个奇怪的想法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.435,
        "end": 67.63,
        "text": "我可以说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 68.367,
        "end": 71.549,
        "text": "“想象一只水母在一个图书馆里 一边跳着华尔兹，"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.549,
        "end": 73.769,
        "text": "一边思考着量子力学。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.769,
        "end": 75.191,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.191,
        "end": 78.223,
        "text": "当然如果大家的生活 到目前为止都还比较顺利的话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.223,
        "end": 80.369,
        "text": "你之前应该没有这样想过。"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.369,
        "end": 81.395,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.395,
        "end": 83.197,
        "text": "而我现在让你们有了这个想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.197,
        "end": 84.346,
        "text": "正是通过语言做到的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.654,
        "end": 86.732,
        "text": "当然，世界上不是只有一种语言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.732,
        "end": 89.92099999999999,
        "text": "全球有大约7000种语言。"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.92099999999999,
        "end": 92.725,
        "text": "这些语言有着各式各样的区别。"
      },
      {
        "start": 92.725,
        "end": 96.33,
        "text": "有些语言有不同的发音，"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.33,
        "end": 98.089,
        "text": "不同的词汇，"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.089,
        "end": 100.106,
        "text": "还有不同的结构——"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.106,
        "end": 102.063,
        "text": "不同的结构很重要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.896,
        "end": 104.05199999999999,
        "text": "于是，我们会问："
      },
      {
        "start": 104.05199999999999,
        "end": 106.718,
        "text": "我们说的语言是否 塑造了我们的思维方式？"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.718,
        "end": 108.304,
        "text": "这其实是个很古老的问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.304,
        "end": 111.499,
        "text": "人们一直以来都在思考这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.499,
        "end": 113.856,
        "text": "神圣罗马帝国的查理曼大帝曾说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.86,
        "end": 116.89,
        "text": "“学会了第二种语言 就拥有了第二个灵魂”——"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.89,
        "end": 119.443,
        "text": "这是相信语言会创造现实。"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.99199999999999,
        "end": 122.886,
        "text": "但另一方面， 莎士比亚笔下的朱丽叶又说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 122.886,
        "end": 124.151,
        "text": "“名字本来没有意义，"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.151,
        "end": 126.515,
        "text": "一朵玫瑰花换个名字也照样芬芳。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.504,
        "end": 130.557,
        "text": "这就指也许语言不能创造现实。"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.926,
        "end": 134.932,
        "text": "这些争论已经持续了几千年。"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.4,
        "end": 138.115,
        "text": "但一直以来，都没有任何数据"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.115,
        "end": 139.711,
        "text": "能够帮助我们确定孰是孰非。"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.23,
        "end": 142.356,
        "text": "最近，在我的实验室 和全球其它一些实验室，"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.356,
        "end": 143.932,
        "text": "我们开始做研究，"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.932,
        "end": 148.559,
        "text": "现在我们有真实的科学数据， 可以帮助回答这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.918,
        "end": 151.459,
        "text": "让我给大家举一些我喜欢的例子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.846,
        "end": 155.224,
        "text": "先从澳大利亚的一个土著社群开始，"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.224,
        "end": 156.986,
        "text": "我有机会跟他们接触过。"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.986,
        "end": 158.743,
        "text": "他们是 Kuuk Thaayorre 人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.743,
        "end": 162.597,
        "text": "他们住在约克角城最西边的 Pormpuraaw。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.351,
        "end": 165.551,
        "text": "Kuuk Thaayorre 人有意思的一点是，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.551,
        "end": 168.643,
        "text": "在这个土著文化里面， 他们没有“左”和“右”这样的词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.643,
        "end": 171.377,
        "text": "所有的东西都是 通过基本方向来表达的："
      },
      {
        "start": 171.381,
        "end": 172.825,
        "text": "东南西北，"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.425,
        "end": 175.954,
        "text": "是的，我说的是“所有的东西”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.954,
        "end": 177.519,
        "text": "比如，你可以说："
      },
      {
        "start": 177.519,
        "end": 180.071,
        "text": "“哦，你西南方的那条腿上有一只蚂蚁”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.178,
        "end": 183.834,
        "text": "或者“把你的杯子往东北偏北边移一下。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.404,
        "end": 187.878,
        "text": "事实上，他们打招呼的方式也是："
      },
      {
        "start": 187.878,
        "end": 189.168,
        "text": "“你往哪里去？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.168,
        "end": 190.53,
        "text": "而回答会是："
      },
      {
        "start": 191.014,
        "end": 193.23,
        "text": "“远处东北偏北处，你呢？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.155,
        "end": 197.27100000000002,
        "text": "想象一下，你走在路上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.27100000000002,
        "end": 198.834,
        "text": "你遇见每一个人"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.834,
        "end": 200.95499999999998,
        "text": "都要报告一下你朝什么方向前进。"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.959,
        "end": 202.132,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.132,
        "end": 205.497,
        "text": "但这会让你很快获得方向感，不是吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.497,
        "end": 208.49099999999999,
        "text": "因为如果你不知道你前行的方向的话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.49099999999999,
        "end": 210.596,
        "text": "你连打招呼都没法进行。"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.969,
        "end": 215.355,
        "text": "事实上，说这类语言的人 他们的方向感非常好，"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.355,
        "end": 218.41,
        "text": "远比我们以为人类可以做到的要好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.84,
        "end": 221.586,
        "text": "我们曾经以为人类的方向感 要比其他生物差，"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.586,
        "end": 223.416,
        "text": "而我们也找了生物原因方面的借口："
      },
      {
        "start": 223.416,
        "end": 226.755,
        "text": "“哦，我们没有 可以感测磁场的鸟嘴或鱼鳞”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 226.755,
        "end": 229.74099999999999,
        "text": "事实并非如此。如果你的语言和文化 给了你这方面的训练，"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.74099999999999,
        "end": 231.014,
        "text": "你是可以做到的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.014,
        "end": 234.084,
        "text": "世界上有些人的方向感就非常好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.088,
        "end": 236.22,
        "text": "为了确保我们大家都同意"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.22,
        "end": 238.839,
        "text": "在这点上我们的思维方式有多大差异，"
      },
      {
        "start": 238.839,
        "end": 241.643,
        "text": "请大家闭上眼睛，"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.887,
        "end": 244.234,
        "text": "然后指向东南方。"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.234,
        "end": 245.958,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.958,
        "end": 247.576,
        "text": "先不要睁开眼睛，请指向东南方。"
      },
      {
        "start": 250.095,
        "end": 252.106,
        "text": "现在，你们可以睁开眼睛了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.106,
        "end": 255.915,
        "text": "我看到你们有指向 那儿、那儿、那儿、那儿的……"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.529,
        "end": 258.351,
        "text": "我自己也不知道哪边是东南方，"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.351,
        "end": 260.049,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.049,
        "end": 261.741,
        "text": "你们也没能帮到我。"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.741,
        "end": 263.102,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.102,
        "end": 265.746,
        "text": "暂且就说，在座的大家 在这个问题上的准确度不是很高。"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.746,
        "end": 269.43,
        "text": "这就是不同语言之间的 认知能力的巨大差异，"
      },
      {
        "start": 269.43,
        "end": 272.865,
        "text": "一群像在座的各位一样 非常优秀的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 272.869,
        "end": 274.452,
        "text": "分不清哪里是哪里，"
      },
      {
        "start": 274.456,
        "end": 275.796,
        "text": "而如果换做另一群人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.796,
        "end": 278.11,
        "text": "一个5岁的孩子也知道答案。"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.11,
        "end": 279.218,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 279.218,
        "end": 282.678,
        "text": "人们思考时间的方式也非常不同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.692,
        "end": 286.713,
        "text": "这里是几张我的祖父 在不同年龄段的照片。"
      },
      {
        "start": 286.713,
        "end": 289.954,
        "text": "如果我让一个英语使用者 将它们按时间进行排列，"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.954,
        "end": 291.443,
        "text": "他们可以会这样排，"
      },
      {
        "start": 291.443,
        "end": 292.638,
        "text": "从左到右。"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.638,
        "end": 294.363,
        "text": "这跟写字的方向有关。"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.363,
        "end": 296.423,
        "text": "如果你说的是希伯来语或阿拉伯语，"
      },
      {
        "start": 296.423,
        "end": 298.847,
        "text": "你则可能会以相反的方向排列，"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.847,
        "end": 300.047,
        "text": "从右到左。"
      },
      {
        "start": 301.578,
        "end": 303.117,
        "text": "那 Kuuk Thaayorre 人——"
      },
      {
        "start": 303.117,
        "end": 305.255,
        "text": "我刚才提到的土著民会怎么排呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 305.255,
        "end": 307.687,
        "text": "他们没有“左”和“右”的概念。"
      },
      {
        "start": 307.687,
        "end": 309.233,
        "text": "我来提示一下大家。"
      },
      {
        "start": 309.233,
        "end": 311.788,
        "text": "当我们让他们面朝南方的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 311.788,
        "end": 313.696,
        "text": "他们将时间顺序从左向右排；"
      },
      {
        "start": 314.391,
        "end": 316.51800000000003,
        "text": "当面朝北方的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 316.51800000000003,
        "end": 318.573,
        "text": "他们将时间顺序从右到左排；"
      },
      {
        "start": 319.026,
        "end": 321.065,
        "text": "当他们面朝东方的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 321.065,
        "end": 322.845,
        "text": "他们将时间从远到近排。"
      },
      {
        "start": 323.608,
        "end": 324.919,
        "text": "发现规律了么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 326.056,
        "end": 327.719,
        "text": "从东到西，对吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 327.719,
        "end": 331.265,
        "text": "因此对他们来说， 时间跟身体的方向无关，"
      },
      {
        "start": 331.265,
        "end": 332.845,
        "text": "而是跟地理有关。"
      },
      {
        "start": 332.849,
        "end": 335.402,
        "text": "对我来说，如果我面向这边， 时间就是这样走的；"
      },
      {
        "start": 335.402,
        "end": 338.019,
        "text": "如果我面向这边， 时间就是这样走的；"
      },
      {
        "start": 338.019,
        "end": 340.283,
        "text": "如果我面向这边， 时间就是这样走的——"
      },
      {
        "start": 340.283,
        "end": 344.204,
        "text": "完全以我为中心， 我每次一转身，"
      },
      {
        "start": 344.204,
        "end": 345.944,
        "text": "时间也要跟着我改变方向。"
      },
      {
        "start": 346.598,
        "end": 349.05899999999997,
        "text": "对 Kuuk Thaayorre 人来说， 时间是跟地理有关的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 349.05899999999997,
        "end": 352.072,
        "text": "这是一种思考时间的 截然不同的方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 352.072,
        "end": 354.023,
        "text": "再给大家说一个人类的聪明之处。"
      },
      {
        "start": 354.027,
        "end": 356.26,
        "text": "假设我问你，这里有多少只企鹅，"
      },
      {
        "start": 356.95799999999997,
        "end": 360.106,
        "text": "我敢说我知道你会怎么解决这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 360.106,
        "end": 362.307,
        "text": "你会“一二三四五六七八”地"
      },
      {
        "start": 362.307,
        "end": 363.525,
        "text": "数过去。"
      },
      {
        "start": 363.525,
        "end": 365.248,
        "text": "你让每一只企鹅对应一个数字，"
      },
      {
        "start": 365.248,
        "end": 368.408,
        "text": "你念出的最后一个数字就是企鹅的总数。"
      },
      {
        "start": 368.408,
        "end": 371.33,
        "text": "这是你小时候就学会了的技巧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 371.33,
        "end": 374.381,
        "text": "你学会了数数， 你也学会了怎么用它。"
      },
      {
        "start": 374.787,
        "end": 376.233,
        "text": "这是一种语言学的技巧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 376.804,
        "end": 378.475,
        "text": "但有些语言不是这样的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 378.475,
        "end": 381.654,
        "text": "因为有些语言没有精确的数字词汇。"
      },
      {
        "start": 382.039,
        "end": 384.91,
        "text": "有一些语言是没有比如“七”"
      },
      {
        "start": 384.91,
        "end": 386.361,
        "text": "或者“八”之类的数字的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 386.793,
        "end": 389.911,
        "text": "事实上，对那些使用没有数字的语言的 人来说，他们不会数数，"
      },
      {
        "start": 389.911,
        "end": 392.762,
        "text": "计算精确的数量 对他们来说是很难的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 392.762,
        "end": 396.649,
        "text": "比如，如果我让你把这么多的企鹅"
      },
      {
        "start": 396.649,
        "end": 398.947,
        "text": "跟同一数量的鸭子匹配起来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 398.947,
        "end": 401.105,
        "text": "你数一下就可以做到了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 401.105,
        "end": 405.0,
        "text": "但对那些没有这一语言特征的人来说 却无法做到。"
      },
      {
        "start": 407.653,
        "end": 410.807,
        "text": "语言的差异还体现在 我们如何分辨颜色，"
      },
      {
        "start": 410.811,
        "end": 411.981,
        "text": "那些视觉的东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 412.348,
        "end": 414.474,
        "text": "有些语言有很多的颜色词汇，"
      },
      {
        "start": 414.474,
        "end": 416.882,
        "text": "有的则很少，就只有“浅色”和“深色”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 416.882,
        "end": 420.519,
        "text": "这些语言差异体现在 不同颜色之间的界限在哪里。"
      },
      {
        "start": 420.519,
        "end": 423.758,
        "text": "比如，在英语里面， 我们有蓝色这个词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 423.758,
        "end": 426.897,
        "text": "它包含了 你在屏幕上看到的所有颜色。"
      },
      {
        "start": 426.897,
        "end": 428.947,
        "text": "但是在俄语里面， 却没有这样的一个词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 428.947,
        "end": 431.167,
        "text": "相反，俄语使用者要把"
      },
      {
        "start": 431.167,
        "end": 432.642,
        "text": "浅蓝色 “goluboy” 和"
      },
      {
        "start": 432.642,
        "end": 434.288,
        "text": "深蓝色 “siniy” 区别开来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 435.138,
        "end": 439.095,
        "text": "所以俄语使用者一生都会在语言上"
      },
      {
        "start": 439.095,
        "end": 440.998,
        "text": "区别这两种颜色。"
      },
      {
        "start": 440.998,
        "end": 444.985,
        "text": "当我们测试人们 辨别这些颜色的能力的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 444.985,
        "end": 447.49,
        "text": "我们发现俄语使用者能够更快地"
      },
      {
        "start": 447.49,
        "end": 449.122,
        "text": "进行这种概念切换，"
      },
      {
        "start": 449.122,
        "end": 451.408,
        "text": "他们能够更快地分辨"
      },
      {
        "start": 451.408,
        "end": 452.916,
        "text": "浅蓝色和深蓝色。"
      },
      {
        "start": 453.299,
        "end": 456.557,
        "text": "当你观察人们在看这些颜色的大脑时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 456.557,
        "end": 459.922,
        "text": "假设你给他们看 从浅蓝色到深蓝色的渐变，"
      },
      {
        "start": 460.798,
        "end": 465.25,
        "text": "那些用不同词形容 “浅蓝”和“深蓝”的人的大脑"
      },
      {
        "start": 465.254,
        "end": 468.758,
        "text": "会在颜色从浅到深的转换时 表现出惊讶，"
      },
      {
        "start": 468.758,
        "end": 471.984,
        "text": "仿佛“哦，某些事情发生了根本的变化”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 471.984,
        "end": 475.858,
        "text": "而不做这种分辨的英语使用者的大脑"
      },
      {
        "start": 475.858,
        "end": 477.468,
        "text": "则不会表现出惊讶，"
      },
      {
        "start": 477.468,
        "end": 479.951,
        "text": "因为没发生什么根本的变化。"
      },
      {
        "start": 482.054,
        "end": 484.522,
        "text": "语言还有各种各样的结构特征。"
      },
      {
        "start": 484.522,
        "end": 485.883,
        "text": "这个是我最喜欢的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 485.883,
        "end": 488.369,
        "text": "很多语言都有语法上的词性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 488.369,
        "end": 493.013,
        "text": "每个名词都有一个指定的词性， 通常是阳性或阴性。"
      },
      {
        "start": 493.013,
        "end": 495.094,
        "text": "这些词性在不同语言中有所不同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 495.094,
        "end": 499.659,
        "text": "比如，太阳在德语中是阴性的， 在西班牙语中则是阳性的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 499.659,
        "end": 501.047,
        "text": "月亮则相反。"
      },
      {
        "start": 501.634,
        "end": 505.096,
        "text": "那这会不会影响人们的思考方式呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 505.096,
        "end": 509.088,
        "text": "德语使用者会觉得太阳更女性化，"
      },
      {
        "start": 509.088,
        "end": 511.044,
        "text": "而月亮更男性化吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 511.767,
        "end": 513.673,
        "text": "事实的确如此。"
      },
      {
        "start": 513.677,
        "end": 519.12,
        "text": "如果你让德语使用者和西班牙语使用者 描述一座桥，"
      },
      {
        "start": 519.124,
        "end": 520.574,
        "text": "就像这一座，"
      },
      {
        "start": 520.574,
        "end": 523.917,
        "text": "“桥”在德语中是阴性的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 523.917,
        "end": 526.117,
        "text": "在西班牙语中则是阳性的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 526.117,
        "end": 530.449,
        "text": "德语使用者更倾向于说桥 “美丽”或“优雅”"
      },
      {
        "start": 530.449,
        "end": 532.62,
        "text": "以及其他很女性化的词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 532.62,
        "end": 535.153,
        "text": "而西班牙语使用者则倾向于说桥"
      },
      {
        "start": 535.153,
        "end": 536.723,
        "text": "“强壮”或“绵长”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 536.723,
        "end": 538.139,
        "text": "那些更男性化的词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 540.849,
        "end": 542.529,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 543.396,
        "end": 547.518,
        "text": "语言的差异还体现在 它们对事件的描述上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 548.06,
        "end": 550.37,
        "text": "以这件事为例，一个意外。"
      },
      {
        "start": 550.37,
        "end": 553.218,
        "text": "在英语里面， 你可以说“他打碎了花瓶”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 553.869,
        "end": 556.387,
        "text": "在西班牙语里面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 556.387,
        "end": 559.278,
        "text": "你更可能会说“花瓶碎了”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 559.278,
        "end": 560.869,
        "text": "或者“花瓶自己碎了”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 561.332,
        "end": 564.554,
        "text": "如果这是一个意外，你不会说 是谁打碎的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 564.558,
        "end": 567.984,
        "text": "在英语里面，很奇怪的是， 我们甚至会说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 567.988,
        "end": 569.255,
        "text": "”我弄伤了我的手臂“。"
      },
      {
        "start": 569.953,
        "end": 571.787,
        "text": "在很多语言里面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 571.791,
        "end": 574.976,
        "text": "你完全不会这样说， 除非你是一个疯子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 574.976,
        "end": 578.349,
        "text": "你试图弄伤自己的手臂， 而且还成功了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 579.22,
        "end": 582.618,
        "text": "如果它是一场意外， 你会使用不一样的语言结构。"
      },
      {
        "start": 582.618,
        "end": 584.537,
        "text": "这会造成不同的结果。"
      },
      {
        "start": 584.537,
        "end": 588.609,
        "text": "使用不同语言的人 关注的点会不一样，"
      },
      {
        "start": 588.609,
        "end": 592.079,
        "text": "这取决于他们的语言是怎么要求的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 592.079,
        "end": 596.265,
        "text": "如果我们让英语使用者和西班牙语使用者 看同样的意外事件，"
      },
      {
        "start": 596.265,
        "end": 599.6,
        "text": "英语使用者会记得这件事是谁干的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 600.525,
        "end": 603.763,
        "text": "因为英语需要你说 “是他做的，他打碎了花瓶”；"
      },
      {
        "start": 603.763,
        "end": 606.87,
        "text": "而西班牙语使用者则 不太可能会记得是谁干的——"
      },
      {
        "start": 606.87,
        "end": 608.235,
        "text": "如果这是一个意外事件的话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 608.235,
        "end": 611.178,
        "text": "他们更可能会记得这是一个意外，"
      },
      {
        "start": 611.178,
        "end": 613.628,
        "text": "他们更可能记得意图。"
      },
      {
        "start": 613.628,
        "end": 616.715,
        "text": "所以两个人看同样的事件，"
      },
      {
        "start": 616.715,
        "end": 618.866,
        "text": "目睹同样的罪行，"
      },
      {
        "start": 618.87,
        "end": 621.936,
        "text": "但记得的却不一定一样。"
      },
      {
        "start": 622.564,
        "end": 625.823,
        "text": "在目击证词方面，这是值得深思的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 626.59,
        "end": 628.886,
        "text": "这对责备和惩罚也有影响。"
      },
      {
        "start": 628.886,
        "end": 630.727,
        "text": "如果我给英语使用者"
      },
      {
        "start": 630.727,
        "end": 632.935,
        "text": "看一个人不小心打碎花瓶，"
      },
      {
        "start": 632.935,
        "end": 636.85,
        "text": "然后我说“他打碎了花瓶”， 而不是说“花瓶碎了”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 637.504,
        "end": 639.447,
        "text": "即使你自己亲眼看到了事件的经过，"
      },
      {
        "start": 639.447,
        "end": 640.633,
        "text": "你看了那段视频，"
      },
      {
        "start": 640.633,
        "end": 642.895,
        "text": "你可以看到花瓶的“罪行”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 644.157,
        "end": 647.114,
        "text": "但是你却会更倾向于惩罚、 责备那个人——"
      },
      {
        "start": 647.114,
        "end": 648.831,
        "text": "仅仅因为我说“他打碎了花瓶”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 648.831,
        "end": 650.318,
        "text": "而不是“花瓶碎了”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 650.931,
        "end": 654.254,
        "text": "语言会引导我们对事件的认知。"
      },
      {
        "start": 655.996,
        "end": 658.882,
        "text": "那我给了大家几个"
      },
      {
        "start": 658.886,
        "end": 662.627,
        "text": "语言如何影响我们思考的例子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 662.627,
        "end": 664.826,
        "text": "它主要通过几个方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 664.826,
        "end": 666.761,
        "text": "语言可以造成大的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 666.761,
        "end": 668.547,
        "text": "我们举了时间和空间的例子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 668.547,
        "end": 670.483,
        "text": "人们对时间和空间的排列"
      },
      {
        "start": 670.487,
        "end": 673.748,
        "text": "可以迥然不同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 674.781,
        "end": 677.015,
        "text": "语言还可以有很深的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 677.019,
        "end": 679.182,
        "text": "我们举了数字的例子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 679.182,
        "end": 681.539,
        "text": "如果你的语言里有数量词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 681.539,
        "end": 682.813,
        "text": "有数字，"
      },
      {
        "start": 682.813,
        "end": 685.378,
        "text": "这会开启一个全新的数学世界。"
      },
      {
        "start": 685.378,
        "end": 687.971,
        "text": "如果你不能数数， 你自然也不会代数学，"
      },
      {
        "start": 687.975,
        "end": 689.423,
        "text": "你将不能做任何"
      },
      {
        "start": 689.423,
        "end": 692.3,
        "text": "需要数学的事情， 像建一个这样的演讲厅，"
      },
      {
        "start": 692.3,
        "end": 694.354,
        "text": "或进行转播，对吧？"
      },
      {
        "start": 694.836,
        "end": 696.523,
        "text": "小小的数字给我们提供了"
      },
      {
        "start": 696.523,
        "end": 699.204,
        "text": "踏进一整个认知领域的垫脚石。"
      },
      {
        "start": 700.42,
        "end": 702.715,
        "text": "语言的影响还可能很早就发生，"
      },
      {
        "start": 702.719,
        "end": 705.609,
        "text": "我们举了颜色的例子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 706.205,
        "end": 708.653,
        "text": "这是非常简单、基本、感知型的决定，"
      },
      {
        "start": 708.653,
        "end": 711.067,
        "text": "我们无时无刻不在做这样的决定，"
      },
      {
        "start": 711.067,
        "end": 712.918,
        "text": "而语言就在那里"
      },
      {
        "start": 712.918,
        "end": 717.279,
        "text": "影响着我们做的这些小小的决定。"
      },
      {
        "start": 718.787,
        "end": 720.64,
        "text": "语言可以有很广阔的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 720.64,
        "end": 723.892,
        "text": "我们举了语法上的词性的例子 看似微不足道，"
      },
      {
        "start": 723.892,
        "end": 727.755,
        "text": "但它却适用于所有名词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 728.061,
        "end": 730.334,
        "text": "这意味着语言可以影响你"
      },
      {
        "start": 730.334,
        "end": 733.261,
        "text": "如何思考所有能用名词表达的东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 733.945,
        "end": 735.514,
        "text": "那可是很多东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 736.449,
        "end": 739.36,
        "text": "最后，我举了一个语言可以如何影响"
      },
      {
        "start": 739.36,
        "end": 741.36,
        "text": "跟我们切身相关的事件的例子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 741.36,
        "end": 743.95,
        "text": "如责备、惩罚和目击证词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 743.95,
        "end": 746.154,
        "text": "这些是我们的日常生活中 非常重要的方面。"
      },
      {
        "start": 748.153,
        "end": 753.148,
        "text": "语言多样性的美丽在于 它向我们揭示了"
      },
      {
        "start": 753.148,
        "end": 757.125,
        "text": "人类的大脑是多么巧妙和灵活。"
      },
      {
        "start": 757.775,
        "end": 762.3,
        "text": "人类大脑创造的不是一个认知体系， 而是7000个，"
      },
      {
        "start": 762.3,
        "end": 764.688,
        "text": "世界上有7000种语言。"
      },
      {
        "start": 766.01,
        "end": 767.681,
        "text": "而我们还可以创造更多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 767.681,
        "end": 770.778,
        "text": "语言是有生命的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 770.778,
        "end": 774.5840000000001,
        "text": "是我们可以打磨和改变 以满足我们需求的东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 775.7860000000001,
        "end": 780.119,
        "text": "不幸的是，这种语言多样性 正在不断丧失。"
      },
      {
        "start": 780.468,
        "end": 782.36,
        "text": "大概平均每个星期 就有一种语言消失，"
      },
      {
        "start": 782.384,
        "end": 783.85,
        "text": "据估计，"
      },
      {
        "start": 783.874,
        "end": 787.141,
        "text": "在接下来的100年里 世界上一半的语言将会消失。"
      },
      {
        "start": 787.966,
        "end": 790.692,
        "text": "更糟糕的是，现在"
      },
      {
        "start": 790.692,
        "end": 794.454,
        "text": "几乎我们所知道的 所有关于人类大脑和思维的东西"
      },
      {
        "start": 794.454,
        "end": 798.826,
        "text": "都是基于大学中说美式英语的"
      },
      {
        "start": 798.826,
        "end": 800.92,
        "text": "学生的研究。"
      },
      {
        "start": 802.742,
        "end": 806.259,
        "text": "这就几乎排除了所有人类，不是吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 806.259,
        "end": 811.264,
        "text": "所以其实我们对人类思维的了解 是非常狭隘和具有偏见的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 811.264,
        "end": 814.53,
        "text": "而我们的科学应该做得更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 817.987,
        "end": 820.24,
        "text": "最后，我想再让大家思考一个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 820.24,
        "end": 823.517,
        "text": "我已经讲了不同语言的使用者 思考的不同方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 823.517,
        "end": 827.035,
        "text": "当然，这不是是关于 其他地方的人怎么思考，"
      },
      {
        "start": 827.035,
        "end": 828.458,
        "text": "而是关于你怎么思考，"
      },
      {
        "start": 828.458,
        "end": 832.164,
        "text": "关于你说的语言 如何影响了你的思维方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 833.07,
        "end": 835.57,
        "text": "大家可以问问自己："
      },
      {
        "start": 835.57,
        "end": 837.725,
        "text": "“我为什么是这样思考问题的？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 837.725,
        "end": 839.361,
        "text": "“我能换种方式思考吗？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 839.908,
        "end": 841.237,
        "text": "还有，"
      },
      {
        "start": 841.237,
        "end": 843.024,
        "text": "“我想创造什么样的想法？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 843.842,
        "end": 844.935,
        "text": "非常感谢。"
      },
      {
        "start": 844.935,
        "end": 847.781,
        "text": "（鼓掌）"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to manage your emotions",
    "youtubeId": "Uew5BbvmLks",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "TED-Ed",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.961,
        "end": 11.507,
        "text": "你和你的朋友必须搞定 周五的考试才能逃过暑期课程，"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.799,
        "end": 16.095,
        "text": "学了一周以后， 你们都有信心能搞定。"
      },
      {
        "start": 16.471,
        "end": 18.097,
        "text": "但是拿到成绩后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.097,
        "end": 20.808,
        "text": "发现比你们俩想的要低得多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.017,
        "end": 22.226,
        "text": "你崩溃了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.393,
        "end": 25.354,
        "text": "但是你的朋友看起来若无其事，"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.354,
        "end": 29.275,
        "text": "所以你在思考为什么 你不能像他/她这样把它视作浮云。"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.525,
        "end": 32.695,
        "text": "但是你真的得保持乐观吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.695,
        "end": 36.949,
        "text": "说到底，真的有可能控制情绪吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.45,
        "end": 41.496,
        "text": "后面这个问题的答案就是“可以”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.788,
        "end": 44.957,
        "text": "有很多策略可以帮助你管理情绪，"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.957,
        "end": 49.837,
        "text": "有一个理解这些技巧的框架 称为“过程模式”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.962,
        "end": 54.467,
        "text": "心理学家利用这个工具判断 该在哪一个阶段、如何干预"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.467,
        "end": 57.011,
        "text": "形成情绪的过程。"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.22,
        "end": 59.722,
        "text": "这个过程有四步："
      },
      {
        "start": 59.722,
        "end": 63.476,
        "text": "首先，我们会进入一个情境， 可以是真实或是虚构的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.476,
        "end": 65.645,
        "text": "吸引了我们的注意。"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.062,
        "end": 69.732,
        "text": "然后我们会评估或评价这个情境，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.732,
        "end": 72.276,
        "text": "判断它是会帮助 还是阻碍我们达成目标。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.568,
        "end": 77.949,
        "text": "最终，这个评价会引起 我们感受、思考、行为的变化，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.324,
        "end": 81.41,
        "text": "即情绪反应。"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.911,
        "end": 86.791,
        "text": "这个过程的每一步都提供了 让你有意识地干预"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.791,
        "end": 88.751,
        "text": "和改变情绪的机会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.83500000000001,
        "end": 93.756,
        "text": "过程模式描述了每个阶段 可以采取什么样的策略。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.798,
        "end": 97.80199999999999,
        "text": "如果要看实际的效果， 假设你受邀参与一个派对，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.80199999999999,
        "end": 101.013,
        "text": "你最讨厌的前任和他/她的现任 也将出席。"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.26400000000001,
        "end": 105.56,
        "text": "你可以采取的第一个策略为 干脆避免这种情况的发生，"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.56,
        "end": 107.27000000000001,
        "text": "直接不去这个派对。"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.27000000000001,
        "end": 112.15,
        "text": "但是如果你出席了， 你也可以试图扭转局面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.15,
        "end": 114.98599999999999,
        "text": "只要不和你的前任 有任何互动就可以了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.11099999999999,
        "end": 119.07300000000001,
        "text": "如果这也很难， 你可以转移你的注意力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.07300000000001,
        "end": 121.117,
        "text": "也许和你的朋友玩玩游戏，"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.117,
        "end": 123.661,
        "text": "而不是死盯你前任的现任。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.87,
        "end": 128.916,
        "text": "另一个选项是重新评估 你对这个情况的看法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.125,
        "end": 131.294,
        "text": "在慎重的重新评估之后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.46,
        "end": 134.964,
        "text": "你可能会发现你根本不在乎 你的前任在和谁谈恋爱。"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.089,
        "end": 136.799,
        "text": "如果这些策略都没有用，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.841,
        "end": 141.596,
        "text": "你可以在情况发生之后 试着缓和自己的情绪反应，"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.929,
        "end": 143.264,
        "text": "但这有点棘手。"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.389,
        "end": 145.558,
        "text": "有很多简单的方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.558,
        "end": 150.47899999999998,
        "text": "比如隐藏自己的情绪， 或服用娱乐性药物改变情绪，"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.563,
        "end": 155.026,
        "text": "通常会带来更负面的感受， 也会长期影响健康。"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.31799999999998,
        "end": 159.447,
        "text": "更可持续的方法包括 长途步行、"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.447,
        "end": 164.202,
        "text": "缓慢地深呼吸，或者 和你情绪支持系统中的某人聊一聊。"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.41,
        "end": 167.663,
        "text": "虽然你需要通过实践 充分利用这些策略，"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.663,
        "end": 169.54,
        "text": "但是学会关注自己的情绪、"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.54,
        "end": 172.627,
        "text": "思考它们的来源 已经是成功的一半。"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.835,
        "end": 177.381,
        "text": "只要你彻底把管理情绪 融为自己的一部分，"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.465,
        "end": 179.46699999999998,
        "text": "那对你来说这就易如反掌了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.88400000000001,
        "end": 184.18,
        "text": "但是你该不该利用这些技巧 一直保持好心情呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.472,
        "end": 188.809,
        "text": "答案取决于 你如何定义“好”心情。"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.227,
        "end": 193.689,
        "text": "你很有可能会觉得 我们总是得避免悲伤和沮丧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.689,
        "end": 197.026,
        "text": "但是情绪本质上是没有好坏的——"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.318,
        "end": 201.405,
        "text": "只是在不同的场合下 它们可能是有益或无益的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.781,
        "end": 205.91,
        "text": "比如你的朋友告诉你 他/她失去了挚爱之人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.91,
        "end": 209.70499999999998,
        "text": "这时，感受、表达悲伤 不仅仅是合适的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.872,
        "end": 212.416,
        "text": "还能让你与他/她感同身受， 为他/她提供支持。"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.583,
        "end": 216.629,
        "text": "相对地，虽然总是 无视自己的情绪不太健康，"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.796,
        "end": 221.25900000000001,
        "text": "但为了忍耐一时的恼怒而假笑 是非常合理的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.26,
        "end": 225.471,
        "text": "人们对情绪众说纷纭。"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.68,
        "end": 228.099,
        "text": "有些人逼迫我们要保持乐观，"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.099,
        "end": 231.519,
        "text": "有些人告诉我们 情绪既来之，则安之，"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.727,
        "end": 235.564,
        "text": "但是实际情况是 每个人都得找到自己的平衡。"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.815,
        "end": 240.111,
        "text": "如果这么问： “你应该一直保持开心吗？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.111,
        "end": 241.32,
        "text": "答案是“不应该”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.32,
        "end": 244.282,
        "text": "研究表明，一直保持开心状态的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.282,
        "end": 246.909,
        "text": "通常会伴随着另一种负面情绪，"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.909,
        "end": 251.455,
        "text": "如因为感到沮丧 而产生的内疚和挫败感"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.455,
        "end": 254.125,
        "text": "和因为无法感到更快乐 而带来的失望。"
      },
      {
        "start": 254.417,
        "end": 257.962,
        "text": "这不代表你应该 沉浸于悲伤或愤怒中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.045,
        "end": 261.424,
        "text": "但是“重新审视”这样的策略 可以让你重新评估"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.424,
        "end": 263.551,
        "text": "你对某种情况的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.551,
        "end": 266.429,
        "text": "让你接受自己可以感到悲伤，"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.429,
        "end": 269.724,
        "text": "也培养希望，相信事情会变得更好。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Are we cooked? How social media shapes language",
    "youtubeId": "rmASLb_Yn5Y",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Adam Aleksic",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 4.786,
        "end": 9.502,
        "text": "有多少人知道“不让活”（unalive） 是“杀死”（kill）的同义词？"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.869,
        "end": 11.302,
        "text": "请举手。"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.236,
        "end": 14.802,
        "text": "OK，大概在座有八成。"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.202,
        "end": 17.569,
        "text": "很好，现在，让我再接着问各位。"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.586,
        "end": 20.869,
        "text": "有多少人在现实生活中 听过“不让活”这个词？"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.652,
        "end": 26.069,
        "text": "OK，大概 40%、50%。"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.652,
        "end": 27.802,
        "text": "很好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.836,
        "end": 31.852,
        "text": "没听过的显然不是中学老师。"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.202,
        "end": 33.352,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.819,
        "end": 36.669,
        "text": "如果你在七八年级的学生周围呆久了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.686,
        "end": 38.502,
        "text": "你就会听到他们使用这个词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.886,
        "end": 40.886,
        "text": "通常都是非正式场合，"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.902,
        "end": 47.402,
        "text": "但会出现在学生撰写有关哈姆雷特 思考“不让自己活”的作文中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.419,
        "end": 52.136,
        "text": "或者在关于《化身博士》中 “不让自己活”的课堂讨论里。"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.236,
        "end": 56.319,
        "text": "这些不是编出来的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.352,
        "end": 61.752,
        "text": "而是来自我向 1000 多名中学老师 调查这个词语而来的实际案例。"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.419,
        "end": 65.419,
        "text": "可能是我的小癖好吧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.436,
        "end": 67.569,
        "text": "显然，就这么新的一个词而言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.586,
        "end": 71.286,
        "text": "“不让活”会出现在各种各样的场合中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.30199999999999,
        "end": 74.05199999999999,
        "text": "但它主要的功能是委婉的表达。"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.602,
        "end": 78.636,
        "text": "很多孩子会在不想谈论 死亡这样的话题时使用这个词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.652,
        "end": 81.669,
        "text": "因为“不让活” 听起来不那么令人害怕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.686,
        "end": 83.586,
        "text": "这并不是一个新现象。"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.602,
        "end": 86.569,
        "text": "凡是涉及了语言， 我们都会委婉地表达死亡。"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.602,
        "end": 90.986,
        "text": "比如，“死亡”（decease） 源自拉丁语中的“decessus”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.002,
        "end": 94.636,
        "text": "再溯源到拉丁语中 “死亡”（mors）的委婉语。"
      },
      {
        "start": 95.786,
        "end": 97.386,
        "text": "显然，连情绪稳定的罗马人"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.419,
        "end": 100.769,
        "text": "都和当今的中学生一样 对死亡感到不安。"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.80199999999999,
        "end": 105.102,
        "text": "但是“不活”（unalive）和“死亡” （decease）截然不同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.136,
        "end": 107.336,
        "text": "我们只能使用“不让活”这个词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.352,
        "end": 109.519,
        "text": "这是因为 TikTok 上不让说“杀死”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.402,
        "end": 113.602,
        "text": "他们有一个神秘的算法， 可以删除或隐藏任何"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.636,
        "end": 115.886,
        "text": "可能违反社区规定的动态。"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.902,
        "end": 119.036,
        "text": "于是人们用“不让活” 绕开这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.05199999999999,
        "end": 121.052,
        "text": "中学生不知道。"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.086,
        "end": 123.352,
        "text": "他们在网上看到这个词 或从朋友那里听到这个词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.369,
        "end": 125.202,
        "text": "并假设这个词和其他词一样。"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.219,
        "end": 129.619,
        "text": "确实，你可能不知道 “已故”（deceased）这个词从何而来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.636,
        "end": 131.802,
        "text": "除非你是词源学的狂热爱好者。"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.819,
        "end": 132.952,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.969,
        "end": 134.802,
        "text": "但是“已故”（deceased）的出现"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.836,
        "end": 139.119,
        "text": "并不是因为古罗马碑文上 不可以写“死亡”（mors）这个词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.152,
        "end": 144.786,
        "text": "在社交媒体算法的推动下，我们 正在进入一个全新的语言变革时代。"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.536,
        "end": 149.252,
        "text": "作为一名语言学家和内容创作者，"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.269,
        "end": 152.369,
        "text": "我一直处于一个独特的位置 从内观察一切。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.236,
        "end": 154.386,
        "text": "太令人震惊了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.402,
        "end": 157.086,
        "text": "我经常感到自己的语言 受到了怎样的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.102,
        "end": 160.586,
        "text": "从回答我两个问题的 40％ 的观众来看，"
      },
      {
        "start": 160.619,
        "end": 162.902,
        "text": "这也会开始改变你的语言。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.66899999999998,
        "end": 166.869,
        "text": "不止为了逃避算法审查的新词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.886,
        "end": 170.56900000000002,
        "text": "社交媒体的结构本身 正在改变词语的来源、"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.586,
        "end": 173.869,
        "text": "风靡的方式和传播的速度。"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.16899999999998,
        "end": 178.219,
        "text": "我相信有些观众 会对这首歌很熟悉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.81900000000002,
        "end": 180.836,
        "text": "（清嗓子）"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.852,
        "end": 183.336,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 183.352,
        "end": 185.852,
        "text": "《‌Sticking Out Your Gyat for The Rizzler》。"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.886,
        "end": 187.536,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.552,
        "end": 191.669,
        "text": "“你太抽象了 / 你像 Fanum 偷吃一样离谱 /"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.452,
        "end": 194.086,
        "text": "我只想当你的高冷男神 /"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.836,
        "end": 197.786,
        "text": "快滚过来 / 给我整活”"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.802,
        "end": 200.236,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.886,
        "end": 202.469,
        "text": "（笑声）摸不着头脑的各位，"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.486,
        "end": 204.502,
        "text": "这些是 Rizzler 这首歌的歌词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 204.519,
        "end": 207.519,
        "text": "去年无比火爆的一个梗。"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.536,
        "end": 209.819,
        "text": "充满了现在中学生的流行语，"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.836,
        "end": 212.636,
        "text": "比如“性张力”（rizz）、 “翘臀”（gyat）、“抽象”（skibidi），"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.652,
        "end": 216.41899999999998,
        "text": "在向更广泛的受众普及这些词上 发挥了重要作用。"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.586,
        "end": 222.052,
        "text": "这是因为社交媒体的算法 会奖励口口相传。"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.086,
        "end": 225.56900000000002,
        "text": "如果一首歌有意思或抓耳， 人们和它互动，"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.586,
        "end": 228.336,
        "text": "那么算法会把它推送给更多的人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.352,
        "end": 230.902,
        "text": "因为它确实可以提高这个 app 的互动度。"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.136,
        "end": 235.086,
        "text": "梗图或流行语也是如此，"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.102,
        "end": 237.052,
        "text": "因为热度数据，比如热门话题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.06900000000002,
        "end": 241.336,
        "text": "也会被推送给之前对类似内容 展现出兴趣的人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.352,
        "end": 244.052,
        "text": "创作者对此非常了解，"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.086,
        "end": 248.652,
        "text": "我们会积极使用流行的音频或话题 来让我们的视频数据更好看。"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.619,
        "end": 251.902,
        "text": "比如在 Rizzler 那首歌之后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.919,
        "end": 257.469,
        "text": "把 “rizz”、“gyat”、“skibidi” 制作进视频的人数激增，"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.486,
        "end": 260.202,
        "text": "因为他们知道这些视频 会有很好的数据。"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.519,
        "end": 264.086,
        "text": "于是口口相传。"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.636,
        "end": 268.852,
        "text": "语言一直有点像病毒。"
      },
      {
        "start": 268.869,
        "end": 271.169,
        "text": "词语从一个宿主传播到另一个宿主，"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.186,
        "end": 275.952,
        "text": "在感染社交网络中的不同人时 繁殖和变化。"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.969,
        "end": 279.019,
        "text": "但现在，社交媒体的病毒性质"
      },
      {
        "start": 279.052,
        "end": 282.252,
        "text": "正在彻彻底底加速这一过程。"
      },
      {
        "start": 283.136,
        "end": 285.302,
        "text": "在短短一年的时间里，"
      },
      {
        "start": 285.336,
        "end": 288.052,
        "text": "像 “rizz” 这样的词 可以从不为人知"
      },
      {
        "start": 288.069,
        "end": 291.236,
        "text": "变成牛津英语词典的年度词汇。"
      },
      {
        "start": 291.252,
        "end": 294.302,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.602,
        "end": 297.086,
        "text": "算法是罪魁祸首，"
      },
      {
        "start": 297.119,
        "end": 299.752,
        "text": "但网红是帮凶。"
      },
      {
        "start": 300.652,
        "end": 303.786,
        "text": "我们不择手段地讨你欢心，"
      },
      {
        "start": 303.819,
        "end": 307.619,
        "text": "因为这会让我们的视频数据更好， 让我们可以谋生。"
      },
      {
        "start": 308.336,
        "end": 313.202,
        "text": "意味着我们最终会创造和传播 助长整个系统的词语。"
      },
      {
        "start": 314.486,
        "end": 316.702,
        "text": "比如，后缀 “XX 风”（-core），"
      },
      {
        "start": 316.719,
        "end": 318.986,
        "text": "最近在 Z 世代中风靡，"
      },
      {
        "start": 319.019,
        "end": 321.186,
        "text": "用于描述某些美学风格，"
      },
      {
        "start": 321.202,
        "end": 325.686,
        "text": "如“田园风”（cottagecore）、“地精风” （goblincore）或“天使风”（angelcore）。"
      },
      {
        "start": 326.169,
        "end": 328.836,
        "text": "乍一看还挺可爱的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 328.852,
        "end": 329.869,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 329.886,
        "end": 332.719,
        "text": "你看了田园风的视频， 你很喜欢。"
      },
      {
        "start": 332.752,
        "end": 335.736,
        "text": "之后就会刷到越来越多的田园风内容。"
      },
      {
        "start": 335.752,
        "end": 339.552,
        "text": "你甚至可能开始认同田园风美学。"
      },
      {
        "start": 341.169,
        "end": 344.336,
        "text": "但问题是这些都是假的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 344.369,
        "end": 346.569,
        "text": "这些美学之所以存在的唯一原因"
      },
      {
        "start": 346.586,
        "end": 352.419,
        "text": "是因为 TikTok 算法认定 “田园风”这样的词属于热度数据，"
      },
      {
        "start": 352.436,
        "end": 356.419,
        "text": "于是创作者会创作 更多的田园风内容来传播这个词，"
      },
      {
        "start": 356.452,
        "end": 359.802,
        "text": "更多人与之互动， 让这个词更流行了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 359.836,
        "end": 362.119,
        "text": "出现这种情况是因为社交媒体算法"
      },
      {
        "start": 362.136,
        "end": 365.636,
        "text": "想让你认同高度细分的标签，"
      },
      {
        "start": 365.652,
        "end": 370.719,
        "text": "这样他们就能给你迎合这一标签的 极具针对性、商业化的内容。"
      },
      {
        "start": 370.752,
        "end": 373.552,
        "text": "你是一个喜欢田园风的人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 373.569,
        "end": 376.536,
        "text": "每次刷到田园风， 你都会觉得自己很特别。"
      },
      {
        "start": 377.102,
        "end": 379.419,
        "text": "你会想：田园风……"
      },
      {
        "start": 379.436,
        "end": 381.352,
        "text": "算法真的很懂我。"
      },
      {
        "start": 381.369,
        "end": 382.369,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 382.402,
        "end": 384.969,
        "text": "算法给了你这个标签。"
      },
      {
        "start": 385.819,
        "end": 389.719,
        "text": "你甚至会开始购买 田园风的衣服或装饰，"
      },
      {
        "start": 389.736,
        "end": 392.286,
        "text": "这样可以让你更符合 “田园风的人”的全新生活方式，"
      },
      {
        "start": 392.302,
        "end": 393.952,
        "text": "而这正是他们想要的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 395.052,
        "end": 398.769,
        "text": "最令人震撼的是 他们毫不掩饰这一企图。"
      },
      {
        "start": 398.786,
        "end": 400.636,
        "text": "TikTok 的商业平台"
      },
      {
        "start": 400.669,
        "end": 404.602,
        "text": "公开声称亚文化就是新的目标群体，"
      },
      {
        "start": 404.636,
        "end": 409.452,
        "text": "还就如何从田园风美学中 赚取收益提供了商业思路。"
      },
      {
        "start": 410.186,
        "end": 414.186,
        "text": "他们其实是在批量制造 让人产生认同的标签，"
      },
      {
        "start": 414.202,
        "end": 415.936,
        "text": "借此赚我们所有人的钱。"
      },
      {
        "start": 419.219,
        "end": 423.386,
        "text": "虽然喜欢 TikTok 上的 田园风无可厚非，"
      },
      {
        "start": 423.402,
        "end": 427.836,
        "text": "它是一个认可你田园风个性的信息茧房。"
      },
      {
        "start": 428.219,
        "end": 431.286,
        "text": "社交媒体上创建的 所有小众社区都是如此。"
      },
      {
        "start": 431.302,
        "end": 433.536,
        "text": "一方面，这对语言学非常有利，"
      },
      {
        "start": 433.552,
        "end": 437.086,
        "text": "因为语言变革总是 由具有共同兴趣的群体推动的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 437.119,
        "end": 439.319,
        "text": "他们有着创造新词语的共同需求。"
      },
      {
        "start": 439.752,
        "end": 441.852,
        "text": "比如，“不活”（unalive）流传开来"
      },
      {
        "start": 441.886,
        "end": 444.052,
        "text": "是因为 TikTok 上的心理健康社区"
      },
      {
        "start": 444.086,
        "end": 447.169,
        "text": "需要一种分享故事和传播资源的方法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 448.252,
        "end": 449.402,
        "text": "另一方面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 449.436,
        "end": 453.852,
        "text": "由算法创建的一些语言学社区 会不断创造危害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 454.302,
        "end": 458.319,
        "text": "很多年轻人开始使用 “XX 上头”（-pilled）的后缀，"
      },
      {
        "start": 458.336,
        "end": 460.786,
        "text": "表达“接纳某种生活方式”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 462.202,
        "end": 466.802,
        "text": "假如最近我发现我很喜欢 吃墨西哥卷饼（burrito），"
      },
      {
        "start": 466.819,
        "end": 469.586,
        "text": "我可以说我太“墨西哥卷饼上头” （burrito-pilled）了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 471.136,
        "end": 473.969,
        "text": "但这个词由 black-pilled 的比喻而来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 473.986,
        "end": 476.869,
        "text": "意思是“接纳非自愿独身者的观念” （类似“屌丝”）。"
      },
      {
        "start": 477.902,
        "end": 481.002,
        "text": "非自愿独身者是个危险、厌女的群体。"
      },
      {
        "start": 481.036,
        "end": 483.436,
        "text": "他们实施了多起恐怖袭击，"
      },
      {
        "start": 483.469,
        "end": 485.402,
        "text": "造成数十人死亡，"
      },
      {
        "start": 485.419,
        "end": 488.486,
        "text": "但他们的词汇流入了 Z 世代的流行语中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 488.519,
        "end": 491.352,
        "text": "因为算法为这些仇恨群体提供了空间。"
      },
      {
        "start": 493.036,
        "end": 496.752,
        "text": "我喜欢看城市设计的视频，"
      },
      {
        "start": 496.769,
        "end": 500.352,
        "text": "几个月前，我刷到了一条视频说"
      },
      {
        "start": 500.369,
        "end": 502.952,
        "text": "当一个“停车场上头的 人行道公主”有多爽。"
      },
      {
        "start": 502.969,
        "end": 505.402,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 505.419,
        "end": 508.636,
        "text": "我确实觉得这个视频很好玩， 我挺喜欢的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 508.652,
        "end": 513.169,
        "text": "结果我刷到了更多城市设计 非自愿独身者主题的玩梗视频，"
      },
      {
        "start": 513.202,
        "end": 516.436,
        "text": "有个视频是化石燃料上头， 对骸骨不好，"
      },
      {
        "start": 516.452,
        "end": 519.186,
        "text": "还有一个视频是 暴走上头的疯狂有氧运动人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 519.202,
        "end": 524.2860000000001,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 524.319,
        "end": 530.152,
        "text": "好多人同样会在讽刺 或玩梗语境中遇到这些词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 531.086,
        "end": 533.386,
        "text": "我们再来看看 Rizzler 那首歌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 534.119,
        "end": 540.002,
        "text": "歌词“我只想当你的高冷男神（sigma）” 指的是“西格玛男性”这一概念，"
      },
      {
        "start": 540.036,
        "end": 544.636,
        "text": "非自愿独身者用它来描述 他们在社会层级以外的理想地位。"
      },
      {
        "start": 545.669,
        "end": 549.402,
        "text": "同样，乍一看这个梗很好玩。"
      },
      {
        "start": 549.419,
        "end": 550.686,
        "text": "它没有错。"
      },
      {
        "start": 550.702,
        "end": 553.319,
        "text": "许多人甚至不知道它出自哪里。"
      },
      {
        "start": 553.352,
        "end": 557.5360000000001,
        "text": "但对于少数对背后深意感兴趣的人来说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 557.569,
        "end": 563.236,
        "text": "由于流行语在网上散播的方式， 他们更容易获取这些内容。"
      },
      {
        "start": 563.252,
        "end": 566.719,
        "text": "它从社交媒体的某个角落开始， 变成了病毒式的梗，"
      },
      {
        "start": 566.752,
        "end": 570.502,
        "text": "久而久之， 很多人就不知道它的词源了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 572.2860000000001,
        "end": 575.969,
        "text": "这不仅让这些社区伤害我们，"
      },
      {
        "start": 576.002,
        "end": 578.436,
        "text": "我们也会伤害社区。"
      },
      {
        "start": 579.369,
        "end": 584.402,
        "text": "产生流行语的两大主要群体 是同性恋和黑人社区，"
      },
      {
        "start": 584.436,
        "end": 588.2860000000001,
        "text": "因为边缘化群体一直 将语言用作夺回权力的方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 589.169,
        "end": 592.486,
        "text": "所有最流行的网络流行语，"
      },
      {
        "start": 592.502,
        "end": 595.2860000000001,
        "text": "“秒杀”（slay）、“绝了”（serve）、"
      },
      {
        "start": 595.319,
        "end": 598.102,
        "text": "“牛逼”（bussin）、“女王”（queen）、 “完蛋”（cooked）、"
      },
      {
        "start": 598.102,
        "end": 600.869,
        "text": "“碾压”（ate）、“翘臀”（gyat）等词语"
      },
      {
        "start": 600.902,
        "end": 602.802,
        "text": "都来自酷儿或黑人文化。"
      },
      {
        "start": 603.236,
        "end": 605.919,
        "text": "这些词语作为一种创意表达而起源，"
      },
      {
        "start": 605.936,
        "end": 609.202,
        "text": "区别于异性恋白人群体的英语用词。"
      },
      {
        "start": 609.736,
        "end": 611.969,
        "text": "但是，当人们开始在网上使用这些词时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 612.002,
        "end": 618.269,
        "text": "它们很快就会被想借黑人或酷儿文化的 酷炫或喜剧效果牟利的人利用。"
      },
      {
        "start": 618.969,
        "end": 620.569,
        "text": "“翘臀”（gyat）这个词"
      },
      {
        "start": 620.586,
        "end": 624.602,
        "text": "起源于非裔美国人读 “该死”（goddamn）的英语发音，"
      },
      {
        "start": 624.619,
        "end": 628.602,
        "text": "再转变为这首歌之类的流行梗里 出现的“翘臀”的名词含义时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 628.636,
        "end": 633.002,
        "text": "效果就被大大增强了， 让这个词的发音和含义变成了笑话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 633.019,
        "end": 636.369,
        "text": "它的风靡削弱了它原有的重要性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 636.386,
        "end": 641.386,
        "text": "满嘴 “gyat” 的中学生 一定都不知道它的词源。"
      },
      {
        "start": 642.602,
        "end": 645.936,
        "text": "不幸的是，就像“不活” 这一委婉说法并不新鲜，"
      },
      {
        "start": 645.952,
        "end": 648.836,
        "text": "挪用非裔美国人英语也不新鲜。"
      },
      {
        "start": 649.452,
        "end": 651.669,
        "text": "从说着“酷”（cool）和 “击掌”（high five）的时代起，"
      },
      {
        "start": 651.669,
        "end": 653.886,
        "text": "我们就一直在把黑人流行语 强行带入白人社会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 653.902,
        "end": 656.202,
        "text": "此时此刻， 这两个词已经被广泛使用，"
      },
      {
        "start": 656.236,
        "end": 658.369,
        "text": "和普通词汇无异。"
      },
      {
        "start": 658.386,
        "end": 661.469,
        "text": "但同样，社交媒体算法"
      },
      {
        "start": 661.502,
        "end": 666.436,
        "text": "就是彻彻底底 创造和加速这个过程的载体。"
      },
      {
        "start": 666.452,
        "end": 670.269,
        "text": "它们创建的社区 让人感觉有使用自己词汇的空间，"
      },
      {
        "start": 670.302,
        "end": 672.019,
        "text": "再开放这些社区，"
      },
      {
        "start": 672.036,
        "end": 674.319,
        "text": "正好可以让这些词语传播开来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 674.336,
        "end": 675.736,
        "text": "这就是“不活”的来源。"
      },
      {
        "start": 676.336,
        "end": 678.319,
        "text": "这就是“田园风”的来源。"
      },
      {
        "start": 678.702,
        "end": 682.019,
        "text": "这就是“高冷男神”、 “翘臀”的来源。"
      },
      {
        "start": 684.386,
        "end": 688.086,
        "text": "每次我发布这些话题的视频，"
      },
      {
        "start": 688.102,
        "end": 690.419,
        "text": "我都必然会收到一条评论。"
      },
      {
        "start": 691.502,
        "end": 693.102,
        "text": "“我们‘药丸’。” （We’re so cooked.）"
      },
      {
        "start": 693.119,
        "end": 695.302,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 695.319,
        "end": 697.119,
        "text": "意思是“我们要完蛋了”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 697.886,
        "end": 701.552,
        "text": "讽刺的是，这也是一个来自 非裔美国人英语的 TikTok 流行语，"
      },
      {
        "start": 701.569,
        "end": 702.919,
        "text": "但我想说说这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 703.902,
        "end": 705.686,
        "text": "我们真的“药丸”吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 705.702,
        "end": 707.569,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 708.186,
        "end": 712.2860000000001,
        "text": "我知道我刚为英语的未来 描绘了一幅悲惨的图景，"
      },
      {
        "start": 712.302,
        "end": 715.069,
        "text": "还会出现很多让人担忧的流行趋势。"
      },
      {
        "start": 715.102,
        "end": 720.319,
        "text": "但这些趋势都遵循着 我们反复看到的历史模式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 721.819,
        "end": 725.819,
        "text": "我认为我们不会落入 《1984》中的反乌托邦情景，"
      },
      {
        "start": 725.836,
        "end": 729.602,
        "text": "因为我们不断找到 绕过媒体审查的新方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 729.619,
        "end": 730.769,
        "text": "如果一个词被禁了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 730.802,
        "end": 733.919,
        "text": "我们就会想出另一个词， 就像“不活”那样。"
      },
      {
        "start": 735.052,
        "end": 738.502,
        "text": "我认为中学生也不会 心智退化（brain rot），"
      },
      {
        "start": 738.519,
        "end": 742.586,
        "text": "因为年轻人们总是想 靠新的流行语建立身份认同，"
      },
      {
        "start": 742.619,
        "end": 746.136,
        "text": "而老一辈总是说： “啊，你这是要毁了英语。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 746.152,
        "end": 749.552,
        "text": "但是，就像过去那些 说着“酷”和“击掌”的人一样，"
      },
      {
        "start": 749.586,
        "end": 751.619,
        "text": "说着“性张力”、“翘臀”、 “马桶人”的中学生"
      },
      {
        "start": 751.619,
        "end": 753.419,
        "text": "并不会丧失写作文的能力。"
      },
      {
        "start": 753.836,
        "end": 758.502,
        "text": "我认为我们语言的商业化 并没有破坏我们的词汇。"
      },
      {
        "start": 758.686,
        "end": 762.752,
        "text": "我们已经在日常对话中使用 像 Kleenex 和 Google 这样的品牌名称，"
      },
      {
        "start": 762.752,
        "end": 766.202,
        "text": "所以“田园风”也不会 让我们变成无脑的消费者机器。"
      },
      {
        "start": 766.202,
        "end": 769.236,
        "text": "我甚至不认为我们在冒着危险 正常接纳非自愿独身者的言论。"
      },
      {
        "start": 769.236,
        "end": 772.952,
        "text": "非要说的话，我们的流行语基于 人们对非自愿独身者想法的一致嘲讽。"
      },
      {
        "start": 773.936,
        "end": 777.836,
        "text": "一个孩子说“我太 ‘墨西哥卷饼上头’了”这样的话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 777.852,
        "end": 780.452,
        "text": "并不是因为他们愿意接受 非自愿独身者的观念，"
      },
      {
        "start": 780.486,
        "end": 784.086,
        "text": "而是因为背后的意图是 想打趣非自愿独身者说话的方式。"
      },
      {
        "start": 784.102,
        "end": 788.636,
        "text": "我其实觉得这些词都为英语 带来了丰富多彩的增色，"
      },
      {
        "start": 788.652,
        "end": 791.552,
        "text": "反映了我们身处的多元文化时刻。"
      },
      {
        "start": 791.869,
        "end": 794.936,
        "text": "但我确实认为我们得保持警惕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 794.952,
        "end": 797.069,
        "text": "我们得警惕我们的说话方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 797.086,
        "end": 799.269,
        "text": "可能会受到算法的操纵。"
      },
      {
        "start": 800.069,
        "end": 802.969,
        "text": "我们得警惕我们使用的词语"
      },
      {
        "start": 802.986,
        "end": 805.802,
        "text": "可能是为了向我们推销东西 而有意设计的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 805.819,
        "end": 809.119,
        "text": "我们得警惕我们的用语 在复刻极端分子的言论。"
      },
      {
        "start": 809.136,
        "end": 813.369,
        "text": "我们得警惕语言被用于伤害他人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 813.686,
        "end": 815.719,
        "text": "我们得了解词源，"
      },
      {
        "start": 815.736,
        "end": 818.602,
        "text": "因为它可以让我们更好地理解 此刻的我们是谁。"
      },
      {
        "start": 819.386,
        "end": 820.719,
        "text": "我们得保持警惕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 822.019,
        "end": 824.986,
        "text": "我有最后一条流行语要送给大家。"
      },
      {
        "start": 825.019,
        "end": 830.252,
        "text": "这是年轻人在说完长篇大论后 常用的词组，"
      },
      {
        "start": 830.869,
        "end": 832.552,
        "text": "“感谢你听我的 TED 演讲。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 832.569,
        "end": 835.5360000000001,
        "text": "（欢呼和掌声）"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Ethos, Pathos, Logos",
    "youtubeId": "2ey232I5nUk",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "TED-Ed",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 0.03,
        "end": 3.78,
        "text": "In this video, we're going to talk about three related concepts from Aristotle."
      },
      {
        "start": 3.78,
        "end": 9.09,
        "text": "Ethos, pathos, and logos. And if you have not yet been exposed to this kind of"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.09,
        "end": 13.78,
        "text": "material, it will absolutely help you take your next presentation up a notch."
      },
      {
        "start": 13.8,
        "end": 16.2,
        "text": "So, let's get into it."
      },
      {
        "start": 20.4,
        "end": 24.52,
        "text": "Hello again friends. I'm Alex Lyon and if you've never subscribed to Communication"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.539,
        "end": 29.25,
        "text": "Coach, this channel, I encourage you to do so. This channel is here for rising"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.25,
        "end": 33.36,
        "text": "leaders, people like you to help you increase your personal impact so you can"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.36,
        "end": 37.53,
        "text": "lead the people around you to higher levels of excellence. And one of the ways"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.53,
        "end": 40.92,
        "text": "we do this on the channel is by [looking at] presentation skills. And today we're"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.92,
        "end": 45.629,
        "text": "going to look at three related concepts: Ethos, Pathos, and Logos. These have, even"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.629,
        "end": 48.899,
        "text": "though they're textbook type concepts, they have direct application for you as"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.899,
        "end": 52.71,
        "text": "a speaker. And you can use these right away. So let's unpack these each and show"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.71,
        "end": 56.52,
        "text": "you how you can apply them. The first is ethos. And that means your"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.52,
        "end": 62.85,
        "text": "personal credibility as a speaker. A lot of times people think that because ethos"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.85,
        "end": 67.38,
        "text": "looks like the word ethics, that's all it means. And that's part of it. Abviously as"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.38,
        "end": 71.82,
        "text": "a speaker you have to have good character. You also, however, have to be an"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.82,
        "end": 76.92,
        "text": "expert. You have to have credentials. You have to be qualified to speak in a way"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.92,
        "end": 81.9,
        "text": "that people would want to listen to you. Very few of us have a public reputation"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.9,
        "end": 86.34,
        "text": "already. And so one of the ways you can do this in your presentations is if"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.34,
        "end": 90.18,
        "text": "you're being introduced by somebody before you speak, make sure the person"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.18,
        "end": 93.81,
        "text": "introducing you has a little bit of information about your background so"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.81,
        "end": 97.38,
        "text": "they can position you as someone worth listening to. If you don't have someone"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.38,
        "end": 101.43,
        "text": "introducing you, then you want to talk about any research that you've done to"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.43,
        "end": 105.18,
        "text": "prepare for this presentation, any personal experience or connection that"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.18,
        "end": 108.42,
        "text": "you have to the topic. You want to position yourself as someone that has"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.42,
        "end": 112.47,
        "text": "ethos, someone that has the credibility, the believability so that people will"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.47,
        "end": 116.46000000000001,
        "text": "want to listen to you. And you can almost always do this right in the introduction"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.46000000000001,
        "end": 121.59,
        "text": "of your presentation. Let's turn now to pathos. Pathos is where the speaker"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.59,
        "end": 127.5,
        "text": "appeals to the emotions of the listeners. So, you want to use things like vivid"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.5,
        "end": 132.599,
        "text": "language, metaphors, and probably the most effective way that we can reach into the"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.599,
        "end": 136.26,
        "text": "hearts of our listeners is through personal stories. You can tell"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.26,
        "end": 139.47,
        "text": "stories about your own personal experiences or you can tell stories"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.47,
        "end": 144.239,
        "text": "about other people's experiences. There's nothing like a story to engage our"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.239,
        "end": 150.03,
        "text": "hearts and get us personally involved in it. It's almost like a story transports us"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.03,
        "end": 154.59,
        "text": "into the moment. And that's a great way to appeal to your audience's emotions. So"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.59,
        "end": 158.909,
        "text": "when you're presenting next, make sure as you're looking at your outline that you"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.909,
        "end": 162.81,
        "text": "have enough personal examples and little stories to bring people into that"
      },
      {
        "start": 162.81,
        "end": 166.769,
        "text": "emotional dimension of your presentation. So now let's talk about logos. Logos,"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.769,
        "end": 170.519,
        "text": "because it looks like the word logic, a lot of people think, oh that just means"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.519,
        "end": 174.18,
        "text": "logic. But there's a lot more to it than that. In fact, you want to think about it"
      },
      {
        "start": 174.18,
        "end": 180.209,
        "text": "in terms of using evidence and reason to construct your speech [argument]. You want to"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.209,
        "end": 186.0,
        "text": "develop your presentation around a series of facts and statistics and good"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.0,
        "end": 189.989,
        "text": "reasonable evidence. And one of the ways you can do this in a presentation and"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.989,
        "end": 194.73,
        "text": "make it work for you, is make sure you have a tight relationship between your"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.73,
        "end": 198.15,
        "text": "claim, that's your thesis, the thing you're trying to demonstrate, and the"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.15,
        "end": 201.54,
        "text": "evidence you are using. If you're claiming one thing and then you have to"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.54,
        "end": 205.739,
        "text": "stretch your evidence to fit it. People are going to start to notice that and"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.739,
        "end": 209.34,
        "text": "they're not going to be as willing to be brought along or convinced by your"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.34,
        "end": 213.239,
        "text": "message. So make sure you're thorough in your research and you integrate that"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.239,
        "end": 216.54,
        "text": "good high-quality research into your presentation. Then your presentation will"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.54,
        "end": 220.949,
        "text": "have good logos. So that way you have ethos, pathos, and logos you're going to"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.949,
        "end": 225.54,
        "text": "be way more persuasive overall as a speaker. Question of the day. What are"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.54,
        "end": 229.53,
        "text": "your thoughts about how to establish any of these three in your next presentation?"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.53,
        "end": 233.25,
        "text": "I would love to hear your comments and your tips below. I learn a lot from"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.25,
        "end": 237.15,
        "text": "reading your comments. So I look forward to reading those in the future. So thanks."
      },
      {
        "start": 237.15,
        "end": 241.159,
        "text": "God bless. And I will see you in the next video."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "The common character trait of geniuses",
    "youtubeId": "Ym6whrAw8wU",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "James Gleick",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 0.51,
        "end": 8.81,
        "text": "I'm tempted to say smart, creative people have no particularly different set of character"
      },
      {
        "start": 8.81,
        "end": 13.58,
        "text": "traits than the rest of us except for being smart and creative, and those being character"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.58,
        "end": 14.58,
        "text": "traits."
      },
      {
        "start": 14.58,
        "end": 18.59,
        "text": "Then, on the other hand, I wrote a biography of Richard Feynman and a biography of Isaac"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.59,
        "end": 19.59,
        "text": "Newton."
      },
      {
        "start": 19.59,
        "end": 27.69,
        "text": "Now, there are two great scientific geniuses whose characters were in some superficial"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.69,
        "end": 30.279,
        "text": "ways completely different."
      },
      {
        "start": 30.279,
        "end": 44.909,
        "text": "Isaac Newton was solitary, antisocial, I think unpleasant, bitter, fought with his friends"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.909,
        "end": 46.679,
        "text": "as much as with his enemies."
      },
      {
        "start": 46.679,
        "end": 57.719,
        "text": "Richard Feynman was gregarious, funny, a great dancer, loved women."
      },
      {
        "start": 57.719,
        "end": 65.03,
        "text": "Isaac Newton, I believe, never had sex. Richard Feynman, I believe, had plenty."
      },
      {
        "start": 65.03,
        "end": 66.6,
        "text": "So you can't generalize there."
      },
      {
        "start": 66.6,
        "end": 75.55,
        "text": "On the other hand, they were both, as I tried to get in their heads, understand their minds,"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.55,
        "end": 80.87,
        "text": "the nature of their genius, I sort of felt I was seeing things that they had in common,"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.87,
        "end": 86.57,
        "text": "and they were things that had to do with aloneness."
      },
      {
        "start": 86.57,
        "end": 91.14,
        "text": "Newton was much more obviously alone than Feynman, but Feynman didn't particularly work"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.14,
        "end": 94.77000000000001,
        "text": "well with others."
      },
      {
        "start": 94.77000000000001,
        "end": 99.22,
        "text": "He was known as a great teacher, but he wasn't a great teacher, I don't think, one on one."
      },
      {
        "start": 99.22,
        "end": 103.28,
        "text": "I think he was a great lecturer. I think he was a great communicator."
      },
      {
        "start": 103.28,
        "end": 111.97,
        "text": "But when it came time to make the great discoveries of science, he was alone in his head."
      },
      {
        "start": 111.97,
        "end": 118.36,
        "text": "Now, when I say he, I mean both Feynman and Newton, and this applies, also, I think, to"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.36,
        "end": 127.78,
        "text": "the geniuses that I write about in The Information, Charles Babbage, Alan Turing, Ada Byron."
      },
      {
        "start": 127.78,
        "end": 136.439,
        "text": "They all had the ability to concentrate with a sort of intensity that is hard for mortals"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.439,
        "end": 149.84,
        "text": "like me to grasp, a kind of passion for abstraction that doesn't lend itself to easy communication,"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.84,
        "end": 151.59,
        "text": "I don't think."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How some friendships last—and others don't",
    "youtubeId": "kOVdiDUlNsg",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Iseult Gillespie",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.961,
        "end": 8.463,
        "text": "在2008年的一项研究中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 8.463,
        "end": 12.508,
        "text": "心理学家要求参与者 对山丘的陡度进行评分。"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.967,
        "end": 15.428,
        "text": "那些有好朋友陪同的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.428,
        "end": 19.515,
        "text": "认为这座山没有独自一人的人那么陡峭。"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.308,
        "end": 24.479,
        "text": "这只是友谊可以改变我们看待和"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.479,
        "end": 25.646,
        "text": "穿越世界的方式的众多方式之一。"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.98,
        "end": 28.524,
        "text": "友谊可以提高我们的学习成绩，"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.524,
        "end": 32.361,
        "text": "帮助我们应对挫折，甚至改善我们的健康状况。"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.904,
        "end": 36.699,
        "text": "我们在童年和青少年时期形成的关系"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.699,
        "end": 40.495,
        "text": "可以塑造我们的信念、价值观和情感成长。"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.828,
        "end": 43.081,
        "text": "很明显，友谊很重要，"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.081,
        "end": 47.001,
        "text": "但是结交和保持朋友并不总是那么容易。"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.251,
        "end": 48.753,
        "text": "让我们从头开始。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.753,
        "end": 52.59,
        "text": "如果您在结识新朋友方面遇到困难， 那么您并不孤单。"
      },
      {
        "start": 52.84,
        "end": 56.969,
        "text": "在一系列研究中，参与者"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.969,
        "end": 58.179,
        "text": "与陌生人进行了不同长度的对话。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.179,
        "end": 61.265,
        "text": "之后，他们被要求估计他们认为"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.265,
        "end": 62.85,
        "text": "每个陌生人有多喜欢他们。"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.267,
        "end": 67.063,
        "text": "总体而言，参与者对自己的好感度的评价"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.063,
        "end": 70.358,
        "text": "远低于其他人对他们的实际评价。"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.858,
        "end": 74.57,
        "text": "科学家们将这种低估其他人对我们公司的"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.57,
        "end": 77.406,
        "text": "喜好程度的趋势称为 “喜好差距”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 77.74,
        "end": 79.65899999999999,
        "text": "因此，在结识新朋友之前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.65899999999999,
        "end": 82.328,
        "text": "振作起来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.328,
        "end": 85.623,
        "text": "记住其他人比你想象的 更喜欢你可能会有所帮助。"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.082,
        "end": 89.418,
        "text": "你甚至可能想进入这些对话，"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.418,
        "end": 91.42,
        "text": "假设对方会喜欢你。"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.754,
        "end": 94.257,
        "text": "被稱為 “接受預言” 的"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.257,
        "end": 97.67699999999999,
        "text": "心理学家被称为 “接受预言”，他们发现， 当人们期望得到好评时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.88499999999999,
        "end": 102.39,
        "text": "他们往往会在不知不觉中表现得更温暖、更友好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.64,
        "end": 106.936,
        "text": "而且，你遇到的新朋友越多，你可能会感到越自信。"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.35300000000001,
        "end": 112.191,
        "text": "在一项研究中，一周内每天只与一个新朋友交谈的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.275,
        "end": 114.86099999999999,
        "text": "报告说，他们不那么害怕被拒绝，对话技巧"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.11099999999999,
        "end": 117.697,
        "text": "更加安全，总体而言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.697,
        "end": 120.908,
        "text": "结识新朋友更加兴奋。"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.45,
        "end": 125.621,
        "text": "接下来，当人际关系从偶然的熟人发展成知己时"
      },
      {
        "start": 125.621,
        "end": 126.956,
        "text": "会发生什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.331,
        "end": 131.878,
        "text": "心理学家已经确定了更亲密友谊的两个关键特征："
      },
      {
        "start": 132.086,
        "end": 134.255,
        "text": "友谊和亲密关系。"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.547,
        "end": 138.176,
        "text": "陪伴关系被定义为具有相似爱好，"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.176,
        "end": 142.388,
        "text": "兴趣或价值观的人之间形成的融洽关系或理解。"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.597,
        "end": 146.184,
        "text": "有时，只要在同一个班级或团队中就足"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.184,
        "end": 147.685,
        "text": "以建立这种联系。"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.768,
        "end": 150.605,
        "text": "陪伴有很多好处——事实证明，"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.688,
        "end": 156.06799999999998,
        "text": "它可以提高自尊心并增强我们对压力的抵御能力。"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.235,
        "end": 160.489,
        "text": "另一方面，每种关系的亲密关系看起来都不一样。"
      },
      {
        "start": 160.74,
        "end": 164.16,
        "text": "这可能意味着在困难时期互相支持，"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.243,
        "end": 167.45499999999998,
        "text": "或者乐于分享自己的想法和感受。"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.70499999999998,
        "end": 172.126,
        "text": "但是，并非每一次友谊都必须是深刻的个人化的， 尤其是刚开始的时候。"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.293,
        "end": 175.755,
        "text": "简单地将您的一天告诉朋友或分享您的兴趣"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.796,
        "end": 177.673,
        "text": "可以帮助建立亲密关系。"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.965,
        "end": 180.843,
        "text": "虽然每一次友谊都有自己的时间表发展，"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.843,
        "end": 182.595,
        "text": "但一致性会有所帮助，"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.678,
        "end": 186.474,
        "text": "这可能包括坚持计划、定期聊天"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.515,
        "end": 189.352,
        "text": "以及记住彼此重要的事情。"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.56,
        "end": 192.563,
        "text": "即使是长途友谊也是如此。"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.688,
        "end": 196.609,
        "text": "聊天和发短信可以使这些关系保持牢固——"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.609,
        "end": 200.238,
        "text": "只要它们保持亲密、信任和一致即可。"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.072,
        "end": 204.28300000000002,
        "text": "然而，即使是最亲密的友谊也遇到了艰难的时期。"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.119,
        "end": 211.165,
        "text": "那时人们通常会第一次应对不同类型的挑战。"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.749,
        "end": 216.04500000000002,
        "text": "例如，可能会出现让两个朋友竞争的情况，"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.04500000000002,
        "end": 218.339,
        "text": "比如申请同一所大学。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.756,
        "end": 222.551,
        "text": "一个人可能会背叛对方的信心或发表伤害性的评论。"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.01,
        "end": 228.474,
        "text": "而且，当一个人感到无法或不愿"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.474,
        "end": 231.519,
        "text": "在充满挑战的情况下"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.519,
        "end": 235.147,
        "text": "例如分手、疾病或个人悲剧中，支持对方时， 这些关系也会步履蹒跚。"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.648,
        "end": 240.027,
        "text": "处理分歧的最可靠方法是谈论它们。"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.403,
        "end": 243.531,
        "text": "这些对话可能既艰难又尴尬。"
      },
      {
        "start": 243.698,
        "end": 245.74099999999999,
        "text": "但是，如果以正确的方式对待"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.825,
        "end": 248.703,
        "text": "他们，从长远来看，他们可以加强友谊。"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.245,
        "end": 251.539,
        "text": "在这些艰难的对话之前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.539,
        "end": 254.959,
        "text": "试着提醒自己不要带任何判断力地露面。"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.209,
        "end": 258.629,
        "text": "避免过于防御或提出指控，"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.629,
        "end": 265.136,
        "text": "而是分享情况给 你的感受，并邀请他们也这样做。"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.678,
        "end": 268.597,
        "text": "一些友谊自然就结束了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 268.764,
        "end": 270.099,
        "text": "其他人会改变。"
      },
      {
        "start": 270.266,
        "end": 273.06,
        "text": "无论是新朋友还是终身朋友，"
      },
      {
        "start": 273.227,
        "end": 276.856,
        "text": "所有友谊都可以从养成健康的习惯中受益。"
      },
      {
        "start": 276.939,
        "end": 280.401,
        "text": "而且结交新朋友永远不会太晚。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Speak like a leader",
    "youtubeId": "bGBamfWasNQ",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Simon Lancaster",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 21.481,
        "end": 26.052,
        "text": "写作演讲稿一定是世界上最奇特的工作之一"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.832,
        "end": 29.751,
        "text": "不论是多么认真地准备好其中的文字"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.751,
        "end": 33.101,
        "text": "你还是不能确定最终的演说是怎样的"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.101,
        "end": 35.24,
        "text": "昨天，我正在伦敦"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.24,
        "end": 38.97,
        "text": "看我的客户，一个澳大利亚大商人"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.982,
        "end": 41.202,
        "text": "演说一份我为他写好的讲稿"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.202,
        "end": 45.119,
        "text": "我为他写了一段话，想象着温斯顿·丘吉尔的样子"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.119,
        "end": 47.499,
        "text": "内容是关于我们如何该为我们的未来斗争"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.499,
        "end": 51.796,
        "text": "为保护我们的地位斗争，向我们的竞争者斗争"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.796,
        "end": 54.786,
        "text": "但我忘了澳大利亚口音这件事"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.821,
        "end": 58.821,
        "text": "结果我坐在房间后排，惶恐万分地看着他开始说："
      },
      {
        "start": 59.331,
        "end": 63.991,
        "text": "“我们该为我的未来 ‘逗争’， 为保护我们的地位 ‘逗争’”"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.991,
        "end": 67.081,
        "text": "“让我告诉你们，朋友们，当我每天早晨醒来”"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.081,
        "end": 71.211,
        "text": "“我知道有件事情我这天一定要做：‘逗’争！”"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.489,
        "end": 74.489,
        "text": "（笑）（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 80.078,
        "end": 84.648,
        "text": "所以今天我要向你们分享一些演讲写手的秘密"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.908,
        "end": 86.622,
        "text": "我不知道你们知不知道"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.622,
        "end": 89.852,
        "text": "这个秘密：领导者的语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.852,
        "end": 94.209,
        "text": "这是一种领导者的秘密语言，然而我们都曾在学校里学习过"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.209,
        "end": 95.594,
        "text": "也就是古代的修辞学"
      },
      {
        "start": 95.594,
        "end": 99.614,
        "text": "修辞学曾经是古罗马课程的核心，中世纪三艺（语法、修辞、逻辑）之一"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.614,
        "end": 103.30799999999999,
        "text": "在伦敦，一直到19世纪"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.30799999999999,
        "end": 108.74799999999999,
        "text": "都可以免费得到修辞教育，但免费学不到数学"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.74799999999999,
        "end": 111.896,
        "text": "由此可见修辞学获得了多么大的重视"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.975,
        "end": 117.745,
        "text": "今天，教学修辞学是受限的，仅局限于一些有权势的少数人身上"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.745,
        "end": 122.195,
        "text": "所以我今天在演讲里要做的，就是复兴这种古老的修辞艺术"
      },
      {
        "start": 122.195,
        "end": 128.385,
        "text": "并向你们分享六个技巧，让你们都能都像领导者一样谈吐"
      },
      {
        "start": 128.385,
        "end": 130.581,
        "text": "所以对了，好吧，停下"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.581,
        "end": 133.751,
        "text": "对，停止倾听"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.751,
        "end": 137.831,
        "text": "朝左看，朝右看，朝中间看"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.608,
        "end": 140.602,
        "text": "你们正感觉如何呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.602,
        "end": 144.832,
        "text": "困扰的？焦虑的？有点急躁？"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.95499999999998,
        "end": 148.95499999999998,
        "text": "这是因为我正在模仿，呼吸急促"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.95499999999998,
        "end": 152.555,
        "text": "这是恐惧真正的声音"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.555,
        "end": 154.815,
        "text": "而这种恐惧传递到了你们身上"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.815,
        "end": 157.305,
        "text": "这正是一种古罗马修辞手法"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.305,
        "end": 159.285,
        "text": "人们曾叫这种手法“连接词省略”"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.285,
        "end": 161.595,
        "text": "它也是现在的领导者仍在用的一种手法"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.595,
        "end": 163.765,
        "text": "大卫·卡梅隆这样用："
      },
      {
        "start": 164.535,
        "end": 166.065,
        "text": "“破碎的家庭”"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.245,
        "end": 167.715,
        "text": "“没有成效的学校”"
      },
      {
        "start": 167.945,
        "end": 169.255,
        "text": "“生活质量极差的住房”"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.734,
        "end": 171.994,
        "text": "托尼·布莱尔也用过这个手法："
      },
      {
        "start": 172.762,
        "end": 174.132,
        "text": "“教育”"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.552,
        "end": 178.042,
        "text": "巴拉克·奥巴马也不例外："
      },
      {
        "start": 178.975,
        "end": 180.505,
        "text": "“一个陷于战争的世界”"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.505,
        "end": 182.285,
        "text": "“一个濒临危机的星球”"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.285,
        "end": 185.705,
        "text": "“一代人所见证的最糟的金融危机”"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.705,
        "end": 187.044,
        "text": "为什么都是三句呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.199,
        "end": 189.269,
        "text": "三就是那个有魔力的数字"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.269,
        "end": 190.449,
        "text": "在修辞学中"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.449,
        "end": 194.079,
        "text": "“民有、民治、民享的政府”"
      },
      {
        "start": 194.927,
        "end": 198.497,
        "text": "（德语）“一个民族,一个帝国,一个领袖”"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.512,
        "end": 205.912,
        "text": "（意大利语）“吃得好，笑口常开，多给予爱”"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.744,
        "end": 210.284,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.736,
        "end": 217.416,
        "text": "这其实是这个演讲里面最难练习的"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.416,
        "end": 219.326,
        "text": "所以非常感谢你们的掌声"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.226,
        "end": 222.856,
        "text": "这同时又是另一种古罗马的修辞手法"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.856,
        "end": 224.536,
        "text": "他们曾称其为“三平行”"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.536,
        "end": 228.036,
        "text": "这名字让它听起来像是消化系统的某个奇特的部分"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.036,
        "end": 230.486,
        "text": "不过它指的不过是把事物三件一组放在一起"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.486,
        "end": 232.046,
        "text": "当你把你的论述组织为三句一组"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.046,
        "end": 236.546,
        "text": "论述会听起来更不可抗拒，更有说服力，更可信"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.776,
        "end": 238.276,
        "text": "就好像我刚刚做的样子"
      },
      {
        "start": 238.276,
        "end": 242.536,
        "text": "所以我们找到了三的规则，这里，那里，到处都是"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.536,
        "end": 245.546,
        "text": "这样你们甚至可以把维罗纳的历史"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.546,
        "end": 247.686,
        "text": "用三的规则讲述出来，不用任何其他话"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.686,
        "end": 251.406,
        "text": "如果你们想到2000年前，凯撒曾经来到这里说:"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.406,
        "end": 254.296,
        "text": "\"我来，我见，我征服\""
      },
      {
        "start": 254.86599999999999,
        "end": 256.436,
        "text": "400年前"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.436,
        "end": 258.756,
        "text": "莎士比亚写下《罗密欧与朱丽叶》"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.756,
        "end": 260.226,
        "text": "故事正设在这里"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.226,
        "end": 264.316,
        "text": "“罗密欧，罗密欧，你在哪里，罗密欧？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.906,
        "end": 266.116,
        "text": "不过，当然啦"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.376,
        "end": 271.666,
        "text": "迄今为止，维罗纳历史上最重大的事件"
      },
      {
        "start": 272.483,
        "end": 274.223,
        "text": "正是今天的TEDx"
      },
      {
        "start": 274.223,
        "end": 277.763,
        "text": "“再发明，再思考，再传递”"
      },
      {
        "start": 277.763,
        "end": 278.586,
        "text": "好的"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.639,
        "end": 281.563,
        "text": "让我们继续吧，第二条"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.563,
        "end": 283.693,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 283.693,
        "end": 287.853,
        "text": "三个句子，开始句都被重复"
      },
      {
        "start": 287.853,
        "end": 290.663,
        "text": "看，这是温斯顿·丘吉尔在他的语句里所用的："
      },
      {
        "start": 290.793,
        "end": 292.58299999999997,
        "text": "“我们将要战斗在海滩”"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.64300000000003,
        "end": 295.043,
        "text": "“我们将要战斗在登陆地”"
      },
      {
        "start": 295.043,
        "end": 298.023,
        "text": "“我们将要战斗在田野，在街头”"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.023,
        "end": 300.813,
        "text": "当然，他可以把话说得快许多"
      },
      {
        "start": 300.813,
        "end": 304.753,
        "text": "但是他希望表达他的情感，所以他选择重复这些话"
      },
      {
        "start": 304.753,
        "end": 308.39300000000003,
        "text": "当我们对事物有强烈的感情时，我们自己的视角会变样"
      },
      {
        "start": 308.39300000000003,
        "end": 310.963,
        "text": "在我们的演讲中也相应体现出来"
      },
      {
        "start": 310.963,
        "end": 314.783,
        "text": "所以，这是激情真正的声音"
      },
      {
        "start": 315.034,
        "end": 316.474,
        "text": "我爱维罗纳"
      },
      {
        "start": 317.154,
        "end": 318.544,
        "text": "我爱意大利"
      },
      {
        "start": 318.544,
        "end": 319.821,
        "text": "我爱意大利通心粉"
      },
      {
        "start": 320.071,
        "end": 321.911,
        "text": "我爱提拉米苏"
      },
      {
        "start": 323.606,
        "end": 325.336,
        "text": "我爱你们所有人"
      },
      {
        "start": 325.68,
        "end": 327.27,
        "text": "我爱这兴奋的感觉"
      },
      {
        "start": 327.27,
        "end": 328.82,
        "text": "我爱这充沛的活力"
      },
      {
        "start": 328.82,
        "end": 331.27,
        "text": "我爱这房间里的热忱"
      },
      {
        "start": 331.27,
        "end": 332.61,
        "text": "你们感受到我的激情了吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 332.61,
        "end": 336.11,
        "text": "你们该感受到了，因为我是个演讲写手，我知道怎么证明一个观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 336.11,
        "end": 338.13,
        "text": "这种手法总能够大获全胜"
      },
      {
        "start": 338.13,
        "end": 343.508,
        "text": "这也是为什么花言巧语的推销员和市场生意人用这种技巧"
      },
      {
        "start": 343.719,
        "end": 347.949,
        "text": "“我不要求20镑，我不要求15镑”"
      },
      {
        "start": 347.949,
        "end": 350.183,
        "text": "“我甚至不要求10镑”"
      },
      {
        "start": 350.183,
        "end": 354.193,
        "text": "这样人们被直接席卷到下一个点，也就是陈述中自由的均衡"
      },
      {
        "start": 354.739,
        "end": 357.979,
        "text": "“不要问你们的国家能为你们做些什么”"
      },
      {
        "start": 357.979,
        "end": 360.249,
        "text": "“而要问你们能为国家做些什么。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 362.753,
        "end": 365.193,
        "text": "“美国没有任何错误的东西”"
      },
      {
        "start": 365.283,
        "end": 368.363,
        "text": "“不能被正确的东西所纠正。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 370.1,
        "end": 373.55,
        "text": "“生存还是毁灭。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 373.72,
        "end": 376.81,
        "text": "如果一句话听起来有种均衡的感觉"
      },
      {
        "start": 376.813,
        "end": 379.723,
        "text": "我们就会认为背后的思想也是不偏不倚的"
      },
      {
        "start": 379.723,
        "end": 382.783,
        "text": "而我们的头脑生来喜欢均衡的东西"
      },
      {
        "start": 382.783,
        "end": 386.303,
        "text": "如均衡的头脑，均衡的食谱，均衡的生活"
      },
      {
        "start": 386.303,
        "end": 388.713,
        "text": "所以我们会受到这样的句子的吸引"
      },
      {
        "start": 388.755,
        "end": 393.295,
        "text": "哪怕均衡的感觉事实上仅是一种假象，我们照样会受其吸引"
      },
      {
        "start": 393.406,
        "end": 395.886,
        "text": "这就像说，我们看向未来，而不是过去"
      },
      {
        "start": 396.006,
        "end": 399.036,
        "text": "我们是在一同合作，而没有敌对"
      },
      {
        "start": 399.036,
        "end": 402.516,
        "text": "我们在想我们能做的事情，而不是不能做的事"
      },
      {
        "start": 402.854,
        "end": 404.794,
        "text": "现在让我们继续到第四点"
      },
      {
        "start": 404.825,
        "end": 405.995,
        "text": "隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 405.995,
        "end": 411.015,
        "text": "隐喻大概是最有力的一种政治表达"
      },
      {
        "start": 411.015,
        "end": 415.015,
        "text": "但隐喻也是人们鲜少提及的一块，像房间里的大象，人们视而不见"
      },
      {
        "start": 415.015,
        "end": 420.971,
        "text": "这相当令人惊奇，考虑到我们平均每16个词就会用一次隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 420.971,
        "end": 426.551,
        "text": "所以说我们的谈话中到处都是隐喻，到处散落着隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 426.551,
        "end": 430.071,
        "text": "我们没法指望不用隐喻而说很多话"
      },
      {
        "start": 430.071,
        "end": 432.794,
        "text": "而隐喻都是意味深长的"
      },
      {
        "start": 433.344,
        "end": 435.317,
        "text": "看，隐喻比比皆是"
      },
      {
        "start": 435.317,
        "end": 438.651,
        "text": "同时他们有很强的政治性，因为人们使用隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 438.651,
        "end": 443.303,
        "text": "将人们引导向某些东西，或正相反，让人们退缩"
      },
      {
        "start": 443.303,
        "end": 447.633,
        "text": "这样，我们用美好的形象，人们的形象，爱的形象"
      },
      {
        "start": 447.633,
        "end": 452.839,
        "text": "家庭、阳光的形象，让事物能够吸引人"
      },
      {
        "start": 452.839,
        "end": 458.606,
        "text": "并用令人厌恶的东西，如害虫，满身鳞片的怪物，恶疾和病痛"
      },
      {
        "start": 458.606,
        "end": 460.973,
        "text": "让人们退缩"
      },
      {
        "start": 461.039,
        "end": 464.469,
        "text": "而这些全部是谎言，并且从未被质疑过"
      },
      {
        "start": 464.469,
        "end": 468.229,
        "text": "但他们却对人们的举动和反应有巨大的影响"
      },
      {
        "start": 468.229,
        "end": 471.659,
        "text": "研究表明对一个文本，仅仅改变其中的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 471.669,
        "end": 473.129,
        "text": "保留全部其他的部分"
      },
      {
        "start": 473.239,
        "end": 476.399,
        "text": "足以导致人们做出本质上不同的反应"
      },
      {
        "start": 476.399,
        "end": 477.899,
        "text": "所问的问题包括"
      },
      {
        "start": 477.899,
        "end": 480.159,
        "text": "他们是否会投资于一个公司"
      },
      {
        "start": 480.384,
        "end": 484.724,
        "text": "他们是否对支持某个关于犯罪的政策"
      },
      {
        "start": 485.204,
        "end": 487.784,
        "text": "甚至他们会不会支持一场国外的战争"
      },
      {
        "start": 488.064,
        "end": 492.224,
        "text": "所以隐喻是真的非常重要的东西，与我们息息相关"
      },
      {
        "start": 492.224,
        "end": 494.524,
        "text": "所以我来举三个著名隐喻的例子"
      },
      {
        "start": 494.524,
        "end": 495.814,
        "text": "—三这个有魔力的数字—"
      },
      {
        "start": 495.814,
        "end": 498.644,
        "text": "这三个例子现在也能够常常听到"
      },
      {
        "start": 498.644,
        "end": 500.254,
        "text": "“阿拉伯之春”"
      },
      {
        "start": 500.254,
        "end": 502.044,
        "text": "你们都听说过阿拉伯之春"
      },
      {
        "start": 502.044,
        "end": 503.004,
        "text": "不用阿拉伯之春这个说法"
      },
      {
        "start": 503.004,
        "end": 506.284,
        "text": "你们没办法谈论正在中东发生的事情"
      },
      {
        "start": 506.284,
        "end": 508.252,
        "text": "“阿拉伯之春”"
      },
      {
        "start": 508.252,
        "end": 511.29200000000003,
        "text": "阳光灿烂，鲜花盛开"
      },
      {
        "start": 511.29200000000003,
        "end": 515.742,
        "text": "这是愈合，再生，再获青春的时期"
      },
      {
        "start": 515.742,
        "end": 518.558,
        "text": "还是个巨大的谎言，不是么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 518.558,
        "end": 521.798,
        "text": "哪怕最为乐观的地缘政治专家"
      },
      {
        "start": 521.798,
        "end": 523.308,
        "text": "看到中东也说"
      },
      {
        "start": 523.308,
        "end": 525.658,
        "text": "这要花费两代人的时间才能恢复"
      },
      {
        "start": 525.658,
        "end": 529.008,
        "text": "这不是阿拉伯之春，是阿拉伯地狱"
      },
      {
        "start": 529.218,
        "end": 532.228,
        "text": "还有另一个例子：“加莱丛林”"
      },
      {
        "start": 532.228,
        "end": 535.538,
        "text": "这个说法已经真正地生根了"
      },
      {
        "start": 535.538,
        "end": 538.558,
        "text": "比喻来说，在过去一年左右"
      },
      {
        "start": 538.558,
        "end": 543.398,
        "text": "如果你谷歌“加莱”和“丛林”，你会得到7000万个结果"
      },
      {
        "start": 543.398,
        "end": 548.337,
        "text": "如果你谷歌“加莱”和“牛角面包”，你只会得到50万个结果"
      },
      {
        "start": 548.337,
        "end": 551.027,
        "text": "而这个说法又在你们的头脑中植入了怎样的图景？"
      },
      {
        "start": 551.027,
        "end": 556.117,
        "text": "它在你们的头脑中种下移民就像野蛮的动物的想法"
      },
      {
        "start": 556.117,
        "end": 561.037,
        "text": "应该害怕他们，他们危险，他们代表了对你们的威胁"
      },
      {
        "start": 561.317,
        "end": 565.346,
        "text": "这是一个危险的隐喻，因为这是种族屠杀的语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 565.346,
        "end": 567.03,
        "text": "仇恨的语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 567.03,
        "end": 571.28,
        "text": "希特勒反犹时将他们描述为毒蛇，与这个是相同的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 571.322,
        "end": 575.372,
        "text": "卢安达种族屠杀时，胡图人用与之相同的语言反对图西人"
      },
      {
        "start": 575.372,
        "end": 579.252,
        "text": "图西人被形容为蟑螂"
      },
      {
        "start": 579.252,
        "end": 581.492,
        "text": "所以我们应该感到强烈的忧虑"
      },
      {
        "start": 581.492,
        "end": 585.592,
        "text": "鉴于主流媒体正使用“加莱丛林”这个说法"
      },
      {
        "start": 585.592,
        "end": 589.032,
        "text": "去谈论我们星球上最为弱势的一群人"
      },
      {
        "start": 589.252,
        "end": 592.332,
        "text": "让我们再看看另一个：“金融风暴”"
      },
      {
        "start": 592.332,
        "end": 595.252,
        "text": "金融风暴，即金融危机"
      },
      {
        "start": 595.252,
        "end": 598.422,
        "text": "金融危机真的是自然的所作所为"
      },
      {
        "start": 598.422,
        "end": 601.272,
        "text": "如同风暴的隐喻所暗示的一样？"
      },
      {
        "start": 601.272,
        "end": 604.522,
        "text": "所以它与贪婪的银行家无关？"
      },
      {
        "start": 604.522,
        "end": 606.312,
        "text": "也不涉及懦弱的政客？"
      },
      {
        "start": 606.312,
        "end": 609.272,
        "text": "或无效的规章制度？"
      },
      {
        "start": 609.272,
        "end": 612.402,
        "text": "风暴的说法将一个虚假的形象植入我们的头脑中："
      },
      {
        "start": 612.402,
        "end": 615.292,
        "text": "金融风暴是一个自然而然，席卷而来的事情"
      },
      {
        "start": 615.292,
        "end": 619.722,
        "text": "同样地，会席卷而去，不需要我们做出任何行动"
      },
      {
        "start": 619.727,
        "end": 621.267,
        "text": "这是个大谎言"
      },
      {
        "start": 621.473,
        "end": 623.793,
        "text": "教宗方济各知道这是个大谎言"
      },
      {
        "start": 623.793,
        "end": 627.533,
        "text": "所以他讲演时没有使用金融风暴这个隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 627.533,
        "end": 629.413,
        "text": "他用了一个不同的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 629.413,
        "end": 632.803,
        "text": "他谈到了资本主义的粪堆"
      },
      {
        "start": 632.987,
        "end": 636.987,
        "text": "所以这里他用了一个粪便的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 637.221,
        "end": 640.311,
        "text": "比喻非常精彩，因为他所呼吁的"
      },
      {
        "start": 640.311,
        "end": 643.241,
        "text": "他所要求的，是对整个系统的一次清扫"
      },
      {
        "start": 643.241,
        "end": 646.501,
        "text": "这也是一个所有这个星球上的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 646.501,
        "end": 651.351,
        "text": "都能够立刻理解，并对其感到厌恶的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 651.351,
        "end": 654.491,
        "text": "也是一个可以偶尔引来几声笑的隐喻"
      },
      {
        "start": 654.491,
        "end": 657.281,
        "text": "所以在隐喻的范围中，也包含"
      },
      {
        "start": 657.281,
        "end": 660.611,
        "text": "我们那些比较好笑的政客有时会做的事情"
      },
      {
        "start": 660.611,
        "end": 663.031,
        "text": "鲍里斯·约翰逊，回到英国"
      },
      {
        "start": 663.031,
        "end": 665.371,
        "text": "曾谈论过工党的党魁"
      },
      {
        "start": 665.371,
        "end": 669.281,
        "text": "是如何从工会运动的肠道中产生的"
      },
      {
        "start": 669.281,
        "end": 671.501,
        "text": "在我为政府工作的期间"
      },
      {
        "start": 671.501,
        "end": 676.981,
        "text": "托尼·布莱尔和戈登·布朗曾被形容为同一臀部的两瓣"
      },
      {
        "start": 677.281,
        "end": 681.6610000000001,
        "text": "罗纳德·里根则曾将政府比作一个婴孩"
      },
      {
        "start": 681.671,
        "end": 684.015,
        "text": "一端有个巨大的胃口"
      },
      {
        "start": 684.015,
        "end": 687.015,
        "text": "却在另一端无责任感可言"
      },
      {
        "start": 687.015,
        "end": 689.737,
        "text": "所以让我们继续到第五点"
      },
      {
        "start": 689.737,
        "end": 691.277,
        "text": "夸张"
      },
      {
        "start": 691.277,
        "end": 694.607,
        "text": "当我们情感强烈时，我们的视角会变形"
      },
      {
        "start": 694.607,
        "end": 696.088,
        "text": "这会相应地体现在我们的演讲中"
      },
      {
        "start": 696.088,
        "end": 698.198,
        "text": "关于某事的情感过于强烈的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 698.198,
        "end": 699.881,
        "text": "就会因此过分夸大"
      },
      {
        "start": 699.881,
        "end": 704.351,
        "text": "像这样，“上帝啊，我这辈子都等着来做这个演讲呢”"
      },
      {
        "start": 704.771,
        "end": 707.13,
        "text": "“我昨晚完全没有闭眼”"
      },
      {
        "start": 707.69,
        "end": 710.87,
        "text": "“我要把我的心和灵魂都献给你们”"
      },
      {
        "start": 710.87,
        "end": 713.729,
        "text": "好的，这些都是夸张的陈述"
      },
      {
        "start": 713.729,
        "end": 715.819,
        "text": "领导者无时不刻不在做这样的事情"
      },
      {
        "start": 715.819,
        "end": 718.389,
        "text": "也许你们觉得这样很不合规矩，但事实上"
      },
      {
        "start": 718.389,
        "end": 723.219,
        "text": "夸张是普通言谈里面不可缺少的一部分"
      },
      {
        "start": 723.223,
        "end": 726.723,
        "text": "所以他们不过是复制了这种"
      },
      {
        "start": 726.731,
        "end": 728.411,
        "text": "我们自然做出的事情"
      },
      {
        "start": 728.411,
        "end": 730.788,
        "text": "让我们继续到第六点，押韵"
      },
      {
        "start": 730.788,
        "end": 733.748,
        "text": "研究表明，相比不押韵的表述"
      },
      {
        "start": 733.748,
        "end": 738.018,
        "text": "如果表述押韵，人们更有可能相信某件事是真实的"
      },
      {
        "start": 738.178,
        "end": 743.108,
        "text": "这听起来很荒唐，但这正源于语言学家口中"
      },
      {
        "start": 743.108,
        "end": 748.258,
        "text": "所谓的处理语言的流畅性：这些话语有多容易理解？"
      },
      {
        "start": 748.258,
        "end": 751.888,
        "text": "如果你用长长的单词和句子讲话"
      },
      {
        "start": 751.888,
        "end": 755.788,
        "text": "就会如同给人一块牛排，叫他们直接吞下去"
      },
      {
        "start": 755.788,
        "end": 759.198,
        "text": "然而你如给他们更简练的话，比如一篇韵文"
      },
      {
        "start": 759.198,
        "end": 762.778,
        "text": "这样就会像请他们品尝一点普罗塞克葡萄酒"
      },
      {
        "start": 763.618,
        "end": 767.988,
        "text": "我们从学步的时候起，就开始通过押韵的话来学习"
      },
      {
        "start": 768.132,
        "end": 770.502,
        "text": "“一，二，系鞋带儿”"
      },
      {
        "start": 770.502,
        "end": 774.042,
        "text": "所以在我们的社会中，韵文是表示真理的符号"
      },
      {
        "start": 774.042,
        "end": 778.212,
        "text": "因此，很多时候他们被用来掩饰逻辑中的谬论"
      },
      {
        "start": 778.212,
        "end": 782.174,
        "text": "我不清楚你们中是否有人记得O.J.辛普森的案子"
      },
      {
        "start": 782.824,
        "end": 786.239,
        "text": "“如果不匹配，你就得判免罪”"
      },
      {
        "start": 786.239,
        "end": 787.219,
        "text": "是吧？"
      },
      {
        "start": 787.319,
        "end": 790.812,
        "text": "“日食一苹果，疾病莫缠我”"
      },
      {
        "start": 790.812,
        "end": 792.615,
        "text": "它听起来很简单，听起来很对"
      },
      {
        "start": 792.615,
        "end": 795.215,
        "text": "但天啊，我们能够节省多少医疗保健开支"
      },
      {
        "start": 795.215,
        "end": 797.405,
        "text": "要是果真如此的话，是不是？"
      },
      {
        "start": 797.475,
        "end": 799.045,
        "text": "英国还有另一个说法："
      },
      {
        "start": 799.045,
        "end": 803.255,
        "text": "我们都通过这个口诀学习拼写：“I在E前，除非在C后”"
      },
      {
        "start": 803.255,
        "end": 805.712,
        "text": "如果真的是这样的话，这事非常棒"
      },
      {
        "start": 805.712,
        "end": 807.312,
        "text": "但这个口诀完全是一派胡言"
      },
      {
        "start": 807.312,
        "end": 810.312,
        "text": "只有44例符合这个说法的词"
      },
      {
        "start": 810.312,
        "end": 814.192,
        "text": "有900例词语不符合"
      },
      {
        "start": 814.49,
        "end": 818.49,
        "text": "我曾向一整屋的城市工作者演说这件事"
      },
      {
        "start": 818.632,
        "end": 823.642,
        "text": "他们说：“哦，对，我们也想到一个：你得多投机，财富才能堆积”"
      },
      {
        "start": 824.262,
        "end": 825.292,
        "text": "诶哟！"
      },
      {
        "start": 825.592,
        "end": 830.992,
        "text": "也许整个金融危机都被一个押韵的谬论所预言过："
      },
      {
        "start": 831.225,
        "end": 834.345,
        "text": "要是这句话在银行家中间口口相传："
      },
      {
        "start": 834.345,
        "end": 836.605,
        "text": "“投机过分，负债破产”"
      },
      {
        "start": 836.605,
        "end": 839.785,
        "text": "也许，我们就不会身陷于现在的混乱之中了"
      },
      {
        "start": 840.292,
        "end": 841.506,
        "text": "好了"
      },
      {
        "start": 841.506,
        "end": 844.506,
        "text": "这就是六个修辞手段"
      },
      {
        "start": 844.506,
        "end": 849.976,
        "text": "用这六个手段，你能够让大多数荒唐的观点听起来合情合理"
      },
      {
        "start": 850.041,
        "end": 851.721,
        "text": "为什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 851.761,
        "end": 853.661,
        "text": "如果你对古代修辞学感兴趣的话"
      },
      {
        "start": 853.661,
        "end": 856.921,
        "text": "原因是他们利用了了社会共有的特定态度，情感共鸣，逻辑条理。"
      },
      {
        "start": 856.971,
        "end": 861.711,
        "text": "如果你更倾向用神经科学看待他们的说服力"
      },
      {
        "start": 861.711,
        "end": 867.521,
        "text": "原因则是他们对本能，情感和理性的掌控"
      },
      {
        "start": 867.521,
        "end": 869.831,
        "text": "我这就展示给你们看"
      },
      {
        "start": 869.831,
        "end": 872.121,
        "text": "我希望你们向我提出一个问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 872.121,
        "end": 877.855,
        "text": "而我会为你们想一篇演讲出来，我会即兴创作这次演说"
      },
      {
        "start": 877.855,
        "end": 880.695,
        "text": "所以，有谁想提出一个话题给我..."
      },
      {
        "start": 881.225,
        "end": 882.742,
        "text": "真的，快来吧"
      },
      {
        "start": 882.742,
        "end": 883.938,
        "text": "（观众喊叫）"
      },
      {
        "start": 883.938,
        "end": 885.408,
        "text": "唐纳德·特朗普？"
      },
      {
        "start": 885.408,
        "end": 887.4639999999999,
        "text": "（笑）"
      },
      {
        "start": 887.4639999999999,
        "end": 889.774,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 892.912,
        "end": 895.116,
        "text": "你们要我支持还是反对？"
      },
      {
        "start": 895.9159999999999,
        "end": 897.506,
        "text": "支持还是反对？"
      },
      {
        "start": 897.506,
        "end": 898.876,
        "text": "（观众喊叫）"
      },
      {
        "start": 898.876,
        "end": 899.876,
        "text": "支持"
      },
      {
        "start": 899.876,
        "end": 902.116,
        "text": "（笑）"
      },
      {
        "start": 902.116,
        "end": 903.086,
        "text": "好吧"
      },
      {
        "start": 905.193,
        "end": 906.713,
        "text": "坦率"
      },
      {
        "start": 906.793,
        "end": 907.753,
        "text": "诚实"
      },
      {
        "start": 908.413,
        "end": 909.923,
        "text": "有权威"
      },
      {
        "start": 910.931,
        "end": 912.581,
        "text": "美国一直在等待"
      },
      {
        "start": 912.581,
        "end": 916.271,
        "text": "等待某人强势地带领起美国，让美国重整雄风"
      },
      {
        "start": 916.271,
        "end": 920.451,
        "text": "美国一直在等待，一位敢于说出事实的政客"
      },
      {
        "start": 920.451,
        "end": 925.281,
        "text": "美国一直被等待，等待某人能够展现出真正的领袖风范"
      },
      {
        "start": 925.7860000000001,
        "end": 928.476,
        "text": "自由主义的当权派在打击特朗普"
      },
      {
        "start": 928.476,
        "end": 930.496,
        "text": "但从民众那里，特朗普赢得了支持"
      },
      {
        "start": 930.496,
        "end": 934.876,
        "text": "这是因为，他没有做有倾向的陈述，实情如何，特朗普就怎样说"
      },
      {
        "start": 935.075,
        "end": 938.655,
        "text": "注意，特朗普不仅是在美国的腹地谈论其问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 938.655,
        "end": 941.845,
        "text": "他所谈论的，是世界范围的真相"
      },
      {
        "start": 941.984,
        "end": 946.654,
        "text": "全世界都在等待特朗普这样的人带来的启发"
      },
      {
        "start": 946.654,
        "end": 948.144,
        "text": "等待了很久了"
      },
      {
        "start": 948.144,
        "end": 949.614,
        "text": "让我来告诉你们"
      },
      {
        "start": 949.614,
        "end": 952.3340000000001,
        "text": "今天在维罗纳，我们所有人"
      },
      {
        "start": 952.3340000000001,
        "end": 956.324,
        "text": "我们都应该感谢我们的幸运星：我们终于得到了"
      },
      {
        "start": 956.326,
        "end": 960.706,
        "text": "真正的政治辩论，此刻正发生在美国"
      },
      {
        "start": 960.706,
        "end": 964.806,
        "text": "也许，谁知道，有一天在欧洲我们也能获得类似的东西"
      },
      {
        "start": 964.806,
        "end": 967.697,
        "text": "毕竟，大千世界，无奇不有"
      },
      {
        "start": 967.697,
        "end": 969.527,
        "text": "所以..."
      },
      {
        "start": 970.657,
        "end": 975.777,
        "text": "如果你们觉得特朗普不过是该丢掉的糟粕"
      },
      {
        "start": 975.777,
        "end": 980.877,
        "text": "那么对所有你们这些欧盟成员，我要说：“ 去你的！”"
      },
      {
        "start": 980.877,
        "end": 985.137,
        "text": "（笑）（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 1004.251,
        "end": 1005.271,
        "text": "谢谢"
      },
      {
        "start": 1007.382,
        "end": 1011.992,
        "text": "不过，顺便说一声，我想明确一件事"
      },
      {
        "start": 1012.735,
        "end": 1015.475,
        "text": "我认为特朗普是我们该丢掉的糟粕"
      },
      {
        "start": 1015.715,
        "end": 1017.095,
        "text": "（笑）（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 1017.095,
        "end": 1018.515,
        "text": "他是个笨蛋"
      },
      {
        "start": 1022.715,
        "end": 1023.965,
        "text": "谢谢"
      },
      {
        "start": 1024.24,
        "end": 1028.95,
        "text": "这是一个玩笑式的小练习，不过我想表达的观点是非常严肃的"
      },
      {
        "start": 1029.233,
        "end": 1032.283,
        "text": "我们之所以都在学校里面学习修辞"
      },
      {
        "start": 1032.283,
        "end": 1035.943,
        "text": "是因为修辞被视为进入社会的基本起点"
      },
      {
        "start": 1035.943,
        "end": 1037.943,
        "text": "社会怎么会公平"
      },
      {
        "start": 1037.943,
        "end": 1042.543,
        "text": "除非所有人都有相同的能力去清楚地表达自己？"
      },
      {
        "start": 1042.854,
        "end": 1044.874,
        "text": "没有它，你们的法律系统"
      },
      {
        "start": 1044.874,
        "end": 1049.004,
        "text": "你们的政治系统，你们的金融系统，都不是公平的"
      },
      {
        "start": 1049.229,
        "end": 1053.229,
        "text": "所以这应该成为我们所有人忧虑的问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 1053.229,
        "end": 1057.899,
        "text": "鉴于修辞的教学已经被局限于一个很小的有权有势的精英群体"
      },
      {
        "start": 1058.0,
        "end": 1061.04,
        "text": "在英国，有一所学校教授修辞的学问"
      },
      {
        "start": 1061.04,
        "end": 1062.31,
        "text": "这所学校就是伊顿公学"
      },
      {
        "start": 1062.377,
        "end": 1066.168,
        "text": "我们过去的50位首相中，有19位都曾在那里接受教育"
      },
      {
        "start": 1066.168,
        "end": 1070.468,
        "text": "我们目前的伦敦市长，坎特伯雷大主教，也是这样"
      },
      {
        "start": 1070.59,
        "end": 1073.23,
        "text": "这完全是件丢脸的事情："
      },
      {
        "start": 1073.23,
        "end": 1077.1,
        "text": "当我们正在世界范围面对巨大的挑战"
      },
      {
        "start": 1077.1,
        "end": 1082.28,
        "text": "--经济上的不平等，气候变化带来的末世威胁--"
      },
      {
        "start": 1082.28,
        "end": 1086.48,
        "text": "--从1940年起最为严重的宗教迫害--"
      },
      {
        "start": 1086.48,
        "end": 1090.86,
        "text": "我们却在将辩论局限于一个狭隘的少数派"
      },
      {
        "start": 1091.036,
        "end": 1093.996,
        "text": "代替教我们的孩子如何坐好如何闭上嘴巴"
      },
      {
        "start": 1093.996,
        "end": 1097.766,
        "text": "我们应该教他们如何站起来，如何为自己发声"
      },
      {
        "start": 1097.766,
        "end": 1099.786,
        "text": "所以让我们复兴修辞学"
      },
      {
        "start": 1099.786,
        "end": 1103.556,
        "text": "让我们在世界范围，为辩论注入新的活力"
      },
      {
        "start": 1103.556,
        "end": 1107.87,
        "text": "让我们真正地给予地球上每个孩子成为领袖的机会"
      },
      {
        "start": 1107.87,
        "end": 1110.54,
        "text": "我们应该怎么称呼这个宏大的倡议呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 1110.84,
        "end": 1112.3,
        "text": "哦，我有个主意"
      },
      {
        "start": 1112.56,
        "end": 1114.8,
        "text": "“民主”如何？"
      },
      {
        "start": 1115.221,
        "end": 1117.771,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 1121.411,
        "end": 1122.771,
        "text": "谢谢"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "What makes things funny",
    "youtubeId": "ysSgG5V-R3U",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Peter McGraw",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 16.198,
        "end": 21.767,
        "text": "In a moment, I'm going to ask you to stand up, turn to someone you don't know,"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.847,
        "end": 27.039,
        "text": "and begin tickling that person. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.869,
        "end": 40.059,
        "text": "Although some of you may find this request slightly terrifying, (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.059,
        "end": 42.278,
        "text": "many of you are clearly amused."
      },
      {
        "start": 43.268,
        "end": 48.08,
        "text": "If this is funny, it begs the question, \"What makes things funny?\""
      },
      {
        "start": 48.96,
        "end": 54.026,
        "text": "And answering that question is important for a few reasons. Humor is pervasive,"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.026,
        "end": 58.31,
        "text": "people of all ages and cultures experience humor on a daily basis."
      },
      {
        "start": 59.73,
        "end": 62.182,
        "text": "Humor influences your choices -"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.182,
        "end": 67.381,
        "text": "from the movies and television you watch to the people you date and mate."
      },
      {
        "start": 68.531,
        "end": 74.46000000000001,
        "text": "And humor - that's true - (Laughter) and humor is beneficial."
      },
      {
        "start": 74.46000000000001,
        "end": 79.904,
        "text": "It makes you happy, and it helps you cope with pain, stress, and adversity."
      },
      {
        "start": 81.624,
        "end": 85.604,
        "text": "Although answering the question what makes things funny is important,"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.604,
        "end": 88.763,
        "text": "it's not why I'm here today. Let me explain."
      },
      {
        "start": 89.553,
        "end": 94.75399999999999,
        "text": "A few years ago, I was giving a talk about moral violations, and I was making the case"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.75399999999999,
        "end": 97.475,
        "text": "that moral violations cause anger and disgust."
      },
      {
        "start": 98.39500000000001,
        "end": 100.753,
        "text": "And I was motivating that case with an example:"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.753,
        "end": 106.687,
        "text": "a news story about a church that was raffling off an H2 Hummer SUV"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.687,
        "end": 114.282,
        "text": "to a lucky member of the congregation. (Laughter) But instead of groans, I got laughs,"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.282,
        "end": 116.787,
        "text": "and an astute member of the audience raised her hand."
      },
      {
        "start": 116.787,
        "end": 120.808,
        "text": "She said, \"Pete, you said that moral violations cause disgust,"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.808,
        "end": 129.847,
        "text": "and yet we're laughing. Why?\" I wanted to answer the question of what makes things funny"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.847,
        "end": 133.977,
        "text": "because I didn't know the answer to the question what makes things funny."
      },
      {
        "start": 135.187,
        "end": 140.22899999999998,
        "text": "E. B. White says, \"Analyzing humor is like dissecting a frog."
      },
      {
        "start": 140.22899999999998,
        "end": 146.5,
        "text": "Few people are interested, and the frog dies of it.\" (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.4,
        "end": 156.07,
        "text": "Nonetheless, for this purpose, I created the Humor Research Lab, or HURL. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.31,
        "end": 163.639,
        "text": "And in the next ten minutes, I'm going to present a theory of humor,"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.639,
        "end": 166.981,
        "text": "evidence from HURL that supports the theory,"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.981,
        "end": 171.235,
        "text": "and discuss implications for how you can have a more humorous life."
      },
      {
        "start": 172.345,
        "end": 177.303,
        "text": "Let's start with the theory. Caleb Warren and I have crafted a theory of humor"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.303,
        "end": 180.362,
        "text": "that we call the Benign Violation Theory."
      },
      {
        "start": 180.362,
        "end": 185.113,
        "text": "The Benign Violation Theory integrates existing humor theory"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.113,
        "end": 189.083,
        "text": "and builds on work by Tom Veatch to say that humor occurs"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.083,
        "end": 193.103,
        "text": "when and only when three conditions are satisfied:"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.103,
        "end": 198.054,
        "text": "a situation is a violation, a situation is benign,"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.054,
        "end": 201.712,
        "text": "and both of these appraisals occur simultaneously."
      },
      {
        "start": 207.734,
        "end": 213.216,
        "text": "Violations are anything that threatens the way you believe the world ought to be;"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.234,
        "end": 215.735,
        "text": "simply put, something seems wrong."
      },
      {
        "start": 216.715,
        "end": 221.45499999999998,
        "text": "Violations take many forms, ranging from violations of social norms,"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.45499999999998,
        "end": 229.017,
        "text": "such as a TED speaker asking people to touch each other, to violations of moral norms,"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.017,
        "end": 233.47899999999998,
        "text": "such as Keith Richards' claim that he snorted, among many other things,"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.47899999999998,
        "end": 240.349,
        "text": "his dead father's ashes. (Laughter) There's many ways to make a violation benign;"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.349,
        "end": 244.368,
        "text": "we've studied three. One way you make a violation benign"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.368,
        "end": 247.498,
        "text": "is to not be strongly committed to the violated norm."
      },
      {
        "start": 248.488,
        "end": 251.105,
        "text": "This explains why a bunch of non-religious academics"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.105,
        "end": 254.931,
        "text": "may laugh about a church giving away a Hummer SUV."
      },
      {
        "start": 256.181,
        "end": 261.38,
        "text": "Another way that a violation can be benign is if it's psychologically distant,"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.38,
        "end": 267.501,
        "text": "such as if it occurs to someone else, happened a long time ago, or just doesn't seem real."
      },
      {
        "start": 268.811,
        "end": 271.39,
        "text": "Yet another way that a violation can seem benign"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.39,
        "end": 276.19,
        "text": "is if there's some alternative explanation that somehow makes the violation OK,"
      },
      {
        "start": 276.19,
        "end": 282.311,
        "text": "as occurs in the case of play fighting and tickling. The Benign Violation Theory"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.311,
        "end": 289.302,
        "text": "predicts that primates laugh when play fighting or tickling because both are mock attacks"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.302,
        "end": 292.43399999999997,
        "text": "or threatening situations that also seem harmless."
      },
      {
        "start": 294.534,
        "end": 300.283,
        "text": "The theory also explains, in addition to what is funny, what is not funny,"
      },
      {
        "start": 300.283,
        "end": 304.164,
        "text": "and distinguishes between the two meanings of the term \"not funny.\""
      },
      {
        "start": 305.354,
        "end": 309.275,
        "text": "Situations that are purely benign are not funny,"
      },
      {
        "start": 310.005,
        "end": 315.895,
        "text": "there is no threat there, and explains why you can't tickle yourself. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 315.895,
        "end": 319.176,
        "text": "You can try; it doesn't work. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 321.986,
        "end": 327.926,
        "text": "Situations that are pure violations, or what we call malign violations,"
      },
      {
        "start": 327.926,
        "end": 332.477,
        "text": "are also not funny. So that creepy guy who's kind of sitting close to you,"
      },
      {
        "start": 332.477,
        "end": 339.377,
        "text": "who looks pretty eager to tickle you - (Laughter) There's nothing OK about that situation."
      },
      {
        "start": 339.377,
        "end": 349.149,
        "text": "(Laughter) The theory also accounts for other types of physical humor."
      },
      {
        "start": 349.149,
        "end": 354.151,
        "text": "Walking down a flight of stairs - no violation, not funny."
      },
      {
        "start": 354.151,
        "end": 360.321,
        "text": "Falling down a flight of stairs, but being unhurt - benign violation, funny."
      },
      {
        "start": 361.661,
        "end": 368.211,
        "text": "Falling down that flight of stairs and being badly hurt - malign violation, not funny."
      },
      {
        "start": 368.211,
        "end": 374.642,
        "text": "(Laughter) Unless it happens to someone else. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 376.051,
        "end": 380.221,
        "text": "The theory also explains why the nerds among us laugh at puns:"
      },
      {
        "start": 380.221,
        "end": 384.682,
        "text": "violations of linguistic norms [This is not a drill. I repeat. This is not a drill!]"
      },
      {
        "start": 384.682,
        "end": 391.532,
        "text": "that also seem OK. How do you make this not funny? Well, you can remove the violation."
      },
      {
        "start": 392.552,
        "end": 396.683,
        "text": "You can also make it funny by removing the thing that makes it OK."
      },
      {
        "start": 396.683,
        "end": 403.985,
        "text": "This attempt is just confusing. (Laughter) Let's try another one just for fun;"
      },
      {
        "start": 403.985,
        "end": 411.466,
        "text": "I saw this one on a T-shirt in Las Vegas recently. [My pen is huge.] (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 412.31600000000003,
        "end": 422.003,
        "text": "Benign violation. How do you make it not funny? Well, you could ... (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 422.003,
        "end": 426.686,
        "text": "just remove the violation, move the \"is\" down. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 426.686,
        "end": 433.098,
        "text": "How do you make it a malign violation? (Laughter) You really want me to do this?"
      },
      {
        "start": 433.098,
        "end": 445.898,
        "text": "(Laughter) So by now, you can see how the benign violation has great explanatory power."
      },
      {
        "start": 445.898,
        "end": 449.698,
        "text": "It explains nervous laughter, for instance, such as -"
      },
      {
        "start": 452.273,
        "end": 455.778,
        "text": "how at tickling you may laugh, but it's unwanted."
      },
      {
        "start": 455.778,
        "end": 459.78,
        "text": "Because a violation is a necessary condition for humor,"
      },
      {
        "start": 459.78,
        "end": 465.159,
        "text": "you may experience a negative emotion in addition to your amusement."
      },
      {
        "start": 465.619,
        "end": 468.64,
        "text": "We've studied this at HURL with benign moral violations,"
      },
      {
        "start": 468.64,
        "end": 471.874,
        "text": "such as when someone is treated unfairly, but probably deserves it."
      },
      {
        "start": 471.874,
        "end": 477.89,
        "text": "[Orange juice $5 Jugo de naranja $4] (Laughter) The American who can't figure this out"
      },
      {
        "start": 477.89,
        "end": 482.83,
        "text": "can probably afford to spend the extra dollar. (Laughter)"
      },
      {
        "start": 482.83,
        "end": 487.223,
        "text": "How do you make this not a violation? You just make the prices equal."
      },
      {
        "start": 487.223,
        "end": 491.572,
        "text": "How do you make it less funny? Well, you target the less affluent group."
      },
      {
        "start": 493.702,
        "end": 496.452,
        "text": "Our participants endorse more negative emotions"
      },
      {
        "start": 496.452,
        "end": 499.134,
        "text": "and less amusement in this condition, don't worry."
      },
      {
        "start": 502.053,
        "end": 506.08299999999997,
        "text": "So you probably can see how both what is funny and what is not funny"
      },
      {
        "start": 506.08299999999997,
        "end": 508.406,
        "text": "is explained by the Benign Violation Theory."
      },
      {
        "start": 508.406,
        "end": 512.484,
        "text": "Let's turn our attention to how to live a more humorous life."
      },
      {
        "start": 512.8340000000001,
        "end": 516.414,
        "text": "The theory indicates that you should pay attention to your audience,"
      },
      {
        "start": 516.414,
        "end": 522.115,
        "text": "and it suggests that everybody has a good sense of humor under the right circumstances."
      },
      {
        "start": 522.115,
        "end": 526.427,
        "text": "What one person sees as benign, another sees as a benign violation,"
      },
      {
        "start": 526.427,
        "end": 532.456,
        "text": "and another sees as a malign violation. These folks won't laugh at your pedophile joke."
      },
      {
        "start": 533.626,
        "end": 540.688,
        "text": "Yeah, I was worried about that one. (Laughter) You should also consider the situation."
      },
      {
        "start": 540.688,
        "end": 545.158,
        "text": "Is the situation a violation? Then try to make it more benign."
      },
      {
        "start": 545.158,
        "end": 546.937,
        "text": "Writers, directors and comedians"
      },
      {
        "start": 546.937,
        "end": 550.527,
        "text": "have long advocated for the use of distance in doing this."
      },
      {
        "start": 551.137,
        "end": 556.288,
        "text": "Tragedy is when I cut my finger. Comedy is when you walk into an open sewer and die."
      },
      {
        "start": 556.288,
        "end": 565.09,
        "text": "(Laughter) Our participants endorse this idea."
      },
      {
        "start": 565.09,
        "end": 569.761,
        "text": "They say that a friend falling into an open sewer is less funny than a stranger."
      },
      {
        "start": 570.671,
        "end": 575.648,
        "text": "They also find this violation funnier when perceived from a far distance"
      },
      {
        "start": 575.648,
        "end": 580.66,
        "text": "than a close distance. (Disgusted laughter) We call this the Silverman strategy."
      },
      {
        "start": 580.66,
        "end": 585.71,
        "text": "The comedian Sarah Silverman transforms violations into benign violations"
      },
      {
        "start": 585.71,
        "end": 590.803,
        "text": "by making racial and ethnic jokes in a cute, non-serious, non-threatening way."
      },
      {
        "start": 592.233,
        "end": 597.412,
        "text": "But not all violations would be made funnier by making them more distant."
      },
      {
        "start": 599.552,
        "end": 603.794,
        "text": "Although Mark Twain said that humor is tragedy plus time,"
      },
      {
        "start": 603.794,
        "end": 611.943,
        "text": "no one says humor is a mild misstep plus time. And our participants seem to indicate"
      },
      {
        "start": 612.813,
        "end": 616.665,
        "text": "that bringing some mild violations closer makes them funnier,"
      },
      {
        "start": 616.665,
        "end": 619.735,
        "text": "so stumbling on a curb is funnier when it happens to your friend"
      },
      {
        "start": 619.735,
        "end": 621.825,
        "text": "than when it happens to a stranger."
      },
      {
        "start": 622.675,
        "end": 630.121,
        "text": "This is evidenced by the saying, \"You had to be there.\" (Laughter) And moreover,"
      },
      {
        "start": 630.121,
        "end": 634.184,
        "text": "our participants find this mild violation funnier when perceived up close"
      },
      {
        "start": 634.944,
        "end": 639.825,
        "text": "than from a far perspective. We call this the Seinfeld strategy."
      },
      {
        "start": 640.615,
        "end": 646.807,
        "text": "Seinfeld transforms normal everyday situations into benign violations"
      },
      {
        "start": 646.807,
        "end": 652.439,
        "text": "by highlighting what is wrong with them. We finally suggest you consider yourself."
      },
      {
        "start": 652.439,
        "end": 655.84,
        "text": "Are you like Sarah Silverman, brash over the top?"
      },
      {
        "start": 656.45,
        "end": 659.409,
        "text": "Soften the situation, soften the violations."
      },
      {
        "start": 659.409,
        "end": 664.498,
        "text": "If you are like Seinfeld though, more reserved and mild-mannered,"
      },
      {
        "start": 664.498,
        "end": 667.78,
        "text": "concentrate on creating these violations, highlighting them."
      },
      {
        "start": 669.687,
        "end": 675.109,
        "text": "So you probably by now have figured out I'm not going to ask you to touch each other,"
      },
      {
        "start": 675.109,
        "end": 678.374,
        "text": "but how did I know that proposition would be funny?"
      },
      {
        "start": 678.374,
        "end": 680.54,
        "text": "Well, first I started with a violation."
      },
      {
        "start": 680.54,
        "end": 685.252,
        "text": "It's clearly wrong to ask you to do that; it violates a host of norms."
      },
      {
        "start": 685.252,
        "end": 689.719,
        "text": "But I had to know that this was going to be benign. Well, first I considered you."
      },
      {
        "start": 689.719,
        "end": 692.739,
        "text": "I figured you're a pretty open-minded group,"
      },
      {
        "start": 692.739,
        "end": 699.262,
        "text": "you're here to learn new things, experience new things, OK. I also created distance:"
      },
      {
        "start": 699.262,
        "end": 704.111,
        "text": "I told you this was going to be in the future, not in the present."
      },
      {
        "start": 704.111,
        "end": 709.762,
        "text": "And lastly, there is an alternative interpretation: I am giving a talk about humor,"
      },
      {
        "start": 709.762,
        "end": 712.465,
        "text": "and so it could make sense to ask you to do this."
      },
      {
        "start": 713.625,
        "end": 718.643,
        "text": "In short, to make things funny, you want to create a benign violation."
      },
      {
        "start": 718.643,
        "end": 720.984,
        "text": "That's easier said than done, however."
      },
      {
        "start": 720.984,
        "end": 727.794,
        "text": "Erma Bombeck said that there's a thin line between laughter and pain, comedy and tragedy,"
      },
      {
        "start": 727.794,
        "end": 734.915,
        "text": "and humor and hurt. Thank you. (Applause)"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Get comfortable with being uncomfortable",
    "youtubeId": "QijH4UAqGD8",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Luvvie Ajayi Jones",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 12.0,
        "end": 14.246,
        "text": "我是个专业的麻烦制造者。"
      },
      {
        "start": 14.246,
        "end": 15.912,
        "text": "(笑声)"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.912,
        "end": 21.913,
        "text": "因为我的工作就是批判世界，"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.913,
        "end": 24.913,
        "text": "批判劣质的系统与不求上进的人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 25.954,
        "end": 28.996,
        "text": "作为一名作家、演讲家 以及一名“臭名昭著”的尼日利亚人——"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.996,
        "end": 29.746,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 29.746,
        "end": 33.954,
        "text": "我觉得我的工作 就和图中这只猫差不多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.954,
        "end": 35.954,
        "text": "（笑声） （图片：自认清高的艺术家）"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.954,
        "end": 39.204,
        "text": "我就是那种挑剔别人生活的人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.204,
        "end": 41.246,
        "text": "总想着 “我需要你改一改。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.246,
        "end": 42.288,
        "text": "这就是我。"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.288,
        "end": 47.329,
        "text": "我希望我们可以 让这个世界变得更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.329,
        "end": 49.996,
        "text": "我选择改变世界的方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.996,
        "end": 51.287,
        "text": "是畅所欲言，"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.287,
        "end": 53.454,
        "text": "通过当第一张多米诺骨牌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.037,
        "end": 57.371,
        "text": "为了让一排骨牌倒下，"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.371,
        "end": 59.037,
        "text": "必须有一个先倒下，"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.037,
        "end": 61.787,
        "text": "剩下的骨牌别无选择， 就会跟着倒下。"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.204,
        "end": 64.829,
        "text": "有了那张倒下的骨牌，"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.829,
        "end": 66.912,
        "text": "我们希望"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.912,
        "end": 70.246,
        "text": "下个看到这个情况的人会被激励， 也成为一张骨牌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.121,
        "end": 75.037,
        "text": "对我而言，作为骨牌就要公开表态，"
      },
      {
        "start": 75.037,
        "end": 76.95400000000001,
        "text": "就要迎难而上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.95400000000001,
        "end": 79.413,
        "text": "特别是当人们需要 有人挺身而出的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.413,
        "end": 81.70400000000001,
        "text": "希望其他人也能效仿。"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.913,
        "end": 85.45400000000001,
        "text": "此外还有一点： 我就是那种会说出"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.45400000000001,
        "end": 88.95400000000001,
        "text": "想说但不敢说的话的人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.95400000000001,
        "end": 91.871,
        "text": "人们经常会觉得 我们这种人是无所畏惧的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.871,
        "end": 93.163,
        "text": "做这种事的人是无所畏惧的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.163,
        "end": 94.663,
        "text": "我们并不是无所畏惧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.663,
        "end": 97.163,
        "text": "我们并不是不怕这些后果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.163,
        "end": 99.49600000000001,
        "text": "也不是不惧怕"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.49600000000001,
        "end": 101.57900000000001,
        "text": "宣扬真理后的牺牲。"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.57900000000001,
        "end": 104.038,
        "text": "事实上，我们觉得这是我们的义务，"
      },
      {
        "start": 104.038,
        "end": 106.37100000000001,
        "text": "因为在这个世界"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.37100000000001,
        "end": 108.20400000000001,
        "text": "愿意当骨牌的人太少，"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.20400000000001,
        "end": 110.62100000000001,
        "text": "鲜有人愿意第一个倒下。"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.62100000000001,
        "end": 112.24600000000001,
        "text": "我们这么做不是不会恐惧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.24600000000001,
        "end": 114.163,
        "text": "现在，我们讲一讲恐惧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.163,
        "end": 116.20400000000001,
        "text": "我曾经很清楚长大后想做什么，"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.20400000000001,
        "end": 118.45400000000001,
        "text": "“我要成为一位医生!”"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.45400000000001,
        "end": 120.413,
        "text": "当上医生是我曾经的梦想，"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.413,
        "end": 123.163,
        "text": "在《小医师大玩偶》流行起来之前 我就在扮演医师。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.163,
        "end": 124.329,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.329,
        "end": 126.579,
        "text": "我记得我上大学的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.579,
        "end": 130.121,
        "text": "我大一的时候， 必须上化学基础这门课，"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.121,
        "end": 131.954,
        "text": "为了我的预科主修做准备。"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.829,
        "end": 135.829,
        "text": "我拿了学术生涯中唯一的一个D。"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.829,
        "end": 137.788,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.788,
        "end": 140.246,
        "text": "于是我去找学校辅导员说："
      },
      {
        "start": 140.246,
        "end": 142.579,
        "text": "“我放弃医学院预科了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.579,
        "end": 144.621,
        "text": "因为我不是当医生的料，"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.621,
        "end": 146.371,
        "text": "因为我根本就不喜欢医院。"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.371,
        "end": 147.371,
        "text": "所以...“"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.371,
        "end": 148.288,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.288,
        "end": 151.329,
        "text": "“还是算了吧。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.329,
        "end": 153.788,
        "text": "也是在那个学期，我开始写博客。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.788,
        "end": 155.496,
        "text": "那是2003年。"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.496,
        "end": 158.288,
        "text": "当一个梦想结束的时候， 另外一个梦想开始了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.288,
        "end": 161.829,
        "text": "后来，当我2010年失去了 市场营销工作的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.829,
        "end": 164.829,
        "text": "这个可爱的爱好 就成为了我全职的工作。"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.829,
        "end": 168.204,
        "text": "但我花了两年多时间才能说： “我是个作家。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.204,
        "end": 173.496,
        "text": "在我写作了九年之后我才说， “我是个作家。“"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.496,
        "end": 176.121,
        "text": "因为我害怕"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.121,
        "end": 178.329,
        "text": "没有退休金的后果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 178.329,
        "end": 180.288,
        "text": "我害怕我不能 继续保持买鞋的习惯，"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.288,
        "end": 181.413,
        "text": "那对我很重要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.413,
        "end": 182.996,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.996,
        "end": 186.038,
        "text": "所以我需要花很长的时间"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.038,
        "end": 187.954,
        "text": "去了解我的目的是什么。"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.954,
        "end": 189.496,
        "text": "然后我意识到，"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.496,
        "end": 191.788,
        "text": "恐惧是一股非常具体的力量，"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.788,
        "end": 196.538,
        "text": "会阻止我们说出和践行 我们真正的目的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.538,
        "end": 198.163,
        "text": "于是我想，“你知道吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.163,
        "end": 201.163,
        "text": "我不会让恐惧主宰我的生活。"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.163,
        "end": 204.121,
        "text": "我不会让恐惧支配我的所作所为。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 204.121,
        "end": 207.288,
        "text": "于是所有奇妙的事情开始发生了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.288,
        "end": 209.829,
        "text": "骨牌开始倒下了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.829,
        "end": 212.246,
        "text": "当我意识到的时候， 我开始想，“好，2015年"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.246,
        "end": 213.454,
        "text": "我30岁了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 213.454,
        "end": 215.871,
        "text": "这将是我 ‘不顾一切‘ 的一年"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.871,
        "end": 219.329,
        "text": "我会积极地去追求 任何令我恐惧的事情。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.329,
        "end": 221.871,
        "text": "我是个摩羯座，"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.871,
        "end": 224.163,
        "text": "我喜欢脚踏实地的感觉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.954,
        "end": 228.163,
        "text": "我决定开启人生的首次个人旅行，"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.163,
        "end": 231.079,
        "text": "我决定去多米尼加共和国。"
      },
      {
        "start": 231.746,
        "end": 234.204,
        "text": "那么在我生日的那一天， 我做了什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.204,
        "end": 237.121,
        "text": "我通过索道 穿越蓬塔·卡纳森林。"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.121,
        "end": 239.454,
        "text": "因为某些奇怪的原因， 我穿了商务装。"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.454,
        "end": 240.954,
        "text": "不要问我为什么。"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.954,
        "end": 243.329,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 243.329,
        "end": 245.204,
        "text": "我度过了特别棒的时光。"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.204,
        "end": 247.371,
        "text": "我不喜欢潜水。"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.371,
        "end": 250.079,
        "text": "再说一次， 我喜欢脚踏实地。"
      },
      {
        "start": 250.079,
        "end": 254.038,
        "text": "所以我去了墨西哥， 在水下和海豚游泳。"
      },
      {
        "start": 254.996,
        "end": 257.454,
        "text": "那一年，我还做了一件超酷的事情，"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.454,
        "end": 259.079,
        "text": "那是我的人生巅峰——"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.788,
        "end": 261.454,
        "text": "我写了一本书，"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.454,
        "end": 263.496,
        "text": "《我在评判你：如何做得更好》"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.496,
        "end": 264.788,
        "text": "所以我现在应该算——"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.788,
        "end": 265.621,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.621,
        "end": 267.538,
        "text": "掌握写作的能力了，对吧？"
      },
      {
        "start": 267.538,
        "end": 268.913,
        "text": "是的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 268.913,
        "end": 271.829,
        "text": "但在那一年，我做的 最非常“反我”的事情，"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.829,
        "end": 273.579,
        "text": "简直要吓死我了——"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.079,
        "end": 276.413,
        "text": "我去跳伞了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 277.371,
        "end": 279.038,
        "text": "我们正要从飞机里跳下去的时候,"
      },
      {
        "start": 279.038,
        "end": 281.704,
        "text": "我在想， “这绝对是我这辈子做过的蠢事之一。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.704,
        "end": 282.954,
        "text": "（笑）"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.954,
        "end": 285.246,
        "text": "接下来我们就向地面坠落，"
      },
      {
        "start": 285.246,
        "end": 289.038,
        "text": "我看着地面， 我简直无法呼吸，"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.038,
        "end": 291.288,
        "text": "我在想，“我刚刚故意从一架 完好无损的飞机上跳下来了！”"
      },
      {
        "start": 291.288,
        "end": 292.329,
        "text": "（笑）"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.329,
        "end": 294.038,
        "text": "“我有毛病吗？！”"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.038,
        "end": 296.079,
        "text": "但当我俯视地表美景时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 296.079,
        "end": 298.704,
        "text": "我在想， ‘“这是我做过的最好的事情，"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.704,
        "end": 301.454,
        "text": "这是一个超棒的决定。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 301.454,
        "end": 304.579,
        "text": "我回想起需要 说出实话的那些时刻。"
      },
      {
        "start": 304.579,
        "end": 307.454,
        "text": "那感觉就像正从飞机上掉下来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 307.454,
        "end": 310.121,
        "text": "就像我在飞机边缘的那一刻，"
      },
      {
        "start": 310.121,
        "end": 311.788,
        "text": "我告诉自己，“你不应该这么做，”"
      },
      {
        "start": 311.788,
        "end": 314.454,
        "text": "但无论如何我还是做了， 因为我意识到自己必须去做。"
      },
      {
        "start": 315.454,
        "end": 317.121,
        "text": "对我来说，坐在飞机边缘，"
      },
      {
        "start": 317.121,
        "end": 320.038,
        "text": "或者说呆在飞机上是很舒服的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 320.038,
        "end": 322.121,
        "text": "我感觉，在我诉说真相，"
      },
      {
        "start": 322.121,
        "end": 324.496,
        "text": "和那些比我强大的机构和人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 324.496,
        "end": 327.371,
        "text": "以及那些更强大的势力抗衡的每一天。"
      },
      {
        "start": 327.371,
        "end": 329.246,
        "text": "都仿佛从那架飞机上掉下来一般。"
      },
      {
        "start": 329.246,
        "end": 331.579,
        "text": "但我意识到， 舒适感其实被高估了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 331.579,
        "end": 334.454,
        "text": "因为沉默是最舒适的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 334.454,
        "end": 337.954,
        "text": "不去改变才是舒适的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 337.954,
        "end": 340.496,
        "text": "但是舒适感能带给我们的 只有维护现状而已。"
      },
      {
        "start": 340.496,
        "end": 342.913,
        "text": "所以我们应该通过 在必要的时候说出严峻的现实"
      },
      {
        "start": 342.913,
        "end": 345.663,
        "text": "来学会走出自己的舒适区。"
      },
      {
        "start": 346.704,
        "end": 347.538,
        "text": "而且我——"
      },
      {
        "start": 347.538,
        "end": 349.163,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 351.079,
        "end": 354.996,
        "text": "我也意识到了坦白真相的重要性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 354.996,
        "end": 356.996,
        "text": "因为诚实对于我来说非常重要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 356.996,
        "end": 358.996,
        "text": "我珍惜我的正直。"
      },
      {
        "start": 358.996,
        "end": 361.454,
        "text": "正义—— 我不认为正义是一个选项。"
      },
      {
        "start": 361.454,
        "end": 363.371,
        "text": "我们需要一直保持公平正义。"
      },
      {
        "start": 363.371,
        "end": 366.413,
        "text": "不过，我相信 乳木果油也十分重要——"
      },
      {
        "start": 366.413,
        "end": 368.204,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 368.204,
        "end": 371.413,
        "text": "因为如果我们更加滋润， 世界就会变得更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 372.496,
        "end": 373.163,
        "text": "但除此之外，"
      },
      {
        "start": 373.163,
        "end": 376.288,
        "text": "我的核心价值观是： 我必须讲出事实。"
      },
      {
        "start": 376.288,
        "end": 378.371,
        "text": "在这个问题上我没有其他的选择。"
      },
      {
        "start": 378.371,
        "end": 380.538,
        "text": "但像我这样的人， 专业的麻烦制造者，"
      },
      {
        "start": 380.538,
        "end": 383.079,
        "text": "不应该只有我们为成为骨牌献身，"
      },
      {
        "start": 383.079,
        "end": 384.621,
        "text": "不应该只有我们 总是从飞机上跳下来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 384.621,
        "end": 387.704,
        "text": "不应该只有我们成为靶子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 387.704,
        "end": 389.871,
        "text": "人们惧怕严重的后果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 389.871,
        "end": 393.121,
        "text": "所以没有意识到，很多时候， 当我们走进房间时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 393.121,
        "end": 395.996,
        "text": "我们是房间里最强大的一批人——"
      },
      {
        "start": 395.996,
        "end": 398.663,
        "text": "或者可能是第二强大、 第三强大的人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 398.663,
        "end": 401.788,
        "text": "并且我坚信那时我们的任务"
      },
      {
        "start": 401.788,
        "end": 404.079,
        "text": "是去中止正在发生的事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 404.079,
        "end": 405.913,
        "text": "如果我们不是最强大的人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 405.913,
        "end": 408.371,
        "text": "只要有更多的人加入我们，"
      },
      {
        "start": 408.371,
        "end": 410.038,
        "text": "我们就会变得更强大。"
      },
      {
        "start": 410.038,
        "end": 412.121,
        "text": "比如在开会时联合所有女性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 412.121,
        "end": 415.288,
        "text": "我们要让那些不敢发声的女性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 415.288,
        "end": 418.746,
        "text": "那些不敢发表看法的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 418.746,
        "end": 420.163,
        "text": "能被倾听。"
      },
      {
        "start": 420.163,
        "end": 423.288,
        "text": "我们的任务是为了 确保她们的这一权益。"
      },
      {
        "start": 423.288,
        "end": 425.329,
        "text": "社会的目标就是确保每个人的幸福。"
      },
      {
        "start": 425.329,
        "end": 427.413,
        "text": "如果我们明确了这一点， 我们就会了解到，"
      },
      {
        "start": 427.413,
        "end": 429.079,
        "text": "当我们需要帮助的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 429.079,
        "end": 430.538,
        "text": "如果我们曾经对他人施以援手，"
      },
      {
        "start": 430.538,
        "end": 432.621,
        "text": "就不必艰难地四处求助。"
      },
      {
        "start": 434.246,
        "end": 436.038,
        "text": "有时候，我在公共场合"
      },
      {
        "start": 436.038,
        "end": 439.913,
        "text": "会感到十分受挫，"
      },
      {
        "start": 439.913,
        "end": 442.913,
        "text": "比如有一次， 我受邀去会议上发表演讲，"
      },
      {
        "start": 442.913,
        "end": 446.413,
        "text": "他们想让我自付差旅费。"
      },
      {
        "start": 446.413,
        "end": 447.288,
        "text": "然后我做了些调查，"
      },
      {
        "start": 447.288,
        "end": 450.663,
        "text": "发现在那儿演讲的 白人男性都拿到了酬劳，"
      },
      {
        "start": 450.663,
        "end": 452.746,
        "text": "并报销了他们的差旅费。"
      },
      {
        "start": 452.746,
        "end": 455.496,
        "text": "在那儿演讲的白人女性 至少也拿到了差旅费。"
      },
      {
        "start": 455.496,
        "end": 459.704,
        "text": "而黑人女性，却需要自费演讲。"
      },
      {
        "start": 459.704,
        "end": 462.288,
        "text": "我就在想，“我该怎么办？“"
      },
      {
        "start": 462.288,
        "end": 465.163,
        "text": "我知道如果将这件事公之于众，"
      },
      {
        "start": 465.163,
        "end": 466.663,
        "text": "我可能会面对财务损失。"
      },
      {
        "start": 466.663,
        "end": 470.496,
        "text": "但是我也知道 我的沉默不会帮助任何人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 470.496,
        "end": 473.621,
        "text": "所以尽管心中十分忐忑， 我还是公开地谈论了这件事情。"
      },
      {
        "start": 473.621,
        "end": 476.121,
        "text": "之后其他女性也开始站出来谈论，"
      },
      {
        "start": 476.121,
        "end": 478.954,
        "text": "“我也面对过这种不公平的待遇。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 478.954,
        "end": 481.704,
        "text": "于是我们开始讨论那个会议的"
      },
      {
        "start": 481.704,
        "end": 484.246,
        "text": "歧视性报酬。"
      },
      {
        "start": 484.246,
        "end": 486.579,
        "text": "当我读到一位公众人物"
      },
      {
        "start": 486.579,
        "end": 489.829,
        "text": "带有歧视性的回忆录 并写了一些读后感时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 489.829,
        "end": 491.538,
        "text": "我觉得我成了一张骨牌，"
      },
      {
        "start": 491.538,
        "end": 494.913,
        "text": "我知道这个人比我更强大， 他可能会影响我的事业，"
      },
      {
        "start": 494.913,
        "end": 496.288,
        "text": "但我想，“我得做这件事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 496.288,
        "end": 499.538,
        "text": "我得坐在“飞机”的边缘， 想了大概两个小时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 499.538,
        "end": 502.663,
        "text": "最后决定放手一搏。 我按了“发布”键，然后溜了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 502.663,
        "end": 503.746,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 503.746,
        "end": 505.746,
        "text": "然后我发现这篇文章 收到了极高的关注，"
      },
      {
        "start": 505.746,
        "end": 509.163,
        "text": "人们在说，“天哪，我很开心 终于有个人说这个了。“"
      },
      {
        "start": 509.163,
        "end": 510.496,
        "text": "然后它开启了一场"
      },
      {
        "start": 510.496,
        "end": 513.663,
        "text": "关于精神健康和自我照顾的讨论，"
      },
      {
        "start": 513.663,
        "end": 515.829,
        "text": "我想，“好啊，"
      },
      {
        "start": 515.829,
        "end": 518.038,
        "text": "我猜我正在做的这件事情， 正在产生影响。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 518.996,
        "end": 522.163,
        "text": "然后当很多人开始讨论"
      },
      {
        "start": 523.329,
        "end": 527.204,
        "text": "自己怎么被位高权重的男性 抨击的时候，他们也成为了骨牌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 527.621,
        "end": 532.204,
        "text": "然后数百万女性也加入进来， 并说出，“我也是。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 532.204,
        "end": 535.162,
        "text": "在此，要感谢 塔拉娜·伯克点燃了这场运动。"
      },
      {
        "start": 536.121,
        "end": 539.746,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 541.412,
        "end": 545.996,
        "text": "大众和体制在依靠 我们的沉默去维持现状。"
      },
      {
        "start": 547.537,
        "end": 553.996,
        "text": "但有的时候成为骨牌就是在做自己。"
      },
      {
        "start": 553.996,
        "end": 557.079,
        "text": "我从三岁起就是个 名声不怎么样的人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 557.079,
        "end": 558.079,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 558.079,
        "end": 560.912,
        "text": "这是我三岁生日时的照片。"
      },
      {
        "start": 560.912,
        "end": 563.287,
        "text": "但我这一生从未改变，"
      },
      {
        "start": 563.287,
        "end": 565.204,
        "text": "我始终觉得应该去当那一张骨牌，"
      },
      {
        "start": 565.204,
        "end": 567.287,
        "text": "因为上帝想让我们去"
      },
      {
        "start": 567.287,
        "end": 569.454,
        "text": "为自己发声，"
      },
      {
        "start": 569.454,
        "end": 571.871,
        "text": "活出自我是一种革命性的行为。"
      },
      {
        "start": 571.871,
        "end": 574.787,
        "text": "在一个想让我们谨言慎行的世界里，"
      },
      {
        "start": 574.787,
        "end": 576.954,
        "text": "我选择大声呼喊。"
      },
      {
        "start": 576.954,
        "end": 579.496,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 581.912,
        "end": 584.371,
        "text": "当我感到有些事情 让我难以启齿的时候，"
      },
      {
        "start": 584.371,
        "end": 586.162,
        "text": "我会问自己三个问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 586.162,
        "end": 588.246,
        "text": "第一：你是认真的吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 588.246,
        "end": 590.871,
        "text": "第二：你可以为它辩护吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 590.871,
        "end": 593.246,
        "text": "第三：你是为爱发声吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 593.246,
        "end": 595.537,
        "text": "如果这三个问题的答案都是肯定的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 595.537,
        "end": 596.996,
        "text": "我就会不计后果地说出来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 599.162,
        "end": 600.329,
        "text": "那很重要。"
      },
      {
        "start": 600.329,
        "end": 602.079,
        "text": "这三个问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 602.079,
        "end": 604.579,
        "text": "始终给予我肯定的力量。"
      },
      {
        "start": 606.454,
        "end": 608.079,
        "text": "说实话—— 说出深思熟虑的实话——"
      },
      {
        "start": 608.079,
        "end": 609.954,
        "text": "不应该成为革命性的举动。"
      },
      {
        "start": 611.871,
        "end": 615.329,
        "text": "对权势说真话不应该 意味着牺牲，但事实却是如此。"
      },
      {
        "start": 616.204,
        "end": 619.329,
        "text": "但是如果更多的人能加入我们，"
      },
      {
        "start": 619.329,
        "end": 621.496,
        "text": "我们的处境会比现在更好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 622.996,
        "end": 624.496,
        "text": "说到更好的世界，"
      },
      {
        "start": 625.371,
        "end": 628.704,
        "text": "我认为我们有责任 用真相搭建桥梁，"
      },
      {
        "start": 628.704,
        "end": 630.496,
        "text": "去连接共同点，"
      },
      {
        "start": 630.496,
        "end": 633.162,
        "text": "那些没有用真相 搭建起来的桥梁就会崩塌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 633.162,
        "end": 635.329,
        "text": "所以，这是我们的工作，"
      },
      {
        "start": 635.329,
        "end": 638.371,
        "text": "我们的义务和责任"
      },
      {
        "start": 638.371,
        "end": 640.996,
        "text": "不屈从于权贵，去成为骨牌，"
      },
      {
        "start": 641.954,
        "end": 643.454,
        "text": "不只是在艰难的时候——"
      },
      {
        "start": 643.454,
        "end": 645.537,
        "text": "尤其是在艰难的时候。"
      },
      {
        "start": 645.537,
        "end": 646.621,
        "text": "谢谢。"
      },
      {
        "start": 646.621,
        "end": 652.412,
        "text": "（掌声）"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to find laughter anywhere",
    "youtubeId": "sUv353ua7E8",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Chris Duffy",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 3.917,
        "end": 6.503,
        "text": "在小学工作， 我最喜欢的部分就是"
      },
      {
        "start": 6.503,
        "end": 9.464,
        "text": "我永远无法预测接下来会发生什么。"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.506,
        "end": 11.258,
        "text": "每天都是崭新、神奇的一天。"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.258,
        "end": 13.385,
        "text": "从来没有过无聊的时刻。"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.426,
        "end": 16.388,
        "text": "有时，你以为你给孩子们发试题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 16.388,
        "end": 18.974,
        "text": "只是想复习形状的名称。"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.974,
        "end": 23.687,
        "text": "但是你收回来的不是“六边形”和“八边形”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.728,
        "end": 24.896,
        "text": "而是这些。"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.938,
        "end": 26.106,
        "text": "[“艾米”“加布里埃拉”]"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.147,
        "end": 28.4,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.441,
        "end": 31.444,
        "text": "我们也可以同意这是对的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 31.486,
        "end": 32.487,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.487,
        "end": 34.447,
        "text": "没错，那就是加布里埃拉。"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.447,
        "end": 37.075,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.117,
        "end": 41.121,
        "text": "或者还有一次我在上课，"
      },
      {
        "start": 41.162,
        "end": 44.124,
        "text": "给五年级学生上人类生物学，"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.165,
        "end": 47.752,
        "text": "有个学生后来交给我一张匿名的问题卡。"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.794,
        "end": 49.462,
        "text": "[蛋蛋是干什么用的。]"
      },
      {
        "start": 49.504,
        "end": 51.923,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.923,
        "end": 54.759,
        "text": "真正让我扎心、让我心痛的是，"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.759,
        "end": 58.513,
        "text": "我们花了这么长时间 学习标点符号。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.555,
        "end": 61.308,
        "text": "他用的还是句号而不是问号。"
      },
      {
        "start": 61.349,
        "end": 63.018,
        "text": "“蛋蛋是干什么用的。”句号。"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.059,
        "end": 65.353,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.979,
        "end": 68.982,
        "text": "我在给小学生上课的同时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.024,
        "end": 72.902,
        "text": "周末我也在当地的剧院 教授成人即兴喜剧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.944,
        "end": 74.988,
        "text": "他们是一群退休人员、"
      },
      {
        "start": 74.988,
        "end": 78.158,
        "text": "研究生和“半成功”的商界人士，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.158,
        "end": 83.83,
        "text": "他们花钱和我一起在不通风的地下室里 度过周六的早晨。"
      },
      {
        "start": 83.872,
        "end": 86.458,
        "text": "我们一起做的大部分练习"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.458,
        "end": 89.878,
        "text": "都是为了让他们抛弃 自己大脑中批判自我的部分，"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.919,
        "end": 93.423,
        "text": "放弃必须追寻“正确”答案的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.465,
        "end": 97.13499999999999,
        "text": "而是更加接纳自己诚实、有创意、"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.13499999999999,
        "end": 98.845,
        "text": "特立独行的想法。"
      },
      {
        "start": 99.22,
        "end": 101.806,
        "text": "随便一位小学老师都会告诉你，"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.806,
        "end": 105.435,
        "text": "让孩子们分享他们诚实、 出人意料的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.477,
        "end": 107.479,
        "text": "不是你要培养的东西。"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.52000000000001,
        "end": 110.315,
        "text": "无论你想不想让他们分享， 他们都会分享。"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.315,
        "end": 115.695,
        "text": "我来说几个孩子们突然 没头没脑问出的真实问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.737,
        "end": 118.239,
        "text": "那时我本该在安静地工作。"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.239,
        "end": 119.407,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.325,
        "end": 124.704,
        "text": "“我能不能活得更久一点， 这样能看到太阳爆炸呢？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.746,
        "end": 125.872,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.873,
        "end": 129.376,
        "text": "“猪真的歧视女性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.417,
        "end": 131.211,
        "text": "还是只是一种说法？” （指 “pig” 代指粗鲁男性）"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.211,
        "end": 136.508,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.008,
        "end": 139.552,
        "text": "“如果你哥哥还没结婚，"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.594,
        "end": 141.596,
        "text": "他为什么不能直接娶了你妈？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.596,
        "end": 142.764,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.806,
        "end": 145.35,
        "text": "其实这引出了一个非常重要的点，"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.392,
        "end": 147.56,
        "text": "那就是孩子们的想法并不总是好的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.56,
        "end": 148.895,
        "text": "有时候它们很糟糕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.895,
        "end": 152.44,
        "text": "我本人很庆幸我妈妈没有和我哥结婚。"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.482,
        "end": 153.608,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 154.025,
        "end": 156.736,
        "text": "有一些研究表明，对于许多人来说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.778,
        "end": 159.197,
        "text": "五年级已经接近这种极度自由、"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.197,
        "end": 161.15699999999998,
        "text": "无拘无束、创造性思维的顶峰了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.199,
        "end": 163.034,
        "text": "但不一定是这样。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.034,
        "end": 166.70499999999998,
        "text": "根据我的经验，具有惊人幽默感的人"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.746,
        "end": 170.5,
        "text": "和没有幽默感的人之间的区别 通常在于他们是否愿意接受"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.5,
        "end": 172.752,
        "text": "和注意到自己的诚实反应，"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.79399999999998,
        "end": 175.714,
        "text": "还是他们会尽全力拘束他们的反应。"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.714,
        "end": 177.132,
        "text": "这可能会随时间的推移发生变化。"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.132,
        "end": 179.38400000000001,
        "text": "我在我的成人即兴表演学生身上 看到了这种转变。"
      },
      {
        "start": 179.426,
        "end": 181.553,
        "text": "刚开始我们做一个练习，"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.594,
        "end": 186.599,
        "text": "要求他们尽快、发挥最大创意地 说出给定类别中的七样东西，"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.641,
        "end": 188.309,
        "text": "许多人会陷入困境。"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.351,
        "end": 190.72899999999998,
        "text": "有个人，公司税律师里克，"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.77,
        "end": 192.063,
        "text": "回答了这个问题："
      },
      {
        "start": 192.063,
        "end": 193.898,
        "text": "“七种奇怪的鞋子”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.898,
        "end": 198.528,
        "text": "他说：“棕色的鞋子、白色的鞋子、"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.528,
        "end": 201.614,
        "text": "黑色的鞋子、灰色的鞋子。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 201.656,
        "end": 203.40800000000002,
        "text": "我不想全部说一遍，"
      },
      {
        "start": 203.40800000000002,
        "end": 205.535,
        "text": "就是一大堆无聊的鞋子，你懂的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.535,
        "end": 208.663,
        "text": "但是，在我们练习 鼓励我们更奇怪的想法，"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.70499999999998,
        "end": 210.874,
        "text": "而不是压抑这些想法之后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.874,
        "end": 214.127,
        "text": "里克最终想出了一系列鞋子，比如："
      },
      {
        "start": 214.127,
        "end": 216.796,
        "text": "“沾满泥巴的鞋子、金子包裹的鞋子、"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.838,
        "end": 219.048,
        "text": "沾满我仇人鲜血的鞋子”等等。"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.09,
        "end": 220.71699999999998,
        "text": "厉害了，里克，"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.75900000000001,
        "end": 223.344,
        "text": "真的厉害了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.053,
        "end": 226.723,
        "text": "但是绝对更有趣了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 226.765,
        "end": 228.224,
        "text": "我认为这就是重点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.266,
        "end": 229.976,
        "text": "当我们停止自我判断，"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.976,
        "end": 232.562,
        "text": "注意到那些令我们印象深刻"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.562,
        "end": 233.73,
        "text": "或者我们思考的东西，"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.772,
        "end": 237.442,
        "text": "我们就能以滑稽、怡人的方式 给自己一个惊喜。"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.484,
        "end": 241.237,
        "text": "我认识的每位喜剧演员都 有一本笔记本或某种记录，"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.279,
        "end": 245.784,
        "text": "用来记下一天之中 注意到或者想到的小奇思。"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.784,
        "end": 248.036,
        "text": "你会发现，你开始记录以后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.036,
        "end": 250.455,
        "text": "就不会缺少素材。"
      },
      {
        "start": 250.455,
        "end": 252.165,
        "text": "有太多值得一笑的素材了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.165,
        "end": 256.169,
        "text": "如果你有一些勇气让别人笑你、"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.211,
        "end": 258.004,
        "text": "嘲笑自己，"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.004,
        "end": 261.216,
        "text": "你就会发现一些 本不会发现的东西，对吧？"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.257,
        "end": 264.844,
        "text": "如果你想知道蛋蛋是干什么用的， 有时候你得问出来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.844,
        "end": 268.515,
        "text": "我发现你甚至 能在最枯燥的地方找到笑点，"
      },
      {
        "start": 268.515,
        "end": 272.101,
        "text": "如果你能把淘气的五年级能量"
      },
      {
        "start": 272.101,
        "end": 275.438,
        "text": "带到教学中和你“本该”做的事中，对吧？"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.438,
        "end": 277.273,
        "text": "不一定是几何课堂。"
      },
      {
        "start": 277.273,
        "end": 281.319,
        "text": "这可能是你和你的好朋友 加布里埃拉一起出去玩的机会。"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.861,
        "end": 285.74,
        "text": "最开心的莫过于将这些"
      },
      {
        "start": 285.782,
        "end": 289.369,
        "text": "来自五年级学生的经验 运用到“自视甚高”的成人领域了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.40999999999997,
        "end": 293.706,
        "text": "运用到我可能会感到恐惧 或没有什么归属感的地方。"
      },
      {
        "start": 293.748,
        "end": 297.418,
        "text": "举个例子， 就我个人而言，领英。"
      },
      {
        "start": 297.46,
        "end": 298.878,
        "text": "太可怕了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.92,
        "end": 300.713,
        "text": "我从来没有过专业的简历，"
      },
      {
        "start": 300.755,
        "end": 303.675,
        "text": "我也一直无法适应商业社交，"
      },
      {
        "start": 303.675,
        "end": 306.386,
        "text": "但我一直对领英有点着迷。"
      },
      {
        "start": 306.386,
        "end": 308.054,
        "text": "他们可以让你创建档案，"
      },
      {
        "start": 308.096,
        "end": 311.391,
        "text": "他们也不会验证 你是不是在你号称的地方工作。"
      },
      {
        "start": 311.432,
        "end": 314.435,
        "text": "所以我决定去试用一下，玩一玩。"
      },
      {
        "start": 314.477,
        "end": 316.354,
        "text": "我在领英上创建了一个档案，"
      },
      {
        "start": 316.396,
        "end": 319.23199999999997,
        "text": "我说我是领英的 CEO。"
      },
      {
        "start": 319.274,
        "end": 321.693,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 321.734,
        "end": 324.153,
        "text": "我都不觉得他们会同意我这么写。"
      },
      {
        "start": 324.195,
        "end": 327.24,
        "text": "但他们不仅让我创建了， 还在我创建之后"
      },
      {
        "start": 327.282,
        "end": 331.87,
        "text": "发生了我这辈子最神奇的一件事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 331.87,
        "end": 336.541,
        "text": "领英把这封邮件 发给了我联系人里的每一个人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 337.0,
        "end": 338.209,
        "text": "他们发送了那封电子邮件。"
      },
      {
        "start": 338.251,
        "end": 339.627,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 339.627,
        "end": 341.88,
        "text": "“恭喜克里斯找到了新工作。"
      },
      {
        "start": 341.921,
        "end": 344.591,
        "text": "克里斯·达菲（Chris Duffy） 现在是领英的 CEO。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 344.591,
        "end": 345.8,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 345.842,
        "end": 349.304,
        "text": "这比我这辈子能写出的任何笑话都好。"
      },
      {
        "start": 349.345,
        "end": 352.724,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 353.266,
        "end": 358.271,
        "text": "我曾在领英上 担任过一年的领英 CEO。"
      },
      {
        "start": 358.271,
        "end": 361.482,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 361.482,
        "end": 363.359,
        "text": "在一周年之际，"
      },
      {
        "start": 363.401,
        "end": 367.572,
        "text": "领英又向我的每位联系人 发了一封邮件，"
      },
      {
        "start": 367.572,
        "end": 370.575,
        "text": "让他们祝贺我的工作周年纪念日。"
      },
      {
        "start": 370.575,
        "end": 372.41,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 372.452,
        "end": 373.912,
        "text": "当时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 373.912,
        "end": 376.039,
        "text": "我收到了一位 名叫菲丝的女士的来信，"
      },
      {
        "start": 376.08,
        "end": 378.666,
        "text": "她就职于领英的信任与安全团队。"
      },
      {
        "start": 378.666,
        "end": 380.335,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 380.376,
        "end": 384.839,
        "text": "她说我的账号被封了， 因为担心账号信息不实。"
      },
      {
        "start": 385.798,
        "end": 388.593,
        "text": "所以我给她发了一张我的驾照的"
      },
      {
        "start": 388.635,
        "end": 389.969,
        "text": "正反两面的照片，"
      },
      {
        "start": 390.011,
        "end": 392.347,
        "text": "用于证明我的名字 确实是克里斯·达菲。"
      },
      {
        "start": 392.388,
        "end": 393.389,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 393.431,
        "end": 395.058,
        "text": "菲丝回复了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 395.058,
        "end": 399.103,
        "text": "“我们担心的不是 你的名字不是克里斯·达菲。"
      },
      {
        "start": 399.145,
        "end": 402.565,
        "text": "问题是你自称你是领英的 CEO。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 402.60699999999997,
        "end": 404.067,
        "text": "于是我回复："
      },
      {
        "start": 404.067,
        "end": 408.696,
        "text": "“菲丝，你作为一个 为我打工的人，说话很不客气。”"
      },
      {
        "start": 408.696,
        "end": 414.40999999999997,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 418.581,
        "end": 422.21,
        "text": "10 秒钟后，她永久停用了我的账户。"
      },
      {
        "start": 422.251,
        "end": 425.63,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 425.672,
        "end": 429.717,
        "text": "这是我运营个人社交网络的短暂高光。"
      },
      {
        "start": 429.759,
        "end": 431.135,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 431.177,
        "end": 433.388,
        "text": "那我最近在干些什么呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 433.429,
        "end": 434.973,
        "text": "很高兴你问了这个问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 435.014,
        "end": 437.225,
        "text": "我不仅是一名五年级毕业生。"
      },
      {
        "start": 437.225,
        "end": 438.935,
        "text": "其实，"
      },
      {
        "start": 438.935,
        "end": 441.104,
        "text": "我是 TED 的创始人和所有者。"
      },
      {
        "start": 441.104,
        "end": 444.065,
        "text": "（笑声）"
      },
      {
        "start": 444.10699999999997,
        "end": 446.442,
        "text": "恭喜我吧，你知道你想的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 446.484,
        "end": 448.194,
        "text": "感谢你们来参加我的大会。"
      },
      {
        "start": 448.194,
        "end": 454.075,
        "text": "（掌声和欢呼）"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Why should you read 'Crime and Punishment'?",
    "youtubeId": "Vtkv3-endYc",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Alex Gendler",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.285,
        "end": 9.605,
        "text": "是什么驱使人变成了冷血杀手？"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.605,
        "end": 12.035,
        "text": "凶手心里想的是什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.035,
        "end": 15.505,
        "text": "又是什么样的社会 造就了这样的人呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.505,
        "end": 17.725,
        "text": "150多年前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.725,
        "end": 21.465,
        "text": "费奥多尔·米哈伊洛维奇·陀思妥耶夫斯基 在作品中提出了上述问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.465,
        "end": 25.585,
        "text": "这部作品后来成为 俄国文学史上最著名的作品之一："
      },
      {
        "start": 26.025,
        "end": 27.386,
        "text": "《罪与罚》。"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.146,
        "end": 32.806,
        "text": "这部小说于1866年 首次在一本文学杂志上连载，"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.806,
        "end": 36.776,
        "text": "讲述了圣彼得堡一个年轻的法学生"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.776,
        "end": 39.967,
        "text": "罗迪·罗曼诺维奇·拉斯科尔尼科夫的故事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.217,
        "end": 42.907,
        "text": "拉斯科尔尼科夫的生活穷困潦倒，"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.907,
        "end": 47.357,
        "text": "故事开头的他因 交不起学费而辍学。"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.357,
        "end": 50.953,
        "text": "农村老家的来信使他更为沮丧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.953,
        "end": 56.513,
        "text": "他发现母亲和妹妹为了让他成功 已经牺牲太多了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.513,
        "end": 59.871,
        "text": "把最后一点值钱的东西 卖给当铺的老太婆后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.871,
        "end": 62.051,
        "text": "他更加绝望了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.051,
        "end": 65.861,
        "text": "他决心要杀掉当铺老板娘， 夺走她的钱财。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.861,
        "end": 69.331,
        "text": "但实施这项鲁莽计划的后果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.331,
        "end": 72.801,
        "text": "比他预想的要严重得多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.801,
        "end": 77.571,
        "text": "虽然该作有时被认为是 最早的心理惊悚小说之一，"
      },
      {
        "start": 77.571,
        "end": 81.837,
        "text": "小说所揭露的远不止 拉斯科利尼科夫内心的挣扎。"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.837,
        "end": 84.407,
        "text": "从潮湿的小酒馆，到破旧的公寓"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.407,
        "end": 86.967,
        "text": "和幽闭恐怖的警察局,"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.967,
        "end": 90.349,
        "text": "19世纪圣彼得堡的社会阴暗面"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.352,
        "end": 93.81700000000001,
        "text": "在陀思妥耶夫斯基 犀利的笔触下跃然纸上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.81700000000001,
        "end": 96.937,
        "text": "我们认识了诸多角色，例如马美拉多夫，"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.937,
        "end": 101.497,
        "text": "一位因酗酒而倾家荡产的可怜的下岗官员；"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.497,
        "end": 106.27199999999999,
        "text": "还有斯维里加洛夫， 一位傲慢、脾气暴躁的贵族。"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.27199999999999,
        "end": 109.368,
        "text": "当拉斯科利尼科夫的家人来到镇上时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 109.368,
        "end": 111.178,
        "text": "他们道德上的纯真"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.178,
        "end": 115.297,
        "text": "与周围人的堕落形成鲜明对比，"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.297,
        "end": 118.807,
        "text": "即使他们的命运逐渐交织在了一起。"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.807,
        "end": 121.167,
        "text": "这幅冷酷的俄罗斯社会肖像画，"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.167,
        "end": 126.517,
        "text": "反映了作者自身复杂的生活经历 和不断发展的思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.517,
        "end": 130.47,
        "text": "告别了前途无量的军队仕途， 费奥多尔成为一名年轻作家，"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.47,
        "end": 134.47,
        "text": "被社会主义和改革思想所吸引，"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.47,
        "end": 136.72,
        "text": "并加入了知识分子的圈子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.72,
        "end": 140.906,
        "text": "讨论被帝国政府禁止的激进文章。"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.326,
        "end": 142.576,
        "text": "暴露后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.576,
        "end": 146.276,
        "text": "包括陀思妥耶夫斯基在内的 团体成员被捕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.276,
        "end": 147.916,
        "text": "许多人被判处死刑，"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.916,
        "end": 153.546,
        "text": "在行刑前一刻才被沙皇赦免， 只经受了模拟处决。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.836,
        "end": 158.05599999999998,
        "text": "陀思妥耶夫斯基 在西伯利亚劳改营待了四年,"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.05599999999998,
        "end": 161.135,
        "text": "直到1854年才被释放。"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.135,
        "end": 165.883,
        "text": "这次经历让他对社会改革越发悲观，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.883,
        "end": 169.381,
        "text": "他也把目光更多地投向了精神层面的话题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.381,
        "end": 173.281,
        "text": "在1864年的中篇小说 《地下室手记》中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.281,
        "end": 176.99099999999999,
        "text": "他阐述了他的观点， 认为乌托邦式的西方哲学"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.99099999999999,
        "end": 181.651,
        "text": "永远无法满足 人类灵魂中相互矛盾的欲望。"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.651,
        "end": 185.953,
        "text": "次年，他构思并完成了《罪与罚》，"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.953,
        "end": 188.593,
        "text": "书中许多主题与上篇小说相同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.593,
        "end": 189.583,
        "text": "在许多方面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.583,
        "end": 192.083,
        "text": "小说遵循一个共同的叙事线索，"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.083,
        "end": 197.053,
        "text": "一个有前途的年轻人被城市 生活的险恶所诱惑和腐蚀，"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.053,
        "end": 200.125,
        "text": "但作品对社会的批评更加深刻。"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.125,
        "end": 202.79500000000002,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫认为，"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.79500000000002,
        "end": 206.355,
        "text": "杀死剥削他人的当铺老板的行为 乃“替天行道”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.355,
        "end": 209.235,
        "text": "对社会有益无害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.235,
        "end": 210.245,
        "text": "他的做法"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.245,
        "end": 214.04500000000002,
        "text": "正契合陀思妥耶夫斯基时代"
      },
      {
        "start": 214.04500000000002,
        "end": 218.45499999999998,
        "text": "许多知识分子所信奉的 自我主义和功利主义思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.45499999999998,
        "end": 223.442,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫认定自己的才智 给予了他超越道德禁忌的权力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.442,
        "end": 227.369,
        "text": "并最终走向了人性的堕落。"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.369,
        "end": 230.459,
        "text": "尽管《罪与罚》 深刻探讨了有关道德的话题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.459,
        "end": 234.299,
        "text": "这本书从来都不是单纯的道德说教，"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.299,
        "end": 239.06900000000002,
        "text": "每个人物都有其独特 而有说服力的声音。"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.06900000000002,
        "end": 242.118,
        "text": "《罪与罚》最引人注目的一点就在于"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.118,
        "end": 245.488,
        "text": "尽管第一幕就详细描绘了 作为故事高潮的谋杀案，"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.488,
        "end": 248.578,
        "text": "全书依然让人欲罢不能。"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.578,
        "end": 251.03,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫的“罪”显而易见。"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.03,
        "end": 253.62,
        "text": "但是，只有通过陀思妥耶夫斯基"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.62,
        "end": 257.25,
        "text": "对社会动荡和主人公内心挣扎 扣人心弦的描述，"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.25,
        "end": 260.69,
        "text": "我们才了解到他的“罚”的 真实本质——"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.69,
        "end": 263.55,
        "text": "以及救赎的可能性。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Why should you read 'Hamlet'?",
    "youtubeId": "QTu39aMg_mU",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Iseult Gillespie",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.746,
        "end": 7.996,
        "text": "“是谁在那儿？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 7.996,
        "end": 9.204,
        "text": "黑暗中，有人悄声问，"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.204,
        "end": 15.329,
        "text": "一个有关阴谋、欺骗和道德模糊的故事 由这个问题开始。"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.329,
        "end": 18.163,
        "text": "在剧中每个人都有所隐瞒，"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.163,
        "end": 20.663,
        "text": "因此答案并不简单。"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.663,
        "end": 24.288,
        "text": "《哈姆雷特》由威廉·莎士比亚 写于 1599 至 1601 年，"
      },
      {
        "start": 24.288,
        "end": 28.204,
        "text": "它讲述了主人公哈姆雷特被过去所困，"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.204,
        "end": 30.871,
        "text": "面对未来又踌躇不前。"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.871,
        "end": 33.537,
        "text": "他父亲突然去世的仅仅几个月后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.537,
        "end": 37.496,
        "text": "他从学校回到家， 像一个陌生人一样归来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.496,
        "end": 40.871,
        "text": "他很不确定黑暗中有什么在潜行。"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.871,
        "end": 44.454,
        "text": "但在一个顶着他父亲的脸的鬼魂 找过他后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.454,
        "end": 46.787,
        "text": "他的忧虑发生了转变。"
      },
      {
        "start": 46.787,
        "end": 51.621,
        "text": "鬼魂声称死于一场“最狠毒”的谋杀，"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.621,
        "end": 55.246,
        "text": "还使哈姆雷特相信 他叔叔克劳狄斯篡夺了王位，"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.246,
        "end": 58.371,
        "text": "还勾引了皇后乔特鲁德。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.371,
        "end": 60.871,
        "text": "王子哈姆雷特的悲痛转为愤怒，"
      },
      {
        "start": 60.871,
        "end": 65.788,
        "text": "他开始策划一场 对新国王和他同谋的朝廷的复仇。"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.204,
        "end": 68.82900000000001,
        "text": "这部戏剧是一部有些奇怪的悲剧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 68.82900000000001,
        "end": 73.32900000000001,
        "text": "它缺少突然爆发的暴力， 以及不顾一切的爱情，"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.32900000000001,
        "end": 76.57900000000001,
        "text": "而这些都是莎士比亚同类作品的特点。"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.57900000000001,
        "end": 81.038,
        "text": "相反，它极力表现了主人公的犹豫不决"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.038,
        "end": 84.163,
        "text": "以及由此引发的悲剧。"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.163,
        "end": 87.82900000000001,
        "text": "鬼魂对真相的揭露 使哈姆雷特陷入了许多困境——"
      },
      {
        "start": 87.82900000000001,
        "end": 90.288,
        "text": "他应该做什么， 可以相信谁,"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.288,
        "end": 93.82900000000001,
        "text": "在伸张正义的过程中， 他可以扮演什么角色。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.82900000000001,
        "end": 97.87100000000001,
        "text": "这些问题因复杂的人物关系 变得更为复杂，"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.87100000000001,
        "end": 101.038,
        "text": "迫使哈姆雷特与朋友、家人、"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.038,
        "end": 103.413,
        "text": "朝臣、爱人周旋，"
      },
      {
        "start": 103.413,
        "end": 106.57900000000001,
        "text": "这些人中很多人都别有用心。"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.57900000000001,
        "end": 110.663,
        "text": "哈姆雷特在如何理解别人、 如何实施复仇的问题上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.663,
        "end": 112.913,
        "text": "一直在拖延和犹豫不决，"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.913,
        "end": 116.70400000000001,
        "text": "这令他显得非常令人生气，"
      },
      {
        "start": 116.70400000000001,
        "end": 121.371,
        "text": "但又让他成为莎士比亚笔下 最有人性的人物之一。"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.371,
        "end": 122.996,
        "text": "哈姆雷特没有冲动地做事，"
      },
      {
        "start": 122.996,
        "end": 127.704,
        "text": "而是沉浸在思考复仇计划本身。"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.704,
        "end": 129.121,
        "text": "并且，在整部剧中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.121,
        "end": 133.788,
        "text": "他的无数问题 也在我们飞快的思绪中引起了共鸣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.788,
        "end": 134.954,
        "text": "为了达到这样的效果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.954,
        "end": 138.079,
        "text": "莎士比亚运用了他最内省的语言。"
      },
      {
        "start": 138.079,
        "end": 142.204,
        "text": "从篡位国王对天堂和地狱的激烈思考，"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.204,
        "end": 145.996,
        "text": "到王子对死亡必然性的反复思索。"
      },
      {
        "start": 145.996,
        "end": 150.454,
        "text": "莎士比亚用忧郁的独白打动人心。"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.454,
        "end": 155.871,
        "text": "也许，最经典的例子就是 哈姆雷特最著名的那段忧虑的宣言："
      },
      {
        "start": 155.871,
        "end": 163.079,
        "text": "“生存还是毁灭—— 这是一个值得考虑的问题："
      },
      {
        "start": 163.079,
        "end": 166.663,
        "text": "是默然忍受"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.663,
        "end": 171.704,
        "text": "命运的暴虐的毒箭，"
      },
      {
        "start": 171.704,
        "end": 176.204,
        "text": "或是挺身反抗人世间的无涯的苦难，"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.204,
        "end": 180.996,
        "text": "通过斗争把它扫清，哪一种更高贵？”"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.996,
        "end": 183.996,
        "text": "这段独白体现了哈姆雷特 关于存在的困境："
      },
      {
        "start": 183.996,
        "end": 186.621,
        "text": "在想法和行动间左右为难，"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.621,
        "end": 190.704,
        "text": "无法选择生还是死。"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.704,
        "end": 194.038,
        "text": "但他无休止的疑问引起了另一个忧虑："
      },
      {
        "start": 194.038,
        "end": 198.371,
        "text": "哈姆雷特疯癫的表现是为了迷惑敌人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.371,
        "end": 202.038,
        "text": "还是真的处于精神失常边缘？"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.038,
        "end": 205.704,
        "text": "哈姆雷特的疑问深深影响了 他与每个角色的交往。"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.704,
        "end": 208.788,
        "text": "由于他花了很多时间向内思考，"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.788,
        "end": 212.954,
        "text": "常常看不到自己造成的破坏。"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.954,
        "end": 215.121,
        "text": "他对欧菲利亚特别残酷，"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.121,
        "end": 220.329,
        "text": "他绝望的爱人 因他难以捉摸的行为变疯。"
      },
      {
        "start": 220.329,
        "end": 224.496,
        "text": "她的命运反映了悲剧本应可轻易避免，"
      },
      {
        "start": 224.496,
        "end": 229.371,
        "text": "也表现了哈姆雷特致命心理游戏的 连锁反应。"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.371,
        "end": 234.454,
        "text": "在整部戏剧中， 类似的悲剧警示一直被忽视。"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.454,
        "end": 237.788,
        "text": "有时，这些疏忽是因为有意的无视——"
      },
      {
        "start": 237.788,
        "end": 241.413,
        "text": "比如欧菲利亚的父亲不理会 哈姆雷特可怕的行为，"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.413,
        "end": 243.704,
        "text": "只把它当作相思病。"
      },
      {
        "start": 243.704,
        "end": 247.829,
        "text": "在其它方面，悲剧源于故意的欺骗——"
      },
      {
        "start": 247.829,
        "end": 253.079,
        "text": "比如因为一次认错人，引发更多的死亡。"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.079,
        "end": 255.704,
        "text": "这些情况让我们难过地认识到，"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.704,
        "end": 259.496,
        "text": "悲剧是由人们的错误演变而来的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 259.496,
        "end": 263.746,
        "text": "即使我们只是错在不去做决定。"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.746,
        "end": 269.829,
        "text": "综上，也许我们唯独不应怀疑的 是哈姆雷特的人性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 269.829,
        "end": 275.121,
        "text": "但我们应该不断设法想出 “真正的”哈姆雷特可能是谁。"
      },
      {
        "start": 275.121,
        "end": 278.454,
        "text": "他是一个为父报仇的贵族子弟吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.454,
        "end": 281.704,
        "text": "还是一个制造宫廷混乱的疯掉的王子？"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.704,
        "end": 284.788,
        "text": "他应该行动还是观察， 怀疑还是相信？"
      },
      {
        "start": 284.788,
        "end": 288.371,
        "text": "他是谁？为什么在这里？"
      },
      {
        "start": 288.371,
        "end": 292.371,
        "text": "还有谁在外面——在黑暗中等待？"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Why should you read 'Dune' by Frank Herbert?",
    "youtubeId": "yhYU4ZbLmmk",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Dan Kwartler",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.758,
        "end": 10.276,
        "text": "一位母亲和她的儿子 穿过了无尽的沙漠。"
      },
      {
        "start": 10.276,
        "end": 14.844,
        "text": "他们穿着用来驱除热气、 保持湿度的特质紧身衣。"
      },
      {
        "start": 14.844,
        "end": 17.596,
        "text": "这两位旅行者并不担心 缺水死亡，"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.596,
        "end": 19.862,
        "text": "他们的恐惧比那大得多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.862,
        "end": 22.23,
        "text": "他们试图不规律地行走，"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.23,
        "end": 26.399,
        "text": "让他们脚印的痕迹融入流沙中。"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.399,
        "end": 31.034,
        "text": "但很快，沙漠被一种 更大的嘶嘶声包围笼罩。"
      },
      {
        "start": 31.034,
        "end": 33.564,
        "text": "当一座沙丘向他们奔来时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 33.564,
        "end": 37.086,
        "text": "他们不自然的步伐改为了短跑。"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.086,
        "end": 39.908,
        "text": "他们爬上了岩石表面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.908,
        "end": 44.99,
        "text": "与此同时，一个 400 米长的爆破 从沙漠地表拔地而起。"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.99,
        "end": 48.141,
        "text": "这就是《沙丘》的世界。"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.141,
        "end": 51.681,
        "text": "由弗兰克 · 赫伯特（Frank Herbert） 创作并发表于 1965 年，"
      },
      {
        "start": 51.681,
        "end": 54.444,
        "text": "《沙丘》的时间背景 是遥远的未来，"
      },
      {
        "start": 54.444,
        "end": 58.448,
        "text": "人类通过一个巨大的 封建帝国管理各个行星。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.448,
        "end": 62.115,
        "text": "这中世纪的理念 不仅体现在政府系统中。"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.115,
        "end": 64.207,
        "text": "和大部分的星际科幻小说不同，"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.207,
        "end": 67.801,
        "text": "赫伯特的人类征服宇宙时， 没有使用任何电脑。"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.801,
        "end": 70.118,
        "text": "在一次与机器人的古老战争后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 70.118,
        "end": 73.754,
        "text": "不论在那种机器制作中， 任何的“仿人类意识”设计"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.754,
        "end": 76.188,
        "text": "都被人类禁止了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 76.188,
        "end": 78.589,
        "text": "但相比于抑制他们的发展，"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.589,
        "end": 82.292,
        "text": "这条法令强迫人们 用非常震惊的方式去进化——"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.292,
        "end": 87.97800000000001,
        "text": "成为生物意义上的电脑， 心理上的女巫，以及有先见之明的宇航员。"
      },
      {
        "start": 87.97800000000001,
        "end": 90.351,
        "text": "这些超能力组织的成员"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.351,
        "end": 94.036,
        "text": "常常会被不同的贵族所聘。"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.036,
        "end": 98.988,
        "text": "这些贵族为了扩张自己的王国， 互相竞争权力并夺取新的星球。"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.988,
        "end": 104.30799999999999,
        "text": "但是几乎所有的超人类技能 都依赖于同一种资源："
      },
      {
        "start": 104.30799999999999,
        "end": 105.708,
        "text": "香料。"
      },
      {
        "start": 105.708,
        "end": 111.44200000000001,
        "text": "这种神秘的作物也被称为“美兰极”， 是所有宇宙旅行的必需，"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.44200000000001,
        "end": 114.458,
        "text": "是星际经济的基石。"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.458,
        "end": 117.925,
        "text": "它只生长于阿拉吉斯星球上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.925,
        "end": 121.546,
        "text": "一个危险且难以居住的世界，"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.546,
        "end": 124.634,
        "text": "土著民长期暴乱。"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.634,
        "end": 128.599,
        "text": "阿拉吉斯，也被称作“沙丘” 是赫伯特小说的背景地点，"
      },
      {
        "start": 128.599,
        "end": 132.723,
        "text": "贵族亚崔迪家族 保罗的迁徙地。"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.723,
        "end": 136.679,
        "text": "这本书的开头为保罗一家 被下令管理沙丘，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.679,
        "end": 139.923,
        "text": "作为他们死敌的 奴隶虐待狂贵族——哈肯尼家族"
      },
      {
        "start": 139.923,
        "end": 143.565,
        "text": "缜密阴谋的一部分。"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.565,
        "end": 148.725,
        "text": "这些贵族之间的矛盾 打破了阿拉吉斯脆弱的政治平衡。"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.725,
        "end": 152.877,
        "text": "很快，保罗突然被迫参与到了 一场星际革命之中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.877,
        "end": 156.06799999999998,
        "text": "他必须要证明 他的领导能力——"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.06799999999998,
        "end": 159.635,
        "text": "并且在这充满敌意的沙漠中 生存下来。"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.635,
        "end": 163.054,
        "text": "但是阿拉吉斯 不仅仅是一片无尽的沙海。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.054,
        "end": 165.471,
        "text": "赫伯特是一位狂热的环境学家，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.471,
        "end": 169.473,
        "text": "他用了 5 年多的时间 创造了沙丘复杂的生态系统。"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.473,
        "end": 172.81900000000002,
        "text": "这个星球有复杂的气候带和风洞，"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.81900000000002,
        "end": 175.368,
        "text": "这塑造了它蜿蜒的地势。"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.368,
        "end": 178.703,
        "text": "不同的温度区 导致了不同的沙漠植物群。"
      },
      {
        "start": 178.703,
        "end": 182.193,
        "text": "几乎每一片沙丘的 生态元素都互相作用"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.193,
        "end": 184.989,
        "text": "生产星球中最重要的出口。"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.989,
        "end": 190.342,
        "text": "赫伯特的世界也包括了 丰富的哲学和宗教网。"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.342,
        "end": 193.89600000000002,
        "text": "保罗的母亲，杰西卡 是本尼 · 吉斯姐妹会的成员，"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.89600000000002,
        "end": 197.07999999999998,
        "text": "一个古老的 香料辅助心理学组织。"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.07999999999998,
        "end": 200.099,
        "text": "有时候因为她们的神秘力量 而被称作“女巫”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.099,
        "end": 204.461,
        "text": "本尼 · 吉斯姐妹会 作为影子政府运作了千年"
      },
      {
        "start": 204.461,
        "end": 207.971,
        "text": "致力于带领社会走向教化。"
      },
      {
        "start": 207.971,
        "end": 210.553,
        "text": "同样古老的还有门塔特——"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.553,
        "end": 214.622,
        "text": "能够处理惊人数量数据 的人类电脑。"
      },
      {
        "start": 214.622,
        "end": 217.45600000000002,
        "text": "门塔特作为 逻辑与理性的城堡，"
      },
      {
        "start": 217.45600000000002,
        "end": 219.94,
        "text": "他们的输出结果不仅是计算，"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.94,
        "end": 223.976,
        "text": "而是一串不断变化的可能性。"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.976,
        "end": 228.395,
        "text": "但是，沙丘中最中心的群体 还是弗瑞曼人。"
      },
      {
        "start": 228.395,
        "end": 233.13,
        "text": "阿拉吉斯的土著人， 他们是这个星球秘密的守护者。"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.13,
        "end": 236.836,
        "text": "保罗的旅程让他潜入 费瑞曼人的特有兄弟会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.836,
        "end": 239.75900000000001,
        "text": "在那，他必须通过 一系列的致命挑战"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.75900000000001,
        "end": 241.993,
        "text": "来证明他的可信度。"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.993,
        "end": 245.904,
        "text": "每一部分都有 很丰富的历史蕴含在文中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.904,
        "end": 249.695,
        "text": "赫伯特也包括了 本书结构的规模感。"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.695,
        "end": 253.397,
        "text": "每一章都以未来历史书中的 一句名言开始，"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.397,
        "end": 256.73199999999997,
        "text": "回忆那些即将被展开叙述的 事件中的元素。"
      },
      {
        "start": 256.73199999999997,
        "end": 260.033,
        "text": "这本书也包括了宇宙中的附录"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.033,
        "end": 262.618,
        "text": "来进一步解释帝国的历史。"
      },
      {
        "start": 262.618,
        "end": 267.328,
        "text": "也包括词汇表，囊括像是“戈姆贾巴尔” 和“西胡鲁德”的词汇。"
      },
      {
        "start": 267.328,
        "end": 273.673,
        "text": "《沙丘》的史诗性故事通过 长达 10 年时间跨度的 6 本书继续展开。"
      },
      {
        "start": 273.673,
        "end": 277.109,
        "text": "但是每一个阿拉吉斯家族的 未来都由此开始："
      },
      {
        "start": 277.109,
        "end": 281.028,
        "text": "保罗继续在一条 危险苛刻的道路上不断被追赶，"
      },
      {
        "start": 281.028,
        "end": 286.129,
        "text": "并且总是在处于即将到来的 风暴的吞噬边缘。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "The myth of Prometheus",
    "youtubeId": "U_u91SjrEOE",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Iseult Gillespie",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 7.041,
        "end": 8.745,
        "text": "在创造人类之前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 8.745,
        "end": 13.827,
        "text": "希腊诸神赢得了一场伟大的战斗， 击败了泰坦巨人种族。"
      },
      {
        "start": 13.827,
        "end": 18.606,
        "text": "大多数的泰坦都被摧毁 或驱赶到了永恒的地狱里。"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.606,
        "end": 21.646,
        "text": "但名字意味着预见的 泰坦巨人普罗米修斯，"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.646,
        "end": 27.836,
        "text": "说服了他的兄弟厄庇墨透斯 与他一同在神的一边作战。"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.836,
        "end": 30.408,
        "text": "作为答谢，宙斯委以兄弟俩"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.408,
        "end": 34.437,
        "text": "创造所有生物的重任。"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.437,
        "end": 38.737,
        "text": "厄庇墨透斯将神的恩赐 分发给这些生物。"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.737,
        "end": 40.168,
        "text": "他给了一些生物飞行的本领，"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.168,
        "end": 42.776,
        "text": "给了另一些生物在水中游的能力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.776,
        "end": 45.088,
        "text": "或者是在草从中奔跑的本事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 45.088,
        "end": 47.209,
        "text": "他给了一些猛兽闪闪发光的鳞片、"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.209,
        "end": 48.219,
        "text": "柔软的皮毛，"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.219,
        "end": 50.768,
        "text": "和锋利的爪子。"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.768,
        "end": 55.388,
        "text": "同时， 普罗米修斯 用泥做出第一个人形，"
      },
      {
        "start": 55.388,
        "end": 57.831,
        "text": "效仿诸神的样貌。"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.831,
        "end": 60.368,
        "text": "但是宙斯发布命令规定 这些人类必须维持平凡，"
      },
      {
        "start": 60.368,
        "end": 65.382,
        "text": "同时要在山下 供奉奥林匹斯山的居民。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.382,
        "end": 69.822,
        "text": "宙斯把人类看作是怯懦的生物， 容易受到各种因素影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.822,
        "end": 72.92,
        "text": "并且依赖诸神保护。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.92,
        "end": 78.61,
        "text": "但是普罗米修斯对于他创造的生物 拥有更美好的设想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.61,
        "end": 82.453,
        "text": "当宙斯让他决定人类该如何献祭时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.453,
        "end": 88.764,
        "text": "机智的普罗米修斯想出了一招 来帮助人类。"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.764,
        "end": 93.924,
        "text": "他宰了一头牛， 并把牛分成两部分呈给宙斯。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.924,
        "end": 97.24000000000001,
        "text": "其中一部分， 他把美味多汁的皮和肉"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.24000000000001,
        "end": 100.825,
        "text": "藏在了难看的肚皮下面。"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.825,
        "end": 104.58,
        "text": "另一部分， 他把骨头藏在了一层很厚的肥肉下。"
      },
      {
        "start": 104.58,
        "end": 108.255,
        "text": "当宙斯选了看起来 更有吸引力的那一部分，"
      },
      {
        "start": 108.255,
        "end": 112.146,
        "text": "他对普罗米修斯的欺骗行为 感到非常愤怒。"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.146,
        "end": 115.60499999999999,
        "text": "火冒三丈的宙斯 禁止了人间用火，"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.60499999999999,
        "end": 119.73599999999999,
        "text": "无论是烧肉还是其他用途。"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.73599999999999,
        "end": 124.487,
        "text": "但普罗米修斯不愿意 看到他创造的人类失去这一资源。"
      },
      {
        "start": 124.487,
        "end": 127.565,
        "text": "因此，他爬上了奥林匹斯山，"
      },
      {
        "start": 127.565,
        "end": 131.474,
        "text": "从赫菲斯托斯和 雅典娜那里盗取火种。"
      },
      {
        "start": 131.474,
        "end": 136.985,
        "text": "他把火焰藏在一根空心的茴香秆中， 并把它安全地送到人间。"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.985,
        "end": 140.473,
        "text": "火使人类能利用自然为自身造福，"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.476,
        "end": 144.558,
        "text": "也带给了人类战胜自然的力量。"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.558,
        "end": 149.056,
        "text": "有了火， 人类可以烹饪食物和取暖，"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.056,
        "end": 152.978,
        "text": "还可以打造武器，发动战争。"
      },
      {
        "start": 152.978,
        "end": 159.316,
        "text": "普罗米修斯的火种 是人类文明进步的催化剂。"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.316,
        "end": 163.617,
        "text": "当宙斯发现人间烟火袅袅， 他才意识到发生了什么。"
      },
      {
        "start": 163.617,
        "end": 166.46699999999998,
        "text": "普罗米修斯再一次伤害了 他的自尊心，"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.46699999999998,
        "end": 168.867,
        "text": "颠覆了他的权威。"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.867,
        "end": 172.048,
        "text": "暴怒的宙斯决定 狠狠惩罚普罗米修斯，"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.048,
        "end": 176.209,
        "text": "用铁链把他永远锁在悬崖绝壁上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.209,
        "end": 180.387,
        "text": "一只秃鹰每天都会去 啄食普罗米修斯的肝脏，"
      },
      {
        "start": 180.387,
        "end": 186.639,
        "text": "每天晚上他的肝脏又会长回来， 第二天继续被啄食。"
      },
      {
        "start": 186.639,
        "end": 189.669,
        "text": "虽然普罗米修斯忍受着 巨大的痛苦，"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.669,
        "end": 193.529,
        "text": "但他从不后悔他的反叛行为。"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.529,
        "end": 198.719,
        "text": "他在面对压迫时的韧性 使他成为人们钟爱的神话人物。"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.719,
        "end": 202.499,
        "text": "他也因机智和探索的精神,"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.499,
        "end": 208.1,
        "text": "以及他带给人类的知识， 进步和力量而闻名。"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.1,
        "end": 211.96,
        "text": "他也常在文学和艺术作品中出现。"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.96,
        "end": 215.381,
        "text": "在珀西·比希·雪莱的 抒情剧《解放了的普罗米修斯》中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.381,
        "end": 218.721,
        "text": "作者把普罗米修斯 描绘成一个浪漫主义的英雄，"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.721,
        "end": 223.45499999999998,
        "text": "他逃跑并继续传播同情和知识。"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.45499999999998,
        "end": 225.233,
        "text": "对于他笔下的主角，雪莱写到"
      },
      {
        "start": 225.233,
        "end": 227.94400000000002,
        "text": "“普罗米修斯是道德和智慧"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.94400000000002,
        "end": 230.517,
        "text": "最完美结合的化身，"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.517,
        "end": 233.145,
        "text": "受最纯粹和真实的目的驱动，"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.145,
        "end": 236.53300000000002,
        "text": "走向最好，最高贵的结局。“"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.53300000000002,
        "end": 240.866,
        "text": "雪莱的妻子玛丽把普罗米修斯 设想成一个更加警世的人物，"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.866,
        "end": 246.067,
        "text": "并给她的小说命名为 《科学怪人：现代普罗米修斯》。"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.067,
        "end": 249.446,
        "text": "内容指出破坏自然秩序的影响，"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.446,
        "end": 251.695,
        "text": "以及道德问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.695,
        "end": 255.936,
        "text": "一直围绕着现代科技。"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.936,
        "end": 258.086,
        "text": "作为一个英雄，反叛者， 或是骗子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.086,
        "end": 262.767,
        "text": "普罗米修斯是人类能够 利用自然力量的象征。"
      },
      {
        "start": 262.767,
        "end": 264.317,
        "text": "从根本上说，"
      },
      {
        "start": 264.317,
        "end": 269.078,
        "text": "他提醒我们 依靠个人力量来点燃世界的可能性。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "Why should you read 'Crime and Punishment'?",
    "youtubeId": "Vtkv3-endYc",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Alex Gendler",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.285,
        "end": 9.605,
        "text": "是什么驱使人变成了冷血杀手？"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.605,
        "end": 12.035,
        "text": "凶手心里想的是什么？"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.035,
        "end": 15.505,
        "text": "又是什么样的社会 造就了这样的人呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 15.505,
        "end": 17.725,
        "text": "150多年前，"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.725,
        "end": 21.465,
        "text": "费奥多尔·米哈伊洛维奇·陀思妥耶夫斯基 在作品中提出了上述问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 21.465,
        "end": 25.585,
        "text": "这部作品后来成为 俄国文学史上最著名的作品之一："
      },
      {
        "start": 26.025,
        "end": 27.386,
        "text": "《罪与罚》。"
      },
      {
        "start": 28.146,
        "end": 32.806,
        "text": "这部小说于1866年 首次在一本文学杂志上连载，"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.806,
        "end": 36.776,
        "text": "讲述了圣彼得堡一个年轻的法学生"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.776,
        "end": 39.967,
        "text": "罗迪·罗曼诺维奇·拉斯科尔尼科夫的故事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.217,
        "end": 42.907,
        "text": "拉斯科尔尼科夫的生活穷困潦倒，"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.907,
        "end": 47.357,
        "text": "故事开头的他因 交不起学费而辍学。"
      },
      {
        "start": 47.357,
        "end": 50.953,
        "text": "农村老家的来信使他更为沮丧，"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.953,
        "end": 56.513,
        "text": "他发现母亲和妹妹为了让他成功 已经牺牲太多了。"
      },
      {
        "start": 56.513,
        "end": 59.871,
        "text": "把最后一点值钱的东西 卖给当铺的老太婆后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 59.871,
        "end": 62.051,
        "text": "他更加绝望了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 62.051,
        "end": 65.861,
        "text": "他决心要杀掉当铺老板娘， 夺走她的钱财。"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.861,
        "end": 69.331,
        "text": "但实施这项鲁莽计划的后果，"
      },
      {
        "start": 69.331,
        "end": 72.801,
        "text": "比他预想的要严重得多。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.801,
        "end": 77.571,
        "text": "虽然该作有时被认为是 最早的心理惊悚小说之一，"
      },
      {
        "start": 77.571,
        "end": 81.837,
        "text": "小说所揭露的远不止 拉斯科利尼科夫内心的挣扎。"
      },
      {
        "start": 81.837,
        "end": 84.407,
        "text": "从潮湿的小酒馆，到破旧的公寓"
      },
      {
        "start": 84.407,
        "end": 86.967,
        "text": "和幽闭恐怖的警察局,"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.967,
        "end": 90.349,
        "text": "19世纪圣彼得堡的社会阴暗面"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.352,
        "end": 93.81700000000001,
        "text": "在陀思妥耶夫斯基 犀利的笔触下跃然纸上。"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.81700000000001,
        "end": 96.937,
        "text": "我们认识了诸多角色，例如马美拉多夫，"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.937,
        "end": 101.497,
        "text": "一位因酗酒而倾家荡产的可怜的下岗官员；"
      },
      {
        "start": 101.497,
        "end": 106.27199999999999,
        "text": "还有斯维里加洛夫， 一位傲慢、脾气暴躁的贵族。"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.27199999999999,
        "end": 109.368,
        "text": "当拉斯科利尼科夫的家人来到镇上时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 109.368,
        "end": 111.178,
        "text": "他们道德上的纯真"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.178,
        "end": 115.297,
        "text": "与周围人的堕落形成鲜明对比，"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.297,
        "end": 118.807,
        "text": "即使他们的命运逐渐交织在了一起。"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.807,
        "end": 121.167,
        "text": "这幅冷酷的俄罗斯社会肖像画，"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.167,
        "end": 126.517,
        "text": "反映了作者自身复杂的生活经历 和不断发展的思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.517,
        "end": 130.47,
        "text": "告别了前途无量的军队仕途， 费奥多尔成为一名年轻作家，"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.47,
        "end": 134.47,
        "text": "被社会主义和改革思想所吸引，"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.47,
        "end": 136.72,
        "text": "并加入了知识分子的圈子，"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.72,
        "end": 140.906,
        "text": "讨论被帝国政府禁止的激进文章。"
      },
      {
        "start": 141.326,
        "end": 142.576,
        "text": "暴露后，"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.576,
        "end": 146.276,
        "text": "包括陀思妥耶夫斯基在内的 团体成员被捕。"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.276,
        "end": 147.916,
        "text": "许多人被判处死刑，"
      },
      {
        "start": 147.916,
        "end": 153.546,
        "text": "在行刑前一刻才被沙皇赦免， 只经受了模拟处决。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.836,
        "end": 158.05599999999998,
        "text": "陀思妥耶夫斯基 在西伯利亚劳改营待了四年,"
      },
      {
        "start": 158.05599999999998,
        "end": 161.135,
        "text": "直到1854年才被释放。"
      },
      {
        "start": 161.135,
        "end": 165.883,
        "text": "这次经历让他对社会改革越发悲观，"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.883,
        "end": 169.381,
        "text": "他也把目光更多地投向了精神层面的话题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 169.381,
        "end": 173.281,
        "text": "在1864年的中篇小说 《地下室手记》中，"
      },
      {
        "start": 173.281,
        "end": 176.99099999999999,
        "text": "他阐述了他的观点， 认为乌托邦式的西方哲学"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.99099999999999,
        "end": 181.651,
        "text": "永远无法满足 人类灵魂中相互矛盾的欲望。"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.651,
        "end": 185.953,
        "text": "次年，他构思并完成了《罪与罚》，"
      },
      {
        "start": 185.953,
        "end": 188.593,
        "text": "书中许多主题与上篇小说相同。"
      },
      {
        "start": 188.593,
        "end": 189.583,
        "text": "在许多方面，"
      },
      {
        "start": 189.583,
        "end": 192.083,
        "text": "小说遵循一个共同的叙事线索，"
      },
      {
        "start": 192.083,
        "end": 197.053,
        "text": "一个有前途的年轻人被城市 生活的险恶所诱惑和腐蚀，"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.053,
        "end": 200.125,
        "text": "但作品对社会的批评更加深刻。"
      },
      {
        "start": 200.125,
        "end": 202.79500000000002,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫认为，"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.79500000000002,
        "end": 206.355,
        "text": "杀死剥削他人的当铺老板的行为 乃“替天行道”，"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.355,
        "end": 209.235,
        "text": "对社会有益无害。"
      },
      {
        "start": 209.235,
        "end": 210.245,
        "text": "他的做法"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.245,
        "end": 214.04500000000002,
        "text": "正契合陀思妥耶夫斯基时代"
      },
      {
        "start": 214.04500000000002,
        "end": 218.45499999999998,
        "text": "许多知识分子所信奉的 自我主义和功利主义思想。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.45499999999998,
        "end": 223.442,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫认定自己的才智 给予了他超越道德禁忌的权力，"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.442,
        "end": 227.369,
        "text": "并最终走向了人性的堕落。"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.369,
        "end": 230.459,
        "text": "尽管《罪与罚》 深刻探讨了有关道德的话题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.459,
        "end": 234.299,
        "text": "这本书从来都不是单纯的道德说教，"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.299,
        "end": 239.06900000000002,
        "text": "每个人物都有其独特 而有说服力的声音。"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.06900000000002,
        "end": 242.118,
        "text": "《罪与罚》最引人注目的一点就在于"
      },
      {
        "start": 242.118,
        "end": 245.488,
        "text": "尽管第一幕就详细描绘了 作为故事高潮的谋杀案，"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.488,
        "end": 248.578,
        "text": "全书依然让人欲罢不能。"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.578,
        "end": 251.03,
        "text": "拉斯科利尼科夫的“罪”显而易见。"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.03,
        "end": 253.62,
        "text": "但是，只有通过陀思妥耶夫斯基"
      },
      {
        "start": 253.62,
        "end": 257.25,
        "text": "对社会动荡和主人公内心挣扎 扣人心弦的描述，"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.25,
        "end": 260.69,
        "text": "我们才了解到他的“罚”的 真实本质——"
      },
      {
        "start": 260.69,
        "end": 263.55,
        "text": "以及救赎的可能性。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "What 'Orwellian' really means",
    "youtubeId": "oe64p-QzhNE",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Noah Tavlin",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.342,
        "end": 9.363,
        "text": "如果你看新闻或者关注政治"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.363,
        "end": 11.839,
        "text": "那么你很有可能听说过“奥威尔现象”"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.839,
        "end": 14.834,
        "text": "频繁地出现在不同的语境中"
      },
      {
        "start": 14.834,
        "end": 17.821,
        "text": "但是你可能会停下来， 好奇这个词究竟是什么意思"
      },
      {
        "start": 17.821,
        "end": 20.425,
        "text": "为什么被这样频繁地使用"
      },
      {
        "start": 20.425,
        "end": 23.475,
        "text": "这个词是根据英国作家 埃里克·布莱尔命名的"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.475,
        "end": 26.883,
        "text": "他的笔名就是乔治·奥威尔"
      },
      {
        "start": 26.883,
        "end": 30.36,
        "text": "在他的最著名的作品《1984》中"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.36,
        "end": 34.377,
        "text": "描述了一个被极权主义政府压制的社会"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.377,
        "end": 38.904,
        "text": "“奥威尔现象”经常被简单地指代专制主义"
      },
      {
        "start": 38.904,
        "end": 40.808,
        "text": "但是这样使用这个词"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.808,
        "end": 43.919,
        "text": "不仅并未传达奥威尔的全意"
      },
      {
        "start": 43.919,
        "end": 50.155,
        "text": "反而有可能适得其反"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.155,
        "end": 53.604,
        "text": "奥威尔确实是反对各种形式的专政"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.604,
        "end": 57.225,
        "text": "他倾其一生对抗反民主力量"
      },
      {
        "start": 57.225,
        "end": 60.53,
        "text": "不论是左翼还是右翼"
      },
      {
        "start": 60.53,
        "end": 65.713,
        "text": "但是他也非常担心这样的思想滋生扩散的方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 65.713,
        "end": 67.606,
        "text": "他最著名的一个见解就是"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.606,
        "end": 73.712,
        "text": "语言在塑造思想和意见中起到重要作用"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.712,
        "end": 79.33500000000001,
        "text": "《1984》中的大洋国的政府"
      },
      {
        "start": 79.33500000000001,
        "end": 82.58,
        "text": "用一种明显的方式控制了人们的行动和言语"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.58,
        "end": 86.40299999999999,
        "text": "他们的一言一行都被监视，"
      },
      {
        "start": 86.40299999999999,
        "end": 89.362,
        "text": "行为异常的下场"
      },
      {
        "start": 89.362,
        "end": 93.213,
        "text": "时刻威胁着所有人"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.213,
        "end": 96.814,
        "text": "其他的控制形式没有这么明显"
      },
      {
        "start": 96.814,
        "end": 100.667,
        "text": "所有的人民都被蒙蔽"
      },
      {
        "start": 100.667,
        "end": 107.93299999999999,
        "text": "在\"真理部门\"捏造的所谓“史实”和数据中"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.93299999999999,
        "end": 111.04599999999999,
        "text": "和平部负责军事"
      },
      {
        "start": 111.04599999999999,
        "end": 113.97200000000001,
        "text": "劳动营被叫做“欢乐营”"
      },
      {
        "start": 113.97200000000001,
        "end": 119.807,
        "text": "政治囚犯被\"友爱部\"囚禁和折磨"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.807,
        "end": 123.645,
        "text": "这种故意的讽刺就是“双重思想”的一个例证"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.645,
        "end": 128.012,
        "text": "言语不为传达却为扭曲其含义"
      },
      {
        "start": 128.012,
        "end": 132.219,
        "text": "腐坏了每个观点的本意"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.219,
        "end": 135.036,
        "text": "政权的言语控制还有更过分的方法"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.036,
        "end": 137.13,
        "text": "从英语中剔除词汇"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.13,
        "end": 140.502,
        "text": "在新闻媒体上塑造官方说法"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.502,
        "end": 144.843,
        "text": "一个简陋的、满是缩写和简单名词的集合"
      },
      {
        "start": 144.843,
        "end": 150.913,
        "text": "缺乏能够表达细微和关键观点的复杂词汇"
      },
      {
        "start": 150.913,
        "end": 155.144,
        "text": "这就产生了一种 被奥威尔叫做“双重思想”的心理现象"
      },
      {
        "start": 155.144,
        "end": 157.452,
        "text": "一种催眠状态下的认知失调"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.452,
        "end": 160.833,
        "text": "在此状态下， 人们被强迫放弃自己的认知"
      },
      {
        "start": 160.833,
        "end": 164.57999999999998,
        "text": "取而代之的是事件解读的官方版本"
      },
      {
        "start": 164.57999999999998,
        "end": 166.739,
        "text": "使个人完全依附于"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.739,
        "end": 170.897,
        "text": "政府定义下的“现实”"
      },
      {
        "start": 170.897,
        "end": 172.079,
        "text": "这样的结果就是"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.079,
        "end": 176.608,
        "text": "个人独立的思维过程被侵犯"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.608,
        "end": 182.261,
        "text": "梦呓可能被认定是思想犯罪"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.261,
        "end": 184.887,
        "text": "写日记或者发生外遇"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.887,
        "end": 190.087,
        "text": "被认为是反叛的颠覆性行为"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.087,
        "end": 195.49,
        "text": "这看起来只有在极权政体下 才可能发生的现象"
      },
      {
        "start": 195.49,
        "end": 198.958,
        "text": "但是奥威尔警示我们"
      },
      {
        "start": 198.958,
        "end": 202.296,
        "text": "这种现象在民主社会仍有可能发生"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.296,
        "end": 208.622,
        "text": "这就是为什么单单“专制主义” 并不等同与“奥威尔现象”"
      },
      {
        "start": 208.622,
        "end": 211.281,
        "text": "在他的《政治与英语语言》一文中"
      },
      {
        "start": 211.281,
        "end": 215.756,
        "text": "他描述了各种手段， 诸如矫饰词汇来形容权威"
      },
      {
        "start": 215.756,
        "end": 219.897,
        "text": "或者用委婉说法掩盖残暴行径， 使其得到接受"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.897,
        "end": 222.848,
        "text": "或者迂回扭曲句子结构"
      },
      {
        "start": 222.848,
        "end": 227.666,
        "text": "更平常的语言滥用 也可以影响我们的思维方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 227.666,
        "end": 230.781,
        "text": "我们每天在广告中看到听到的言论"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.781,
        "end": 235.852,
        "text": "都是为了吸引观众和改变其行为而塑造的"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.852,
        "end": 240.038,
        "text": "政治竞选中的评述和论点亦是如此"
      },
      {
        "start": 240.038,
        "end": 244.917,
        "text": "这些都很少表达出细致的观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 244.917,
        "end": 249.825,
        "text": "在我们使用这些媒体报道中 现成的短语或者评论"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.825,
        "end": 251.918,
        "text": "或者从网络上复制内容的时候"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.918,
        "end": 255.478,
        "text": "就很少再去深刻思考"
      },
      {
        "start": 255.478,
        "end": 258.434,
        "text": "或者质疑前提假设"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.434,
        "end": 261.324,
        "text": "下一次你听到某人使用 “奥威尔现象这次词”的时候"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.324,
        "end": 263.152,
        "text": "可要注意了"
      },
      {
        "start": 263.152,
        "end": 266.588,
        "text": "如果他们说的是对语言的欺诈性 和操控性使用"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.588,
        "end": 269.067,
        "text": "这是正确的使用方式"
      },
      {
        "start": 269.067,
        "end": 272.374,
        "text": "如果他们说的是大规模监视 和干预型政府"
      },
      {
        "start": 272.374,
        "end": 278.141,
        "text": "那他们更像是在说“专制主义”， 而不一定是“奥威尔现象”"
      },
      {
        "start": 278.141,
        "end": 282.348,
        "text": "如果他们试图用万能词汇 描述他们反对的观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.348,
        "end": 286.047,
        "text": "那么有可能他们正表现出了“奥威尔现象”"
      },
      {
        "start": 286.047,
        "end": 290.319,
        "text": "而非他们所批评的内容"
      },
      {
        "start": 290.319,
        "end": 292.158,
        "text": "词汇有塑造思维的力量"
      },
      {
        "start": 292.158,
        "end": 295.975,
        "text": "语言是政治的流通货币"
      },
      {
        "start": 295.975,
        "end": 299.861,
        "text": "从日常互动到高级理想"
      },
      {
        "start": 299.861,
        "end": 302.817,
        "text": "建立社会的基础"
      },
      {
        "start": 302.817,
        "end": 305.575,
        "text": "奥威尔劝告我们去保护我们的语言"
      },
      {
        "start": 305.575,
        "end": 309.305,
        "text": "因为，思考和交流的能力"
      },
      {
        "start": 309.305,
        "end": 313.381,
        "text": "正是我们与一个颠倒的世界之间的屏障"
      },
      {
        "start": 313.381,
        "end": 315.919,
        "text": "在那里，战争即和平，奴役即自由。"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "How to recognize a dystopia",
    "youtubeId": "6a6kbU88wu0",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Alex Gendler",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 6.953,
        "end": 9.856,
        "text": "你曾尝试想象过一个理想的世界吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 9.856,
        "end": 12.676,
        "text": "一个没有战争，贫穷，和犯罪的世界？"
      },
      {
        "start": 12.676,
        "end": 14.636,
        "text": "如果有，那你并不是一个人"
      },
      {
        "start": 14.636,
        "end": 19.206,
        "text": "柏拉图想象了一个由顶尖哲学家统治的开化的共和国"
      },
      {
        "start": 19.206,
        "end": 22.077,
        "text": "许多宗教都期望来世的极乐"
      },
      {
        "start": 22.077,
        "end": 23.382,
        "text": "并且纵观整个历史，"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.382,
        "end": 27.447,
        "text": "许多群体都曾尝试在地球上创建天堂"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.447,
        "end": 32.926,
        "text": "托马斯·莫尔在1516年出版的书《乌托邦》 给了这个概念一个名字"
      },
      {
        "start": 32.926,
        "end": 35.517,
        "text": "希腊语指”没有地方“"
      },
      {
        "start": 35.517,
        "end": 37.707,
        "text": "虽然这个名字暗指了不可能性"
      },
      {
        "start": 37.707,
        "end": 40.077,
        "text": "但现代科学和政治的进步"
      },
      {
        "start": 40.077,
        "end": 44.068,
        "text": "使实现这些梦想的希望最终变得现实"
      },
      {
        "start": 44.068,
        "end": 48.007,
        "text": "但是一次又一次，它们相反地变成了"
      },
      {
        "start": 48.007,
        "end": 50.837,
        "text": "战争，饥荒和压迫的噩梦"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.837,
        "end": 53.988,
        "text": "并且当艺术家们开始质疑乌托邦的想法时"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.988,
        "end": 58.768,
        "text": "反乌托邦题材--“不好的地方”应运而生"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.768,
        "end": 63.418,
        "text": "乔纳森·斯威夫特的《格列佛游记》 是最早的反乌托邦题材作品之一"
      },
      {
        "start": 63.418,
        "end": 66.738,
        "text": "在他的整个旅行过程中，格列佛偶遇了一些虚构的社会"
      },
      {
        "start": 66.738,
        "end": 71.728,
        "text": "其中有一些起初看起来是使人敬畏的， 但结果却是有严重缺陷的社会"
      },
      {
        "start": 71.728,
        "end": 73.628,
        "text": "在格列佛游记中"
      },
      {
        "start": 73.628,
        "end": 78.287,
        "text": "科学家和社会规划师追寻夸张和无用的计划"
      },
      {
        "start": 78.287,
        "end": 82.14699999999999,
        "text": "而忽视下层人的实际需要"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.14699999999999,
        "end": 85.168,
        "text": "同时生活在完全合理的和谐中的Houyhnhnm人"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.168,
        "end": 90.128,
        "text": "一点也不能忍受人类的缺陷"
      },
      {
        "start": 90.128,
        "end": 93.488,
        "text": "在他的小说中，斯威夫特为反乌托邦构建了一个蓝图"
      },
      {
        "start": 93.488,
        "end": 97.179,
        "text": "他想象了一个世界，在这个世界中"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.179,
        "end": 98.928,
        "text": "存在在当代社会的某些趋势走向了极端"
      },
      {
        "start": 98.928,
        "end": 102.25800000000001,
        "text": "暴露出了它们潜在的问题"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.25800000000001,
        "end": 106.952,
        "text": "并且接下来的几个世纪里将会生产大量物资"
      },
      {
        "start": 106.952,
        "end": 110.12899999999999,
        "text": "工业技术的进步预示着体力劳动者的解放"
      },
      {
        "start": 110.12899999999999,
        "end": 114.53,
        "text": "取而代之的却是被关押在贫民窟和工厂"
      },
      {
        "start": 114.53,
        "end": 117.858,
        "text": "而与此同时巨头们变得比国王更富有"
      },
      {
        "start": 117.858,
        "end": 122.699,
        "text": "到了19世纪末期 许多人开始担忧这种状况可能成为现实"
      },
      {
        "start": 122.699,
        "end": 126.489,
        "text": "赫伯特·乔治·威尔斯在《时间机器》中 想象上层社会和工人"
      },
      {
        "start": 126.489,
        "end": 129.209,
        "text": "逐步进化成不同的人种"
      },
      {
        "start": 129.209,
        "end": 133.84,
        "text": "同时杰克·伦敦的《铁蹄》 描绘了一个残暴的寡头政治"
      },
      {
        "start": 133.84,
        "end": 137.399,
        "text": "统治着贫穷的劳动阶层"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.399,
        "end": 142.609,
        "text": "新的世纪带来了更多令人既兴奋又恐惧的变化"
      },
      {
        "start": 142.609,
        "end": 146.68,
        "text": "医疗的进步使跨越生物界限成为可能"
      },
      {
        "start": 146.68,
        "end": 149.35,
        "text": "同时大众传媒使领导者和公众之间的"
      },
      {
        "start": 149.35,
        "end": 151.98,
        "text": "及时交流成为可能"
      },
      {
        "start": 151.98,
        "end": 156.159,
        "text": "在阿道司·赫胥黎的《美丽新世界》 每个公民的基因都是被设计过的"
      },
      {
        "start": 156.159,
        "end": 159.91,
        "text": "并根据社会角色接受相应的训练"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.91,
        "end": 162.69,
        "text": "政府宣传和药品让他们保持愉悦"
      },
      {
        "start": 162.69,
        "end": 166.49,
        "text": "显而易见的是 这些人被剥夺了人类最基本的特征"
      },
      {
        "start": 166.49,
        "end": 172.02,
        "text": "但是众所周知的反乌托邦并不是虚幻的"
      },
      {
        "start": 172.02,
        "end": 175.101,
        "text": "就像欧洲经历了空前的工业革命"
      },
      {
        "start": 175.101,
        "end": 177.673,
        "text": "新的政治运动取得了统治权"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.673,
        "end": 181.1,
        "text": "一些承诺要消除所有的社会差别"
      },
      {
        "start": 181.1,
        "end": 184.331,
        "text": "另一些则试图用一些虚构的事物 将人们团结起来"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.331,
        "end": 187.621,
        "text": "导致的结果就是真实世界的反乌托邦"
      },
      {
        "start": 187.621,
        "end": 191.572,
        "text": "人们一生都活在监视下"
      },
      {
        "start": 191.572,
        "end": 196.902,
        "text": "不遵守规则的人将会被无情地处死"
      },
      {
        "start": 196.902,
        "end": 199.812,
        "text": "在那个时代，作家们不仅仅是发现了这些恐惧"
      },
      {
        "start": 199.812,
        "end": 202.231,
        "text": "还经历了它们"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.231,
        "end": 206.782,
        "text": "苏联作家叶夫根尼·萨米尔钦在他的小说《我们》中"
      },
      {
        "start": 206.782,
        "end": 210.652,
        "text": "描述了一个自由意志和个体特征都被消灭了的未来"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.652,
        "end": 214.832,
        "text": "尽管苏联将它列为禁书 它仍鼓舞了一些作家"
      },
      {
        "start": 214.832,
        "end": 219.53300000000002,
        "text": "比如奋斗在共产主义 和反法西斯主义前线的乔治·奥威尔"
      },
      {
        "start": 219.53300000000002,
        "end": 223.362,
        "text": "他的小说《动物农场》直接嘲讽了苏维埃政权"
      },
      {
        "start": 223.362,
        "end": 230.442,
        "text": "经典的《1984》则是对 集权主义、媒体、和语言更广泛的批判"
      },
      {
        "start": 230.442,
        "end": 234.013,
        "text": "并且在美国，辛克莱·刘易斯的《不会发生在这里》"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.013,
        "end": 239.412,
        "text": "想象了民主政体被法西斯取代是多么容易"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.412,
        "end": 241.293,
        "text": "在二战后的几十年里"
      },
      {
        "start": 241.293,
        "end": 243.214,
        "text": "作家们想知道新科技"
      },
      {
        "start": 243.214,
        "end": 246.963,
        "text": "比如原子能，人工智能，太空旅行"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.963,
        "end": 249.553,
        "text": "将对人类的未来产生怎样的影响"
      },
      {
        "start": 249.553,
        "end": 252.422,
        "text": "与广为流传的、赞美科学进步的观点相比"
      },
      {
        "start": 252.422,
        "end": 258.044,
        "text": "反乌托邦科学小说拓展到了电影，喜剧，和游戏"
      },
      {
        "start": 258.044,
        "end": 261.403,
        "text": "机器人们转向反抗他们的制造者"
      },
      {
        "start": 261.403,
        "end": 265.494,
        "text": "与此同时电视上播放着乏味的大众娱乐"
      },
      {
        "start": 265.494,
        "end": 270.153,
        "text": "工人们在太空殖民地辛勤工作"
      },
      {
        "start": 270.153,
        "end": 274.003,
        "text": "它在资源耗尽，人口过多， 犯罪侵扰城市的地球上空"
      },
      {
        "start": 274.003,
        "end": 276.644,
        "text": "然而政治从未消失"
      },
      {
        "start": 276.644,
        "end": 282.064,
        "text": "像《奇爱博士》和《守望者》这样的作品 探究了核战争带来的真正威胁"
      },
      {
        "start": 282.064,
        "end": 284.645,
        "text": "同时《V字仇杀队》和《女仆的故事》"
      },
      {
        "start": 284.645,
        "end": 289.634,
        "text": "告诫了在危机中我们的权利多么容易丧失"
      },
      {
        "start": 289.634,
        "end": 293.294,
        "text": "现今的反乌托邦小说继续反映着当代的焦虑"
      },
      {
        "start": 293.294,
        "end": 294.644,
        "text": "关于不平等"
      },
      {
        "start": 294.644,
        "end": 295.634,
        "text": "气候变化"
      },
      {
        "start": 295.634,
        "end": 296.705,
        "text": "政府权力"
      },
      {
        "start": 296.705,
        "end": 298.914,
        "text": "和全球性的流行病"
      },
      {
        "start": 298.914,
        "end": 301.565,
        "text": "那么他们为什么会想象出如此悲观的世界呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 301.565,
        "end": 304.984,
        "text": "因为在他们心中，反乌托邦的作品都是警示故事"
      },
      {
        "start": 304.984,
        "end": 308.095,
        "text": "不是关于一些特定的政府，或技术"
      },
      {
        "start": 308.095,
        "end": 314.344,
        "text": "而是人类可以被塑造成一个理想的模型这个观点"
      },
      {
        "start": 314.344,
        "end": 317.665,
        "text": "回忆一下你想象中的完美世界"
      },
      {
        "start": 317.665,
        "end": 320.936,
        "text": "你思考过要怎么样才能实现吗？"
      },
      {
        "start": 320.936,
        "end": 324.355,
        "text": "你怎样让人们合作？"
      },
      {
        "start": 324.355,
        "end": 328.065,
        "text": "还有你将如何确保它延续下去"
      },
      {
        "start": 328.065,
        "end": 330.055,
        "text": "现在再想想"
      },
      {
        "start": 330.055,
        "end": 332.507,
        "text": "那个世界依旧看起来完美吗？"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "title": "What is the tragedy of the commons?",
    "youtubeId": "CxC161GvMPc",
    "duration": "",
    "author": "Nicholas Amendolare",
    "theme": "communication",
    "transcript": [
      {
        "start": 1.22,
        "end": 5.767,
        "text": "“大众共同拥有的往往却是最被忽视的。” ——亚里士多德，《政治学》"
      },
      {
        "start": 7.687,
        "end": 11.534,
        "text": "有这样一道思考题， 假设你住在一个小村庄里，"
      },
      {
        "start": 11.534,
        "end": 18.071,
        "text": "村民们依靠在当地鱼塘打渔为食。 你要与另外三位村民共享这个鱼塘。"
      },
      {
        "start": 18.071,
        "end": 23.412,
        "text": "鱼塘自起始时有十二条鱼， 同时鱼也会繁殖。"
      },
      {
        "start": 23.412,
        "end": 27.856,
        "text": "每两条鱼每晚会产出一条小鱼。"
      },
      {
        "start": 27.856,
        "end": 30.424,
        "text": "那么为了最大化你们的食物供给，"
      },
      {
        "start": 30.424,
        "end": 33.466,
        "text": "你们每天可以捕多少条鱼呢？"
      },
      {
        "start": 34.266,
        "end": 36.596,
        "text": "让我们花点时间思考一下。"
      },
      {
        "start": 36.596,
        "end": 39.847,
        "text": "假设大鱼每晚产下的小鱼 在次日就会变为大鱼，"
      },
      {
        "start": 39.847,
        "end": 42.866,
        "text": "鱼塘自起始时也有 足够的条件供鱼类生息，"
      },
      {
        "start": 42.866,
        "end": 46.136,
        "text": "同时忽略鱼的性别， 以及类似的影响因素。"
      },
      {
        "start": 46.726,
        "end": 50.556,
        "text": "答案是一条， 而且不仅仅是你只能打一条鱼。"
      },
      {
        "start": 50.556,
        "end": 53.707,
        "text": "最大化每位村民 食物供给的方法就是，"
      },
      {
        "start": 53.707,
        "end": 57.807,
        "text": "每位渔民每天只能捕一条鱼。"
      },
      {
        "start": 58.277,
        "end": 60.108,
        "text": "算法是这样的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 60.108,
        "end": 64.734,
        "text": "如果每位村民每天打一条鱼， 当晚鱼塘内会剩下八条鱼。"
      },
      {
        "start": 64.734,
        "end": 67.117,
        "text": "每两条鱼会繁殖出一条小鱼，"
      },
      {
        "start": 67.117,
        "end": 71.577,
        "text": "于是次日，鱼塘内鱼的 数量又会恢复到十二条。"
      },
      {
        "start": 72.187,
        "end": 77.499,
        "text": "如果有任何一位多捕了一条， 鱼塘内的繁殖对数量就会减少，"
      },
      {
        "start": 77.499,
        "end": 81.732,
        "text": "鱼的数量也就无法恢复， 无法维持正常供给。"
      },
      {
        "start": 82.408,
        "end": 85.149,
        "text": "最终鱼塘里也就不再有鱼了，"
      },
      {
        "start": 85.149,
        "end": 88.699,
        "text": "而村民们只能挨饿。"
      },
      {
        "start": 88.699,
        "end": 91.85900000000001,
        "text": "这个鱼塘引发的问题， 只是这类问题的一个示例，"
      },
      {
        "start": 91.85900000000001,
        "end": 94.937,
        "text": "即所谓的“公用品悲剧”。"
      },
      {
        "start": 94.937,
        "end": 97.50800000000001,
        "text": "这个现象首次于1833年"
      },
      {
        "start": 97.50800000000001,
        "end": 102.17699999999999,
        "text": "由威廉·福斯特·洛伊提出， 发布在一本小手册上，"
      },
      {
        "start": 102.17699999999999,
        "end": 104.749,
        "text": "以此讨论了在村庄的公共区域内"
      },
      {
        "start": 104.749,
        "end": 107.188,
        "text": "过度放牧的现象。"
      },
      {
        "start": 107.788,
        "end": 112.628,
        "text": "一百多年后，经济学家 加勒特·哈丁再次提出了这个概念，"
      },
      {
        "start": 112.628,
        "end": 115.358,
        "text": "用来描述当许多人 共享一种有限的资源时"
      },
      {
        "start": 115.358,
        "end": 118.2,
        "text": "会发生什么，"
      },
      {
        "start": 118.2,
        "end": 119.689,
        "text": "比如共用牧场、"
      },
      {
        "start": 119.689,
        "end": 120.792,
        "text": "鱼塘、"
      },
      {
        "start": 120.792,
        "end": 121.889,
        "text": "生活空间、"
      },
      {
        "start": 121.889,
        "end": 123.94,
        "text": "甚至是清新的空气。"
      },
      {
        "start": 123.94,
        "end": 128.039,
        "text": "哈丁认为造成这些 公共资源短缺的现象"
      },
      {
        "start": 128.039,
        "end": 130.249,
        "text": "是由于人们盲目追求短期自我利益，"
      },
      {
        "start": 130.249,
        "end": 132.74099999999999,
        "text": "而这最终只会有害于所有人，"
      },
      {
        "start": 132.74099999999999,
        "end": 134.14,
        "text": "导致过度放牧、"
      },
      {
        "start": 134.14,
        "end": 135.179,
        "text": "过度捕鱼、"
      },
      {
        "start": 135.179,
        "end": 136.489,
        "text": "人口过剩、"
      },
      {
        "start": 136.489,
        "end": 137.56,
        "text": "大气污染"
      },
      {
        "start": 137.56,
        "end": 140.76,
        "text": "以及其他社会环境问题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 140.76,
        "end": 143.27,
        "text": "“公用品悲剧“的主要特点是，"
      },
      {
        "start": 143.27,
        "end": 148.6,
        "text": "它为人们提供了让自己获益的机会，"
      },
      {
        "start": 148.6,
        "end": 153.315,
        "text": "同时却对大众造成负面影响。"
      },
      {
        "start": 153.872,
        "end": 157.107,
        "text": "想要进一步了解它的含义， 让我们回到之前的鱼塘思考题。"
      },
      {
        "start": 157.107,
        "end": 159.691,
        "text": "每位渔民都有理由"
      },
      {
        "start": 159.691,
        "end": 162.952,
        "text": "为自己捕捞尽可能多的鱼。"
      },
      {
        "start": 162.952,
        "end": 165.571,
        "text": "然而同时鱼塘内 鱼的繁殖量下降"
      },
      {
        "start": 165.571,
        "end": 168.332,
        "text": "是需要所有村民一起承受的。"
      },
      {
        "start": 168.762,
        "end": 171.453,
        "text": "急于避免自己的捕鱼量比邻居少，"
      },
      {
        "start": 171.453,
        "end": 176.403,
        "text": "渔民会为了个人利益 尽可能地多捕一条鱼，"
      },
      {
        "start": 176.403,
        "end": 177.242,
        "text": "或者两条，"
      },
      {
        "start": 177.242,
        "end": 178.643,
        "text": "或者三条。"
      },
      {
        "start": 178.643,
        "end": 182.591,
        "text": "不幸的是，每位渔民都是这样想的，"
      },
      {
        "start": 182.591,
        "end": 184.043,
        "text": "而这就是悲剧的开始。"
      },
      {
        "start": 184.043,
        "end": 190.419,
        "text": "自身短期的利益往往 与群体长期利益向冲突。"
      },
      {
        "start": 190.419,
        "end": 193.303,
        "text": "以上只是一个简单的例子， 然而公用品悲剧"
      },
      {
        "start": 193.303,
        "end": 197.864,
        "text": "也发生在现实生活中 更复杂的情形里。"
      },
      {
        "start": 197.864,
        "end": 202.78300000000002,
        "text": "过多使用抗生素可以增长 畜牧生产的短期收益"
      },
      {
        "start": 202.78300000000002,
        "end": 205.023,
        "text": "并治疗一些人类普遍的疾病，"
      },
      {
        "start": 205.023,
        "end": 210.003,
        "text": "但同时也会引发细菌的抗药性，"
      },
      {
        "start": 210.003,
        "end": 212.84300000000002,
        "text": "从而对整个人口系统造成威胁。"
      },
      {
        "start": 212.84300000000002,
        "end": 216.466,
        "text": "依靠燃煤发电可以为人们 提供廉价的电力"
      },
      {
        "start": 216.466,
        "end": 218.563,
        "text": "并使发电厂获利。"
      },
      {
        "start": 218.563,
        "end": 221.225,
        "text": "这些诚然可以为当地发展 提供短期的利益，"
      },
      {
        "start": 221.225,
        "end": 226.985,
        "text": "但采矿和燃煤造成的污染 则会遍布整个大气层，"
      },
      {
        "start": 226.985,
        "end": 229.96800000000002,
        "text": "在几千年内都无法消失。"
      },
      {
        "start": 229.96800000000002,
        "end": 232.108,
        "text": "这样的例子举不胜举。"
      },
      {
        "start": 232.108,
        "end": 233.024,
        "text": "乱扔垃圾、"
      },
      {
        "start": 233.024,
        "end": 234.188,
        "text": "水资源短缺、"
      },
      {
        "start": 234.188,
        "end": 235.495,
        "text": "砍伐森林、"
      },
      {
        "start": 235.495,
        "end": 236.728,
        "text": "交通堵塞，"
      },
      {
        "start": 236.728,
        "end": 239.541,
        "text": "甚至是购买瓶装水。"
      },
      {
        "start": 239.541,
        "end": 245.295,
        "text": "然而人类文明已经证明了 它可以做一些卓尔不群的事。"
      },
      {
        "start": 245.295,
        "end": 246.785,
        "text": "我们起草社会契约、"
      },
      {
        "start": 246.785,
        "end": 248.595,
        "text": "我们制定公用协定、"
      },
      {
        "start": 248.595,
        "end": 250.14600000000002,
        "text": "我们选择政府党派、"
      },
      {
        "start": 250.14600000000002,
        "end": 251.995,
        "text": "我们通过法律议案。"
      },
      {
        "start": 251.995,
        "end": 257.616,
        "text": "这都是为了拯救因个人行为 而受损的集体利益。"
      },
      {
        "start": 257.616,
        "end": 262.186,
        "text": "这并不是简单的事， 而我们也没有经常做对。"
      },
      {
        "start": 262.186,
        "end": 266.995,
        "text": "但当人类怀有最好的意愿时， 我们总是可以解决这些问题，"
      },
      {
        "start": 266.995,
        "end": 271.337,
        "text": "如果我们能铭记哈丁的这个理论， 就能继续做正确的决定。"
      },
      {
        "start": 271.337,
        "end": 273.866,
        "text": "当公用品的利益出现时，"
      },
      {
        "start": 273.866,
        "end": 277.266,
        "text": "对大家都有益的， 才是对每个人有益的。"
      }
    ]
  }
